const CARDS = [{"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "What is the Caprini score and what organization formally recommends its use for plastic surgery patients?", "answer": "The 2005 Caprini score is a widely validated VTE risk stratification tool that creates an aggregate risk score based on ~40 individual risk factors. It is formally recommended by the American Society of Plastic Surgeons (ASPS) and the American College of Chest Physicians (ACCP).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "For plastic surgery inpatients, what is the approximate range of VTE risk identified by the Caprini score?", "answer": "The Caprini score identifies approximately a 20-fold variation in VTE risk among plastic surgery inpatients, ranging from 0.3% to 8.5%.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "A patient on warfarin for atrial fibrillation needs elective plastic surgery. Based on Level I evidence from the BRIDGE trial, describe the perioperative anticoagulation management.", "answer": "Warfarin should be stopped 5 days prior to the procedure and re-initiated 24 hours after surgery (or at surgeon discretion). Bridging therapy with LMWH should NOT be routinely performed, as it did not significantly reduce arterial thromboembolism (0.3% vs 0.4%) but did increase major bleeding (3.2% vs 1.3%).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "How long before and after surgery should oral contraceptives or hormone replacement therapy be discontinued to reduce VTE risk?", "answer": "3 weeks before and 3 weeks after surgery to allow VTE risk to return to normal levels. However, patients must be counseled about unintended consequences (menstrual irregularity, unintended pregnancy, menopausal symptoms).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "Describe the mechanism by which sequential compression devices (SCDs) reduce VTE risk, including both local and systemic effects.", "answer": "Locally, SCDs recapitulate the calf muscle pump and physically propel blood out of the lower extremities, reducing venous stasis. Systemically, they augment head-to-toe fibrinolysis through increased fibrinolytic tPA (tissue plasminogen activator) and decreased PAI-1 (plasminogen activator inhibitor-1) levels.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "At what Caprini score threshold do plastic surgery inpatients benefit from postoperative enoxaparin prophylaxis? What are the specific VTE risk reductions?", "answer": "Caprini score >= 7. Per the VTEPS study: Caprini >8 patients had 60-day VTE decrease from 8.5% to 4.1%; Caprini 7-8 patients decreased from 2.6% to 1.2%. Routine anticoagulation carries a 0.7% increased risk for re-operative hematoma.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "What Level I evidence supports weight-based dosing of enoxaparin for VTE prophylaxis, and what is the recommended dose?", "answer": "The FIVE (Fixed or Variable Enoxaparin) trial showed that weight-based dosing at 0.5 mg/kg BID optimizes pharmacokinetics compared to one-size-fits-all dosing.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "A patient is traveling by air 1 week after cosmetic surgery. What does the evidence say about DVT risk during long flights, and what is recommended?", "answer": "Duplex ultrasound studies show 4.5% of asymptomatic travelers develop DVT during trans-Pacific flights (Coach Class Syndrome). Level I evidence shows 20-30 mmHg compression stockings decrease asymptomatic DVT risk from 4.5% to 0.25%.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "Why does abdominal wall plication increase DVT risk? Include the specific pressure changes.", "answer": "Plication increases intra-abdominal pressure (2-6 mmHg in abdominoplasty, 4-8 mmHg in DIEP). This increased pressure is transmitted to the inferior vena cava, causing increased common femoral vein pressure, resulting in bilateral lower extremity venous stasis and dilation.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "Compare the VTE risk with abdominoplasty vs the overall aesthetics population.", "answer": "Abdominoplasty patients have a VTE rate of ~0.2% vs ~0.09% in the overall aesthetics population - more than double the baseline risk, likely due to plication, longer operative times, and concurrent procedures.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "What is the relationship between OR time and VTE risk?", "answer": "A linear relationship exists between time spent in the operating room and risk for VTE. Similarly, combined procedures carry increased VTE risk compared to single procedures.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Malignant hyperthermia awareness", "question": "What is malignant hyperthermia (MH), what triggers it, and what are the initial signs vs late signs?", "answer": "MH is an autosomal dominant disorder causing a life-threatening reaction to succinylcholine and volatile anesthetics, resulting in uncontrolled skeletal muscle metabolism. Initial signs: increased end-tidal CO2, tachycardia, and/or muscle rigidity. Increased body temperature is a LATE sign. Treatment: IV dantrolene and removal of the offending agent, plus cardiovascular support.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Fire risk in OR", "question": "What three factors combine to create the fire triad in the operating room? Give examples of each.", "answer": "The fire triad (per AORN) consists of: (1) Ignition sources: electrocautery, laser beams, frayed cords; (2) Fuel sources: draping material, hair, clothes, mattresses, foam padding, alcohol-based skin prep; (3) Oxidizers: oxygen delivered via nasal cannula or open masks that builds up underneath drapes.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Fire risk in OR", "question": "What strategies reduce fire risk in the operating room?", "answer": "Set audible activation tones for electrocautery units, keep electrocautery in a holster, and avoid grounding pad failure (from fluid on pad, dryness of adhesive gel, or inappropriate location over metal, tattoos, or bony prominence).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Pressure injury prevention in long cases", "question": "What temperature defines intraoperative hypothermia, and what are its consequences?", "answer": "Hypothermia = core body temperature below 36 degrees C (98.6 F). It is correlated with increased risk of postoperative surgical site infection and platelet dysfunction. Regional and general anesthesia interfere with homeostatic temperature maintenance, requiring active warming.", "notes": "Closest match; content relates to intraoperative temperature management"}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Local anesthetic toxicity", "question": "What is the standard acceptable lidocaine dose, and how does this differ in the tumescent liposuction setting?", "answer": "Standard: 5-7 mg/kg. For liposuction with tumescent technique (paired with epinephrine): up to 35 mg/kg. The higher dose is safe because fat is poorly vascularized, slowing absorption, and epinephrine further vasoconstricts.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Local anesthetic toxicity", "question": "Describe the progression of lidocaine toxicity symptoms by plasma level.", "answer": "3-6 mcg/mL: light-headedness, tinnitus, slurred speech, metallic taste, lip/tongue numbness. Above 10 mcg/mL: CNS depression. Above 20 mcg/mL: respiratory depression and cardiac arrest.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Local anesthetic toxicity", "question": "When performing multi-site liposuction, why does the timing of peak plasma lidocaine levels matter?", "answer": "In fat (poorly vascularized), plasma lidocaine peaks ~12 hours after infiltration with epinephrine. In more vascular areas like the head and neck, levels peak ~6 hours after infiltration. This difference is critical for multi-site procedures to avoid toxicity.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Body contouring", "subtopic": "Gluteal fat grafting safety awareness", "question": "What is the mortality rate associated with gluteal fat grafting, and what is the mechanism of death?", "answer": "Published mortality rates: 1:2,351 to 1:6,241, the highest of any aesthetic procedure. 3% of surgeons report a patient death from fat embolism. Mechanism: grafted fat placed intravascularly travels through superior/inferior gluteal veins to iliac vein to central circulation, causing pulmonary fat embolism.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Body contouring", "subtopic": "Gluteal fat grafting safety awareness", "question": "What are the current safety guidelines for gluteal fat grafting to minimize fat embolism risk?", "answer": "Subcutaneous fat injection ONLY (avoid intramuscular), use a constantly moving single-hole cannula 4.1 mm or larger diameter, cannula trajectory should avoid the muscle, and avoid excessively high graft fill pressures.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Body contouring", "subtopic": "Liposuction", "question": "What defines large-volume liposuction and what are the ASPS recommendations for its management?", "answer": "Large-volume liposuction = removal of more than 5,000 mL of aspirate in a single setting. ASPS recommends it be performed only in a hospital or accredited/licensed facility, with postoperative admission to monitor for dehydration and fluid overload as fluid transitions from extra- to intravascular space.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "General postop issues", "subtopic": "Pain control", "question": "List the components of multimodal analgesia in plastic surgery and their key benefits.", "answer": "(1) NSAIDs: reduce opioid use by 40%, given around the clock; (2) Acetaminophen: safe profile, up to 4000 mg/day (1000 mg q6h), can start night before surgery; (3) Gabapentin: reduces opioid use by 35%, decreases pain/nausea (avoid in elderly); (4) Local anesthetics: lidocaine/bupivacaine for 8-12h, liposomal bupivacaine for 72+ hours; (5) Dexamethasone: single 8 mg IV dose reduces opioid use and PONV (avoid in poorly controlled diabetes).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "General postop issues", "subtopic": "Pain control", "question": "Why should patients receiving scheduled acetaminophen NOT also receive combination narcotics (e.g., Percocet)?", "answer": "To avoid acetaminophen overdose, as combination narcotics contain acetaminophen. If a patient is already receiving scheduled acetaminophen (up to 4000 mg/day), adding combination narcotics could exceed safe hepatotoxic limits.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Patient optimization before reconstruction", "question": "Describe the ASA physical status classification system (classes I-VI) and its relevance to outpatient plastic surgery.", "answer": "ASA I: Normal healthy patient. ASA II: Mild systemic disease (e.g., controlled HTN). ASA III: Severe systemic disease. ASA IV: Severe systemic disease, constant threat to life. ASA V: Moribund, not expected to survive without surgery. ASA VI: Brain-dead for organ donation. Foley et al. found an 89-fold increase in mortality in ASA IV vs I patients in ambulatory surgery.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "Is routine anticoagulation recommended for aesthetic/ambulatory plastic surgery patients? What does the evidence show?", "answer": "No. Meta-analysis showed an unfavorable risk-benefit relationship for routine anticoagulation of abdominoplasty patients with no significant VTE risk reduction. While one study showed benefit with fondaparinux in body contouring, multiple other studies using similar regimens did not confirm this. Routine anticoagulation of the aesthetic population is not advisable.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "DVT prophylaxis", "question": "What type of anesthesia is protective against postoperative VTE, and what is the evidence?", "answer": "Regional anesthesia, MAC, or local anesthesia rather than general anesthesia. Meta-analyses show that avoiding general anesthesia is protective against postoperative VTE. General anesthesia is a recognized independent risk factor for VTE.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Safety", "subtopic": "Time-out and site marking", "question": "What is the evidence for surgical safety checklists, and what did the WHO Surgical Safety Checklist demonstrate?", "answer": "In simulations, checklists produce higher adherence to gold-standard care. In low-income countries, the WHO Surgical Safety Checklist decreased overall and infection-specific complication rates. In childbirth settings, checklist use increased compliance with essential practices.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "What are the clinical consequences of inadequate postoperative pain control across organ systems?", "answer": "Cardiovascular: increased cardiac work, ischemia, infarction. Pulmonary: splinting, decreased ambulation/vital capacity, atelectasis, hypoventilation, pneumonia. GI: reduced motility, ileus, nausea/vomiting. Hematologic: decreased ambulation, venostasis, DVT risk. Immunologic: altered immune response, increased wound infections. Neurologic: persistent chronic postoperative pain. Psychological: anxiety, fear, depression, poor satisfaction.", "notes": "Closest match; content is about pain management consequences"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "Compare acetaminophen, NSAIDs, and COX-2 inhibitors in terms of mechanism, platelet effects, and key contraindications.", "answer": "Acetaminophen: inhibits COX-1/2 centrally and peripherally, NO significant platelet effects, hepatotoxicity risk at high doses. NSAIDs: inhibit COX-1 and COX-2, impair platelet function/hemostasis, risk of GI bleeding, renal insufficiency (especially with hypovolemia), cardiovascular risk (diclofenac highest, naproxen lowest). COX-2 inhibitors: selective COX-2 inhibition, negligible platelet effect, lower GI bleeding risk, but increased thromboembolic/cardiovascular risk (avoid in ischemic heart disease). Celecoxib contraindicated in sulfa allergy.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Maximum dosing concepts", "question": "What is the maximum daily dose of acetaminophen in adults without hepatic disease, and what formulations are available?", "answer": "Maximum 4 grams (4000 mg) per day in adults without hepatic or renal disease. Available in oral, rectal, and IV formulations. Dose reduction recommended in patients with liver insufficiency.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "What is ketamine's mechanism of action, and what makes it uniquely favorable for hemodynamically unstable patients?", "answer": "Ketamine is a noncompetitive NMDA-receptor antagonist. It preserves respiratory drive, maintains hemodynamic stability, and has sympathomimetic effects (catecholamine release, inhibition of noradrenaline reuptake) leading to increased heart rate, stroke volume, and mean arterial pressure. It also preserves upper airway muscle tone, pharyngeal, and laryngeal reflexes. At subanesthetic doses (0.1 mg/kg/h), it reduces opioid requirements. Half-life: 180 minutes.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "What are the dose-dependent side effects of ketamine, and at what doses are they most commonly seen?", "answer": "Neuropsychiatric effects include dysphoria, hallucinations, vivid unpleasant dreams, and catatonia/psychoses. These are dose-dependent and most common at anesthetic doses (1-5 mg/kg). At subanesthetic doses (0.1 mg/kg/h), these effects are considerably less common and generally well tolerated.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "What is the mechanism of gabapentinoids, and what is the FDA Black Box warning regarding their use?", "answer": "Gabapentin and pregabalin are GABA analogues that bind voltage-gated calcium channels on cortical and dorsal horn neurons, attenuating release of glutamate, norepinephrine, and substance P. They also activate descending inhibitory noradrenergic pathways. The FDA issued a Black Box warning (Dec 2019): when combined with other CNS depressants (benzodiazepines, opioids), respiratory depression can occur, especially in elderly, COPD patients, and those on chronic opioids.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Maximum dosing concepts", "question": "Fill in the blank: For subcutaneous infiltration, the maximum dose of lidocaine with epinephrine is ___ mg/kg, bupivacaine with epinephrine is ___ mg/kg, and ropivacaine with epinephrine is ___ mg/kg.", "answer": "Lidocaine with epi: 5-7 mg/kg. Bupivacaine with epi: 2-3 mg/kg. Ropivacaine with epi: 2-3 mg/kg.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Tumescent anesthesia basics", "question": "Describe Klein's Solution for tumescent anesthesia and its components.", "answer": "500 mg lidocaine + 1 mg epinephrine + 12.5 mEq sodium bicarbonate in 1000 mL of normal saline. Epinephrine prolongs analgesia, reduces bleeding, and reduces absorption of local anesthetic.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Tumescent anesthesia basics", "question": "What is the maximal hemostatic effect timing of epinephrine in tumescent analgesia, and what dosing concerns exist?", "answer": "Maximal hemostatic effects occur at 25 minutes after administration (not 7-10 minutes as commonly believed), with minimal improvement after 15 minutes. Epinephrine has a 2-3 minute half-life. An upper limit of 10 mcg/kg has been suggested. Under general anesthesia with volatile agents, arrhythmias can develop in adults with as little as 2-3 mcg/kg. Avoid in pheochromocytoma, hyperthyroidism, severe HTN, cardiac disease, or PVD.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Recognition of local anesthetic systemic toxicity", "question": "A patient develops cardiac arrest from local anesthetic toxicity during liposuction. Walk through the step-by-step management.", "answer": "(1) Stop infusion of fluids with local anesthetic; (2) Assure airway management and oxygenation; (3) Call for help; (4) Prepare for seizure suppression with benzodiazepines; (5) Administer 20% Intralipid 1.5 mL/kg (may repeat up to 10 mL/kg), then infuse 0.25 mL/kg/h if cardiac effects persist; (6) Manage arrhythmias per ACLS but do NOT use lidocaine, reduce epinephrine to 1 mcg/kg; (7) For isolated seizures: benzodiazepines or propofol (propofol NOT as lipid substitute for cardiac arrest).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Tumescent anesthesia basics", "question": "Why is bupivacaine generally not recommended for tumescent anesthesia, and which organizations advise against it?", "answer": "Both the American Society of Plastic Surgeons (ASPS) and American Academy of Dermatology (AAD) in 2013 guidelines advise against use of bupivacaine for tumescent anesthesia. While it has been used in combination with lidocaine without reported complications, there is little guidance on upper limits of dosing when used in combination, creating safety concerns.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Tumescent anesthesia basics", "question": "List at least 8 plastic surgery procedures where tumescent analgesia can be used.", "answer": "Liposuction, subcutaneous mass excision/scar revisions, excisional body contouring (abdominoplasty, body lifts, brachioplasty, thigh lifts), breast augmentation/reduction/mastopexy/gynecomastia, mastectomy, burn excision and skin grafting, face/neck lifts, hair grafting, skin procedures (dermabrasion, laser resurfacing), and lymph node dissections.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Tumescent anesthesia basics", "question": "What electrolyte abnormalities can occur with large-volume tumescent infiltration during liposuction?", "answer": "Mild hyponatremia and hypokalemia may occur in large-volume liposuction. Rarely clinically significant but must be monitored. Additionally, large volumes of room temperature tumescent fluid can lower body temperature; fluid should be warmed to 37 degrees C in cases prone to hypothermia.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "What is liposomal bupivacaine (Exparel), and what are its pharmacologic properties?", "answer": "Liposomal bupivacaine provides sustained delivery via a vesicular network that opens successively over time. 3% of bupivacaine is initially free at injection for immediate effect; the remainder is in vesicles for gradual delivery. FDA approved in 2011 for wound infiltration and 2018 for interscalene nerve block. Can provide 72+ hours of pain relief, though well-designed plastic surgery studies have not consistently found benefit over properly dosed traditional local anesthetics.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "List 9 techniques for minimizing pain during injection of local anesthesia with sharp needles.", "answer": "(1) Buffer lidocaine/epi with 8.4% sodium bicarbonate; (2) Warm the local anesthetic; (3) Distract patient or area (pinch/pressure near injection); (4) Use smaller 27- or 30-gauge needles; (5) Stabilize syringe with both hands; (6) Inject 0.5 mL perpendicularly subdermally, pause until patient reports no needle pain; (7) Inject 2 mL before moving needle, then advance slowly with 1 cm anesthetic ahead of needle; (8) Reinsert within 1 cm of blanched areas; (9) Have patients provide feedback and pain scores during injection.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "WALANT principles", "question": "What does WALANT stand for and in what procedures has wide-awake local anesthesia been proven effective?", "answer": "Wide-Awake Local Anesthesia No Tourniquet. It has been proven effective in hand surgery, cosmetic surgery, facial skin cancer reconstruction, and adult cleft lip repair, among others. The approach uses local anesthesia without sedation.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "Describe the PEC 1 and PEC 2 nerve blocks: what nerves do they target, what is the typical anesthetic, and when are they used?", "answer": "PEC 1: targets medial and lateral pectoral nerves (from brachial plexus, C5-T1) as they travel between pec major and minor. Provides analgesia for pectoralis muscles. Typical: 10 mL 0.5% bupivacaine. PEC 2: targets intercostal nerves (1-7) as they exit serratus anterior. Provides analgesia for overlying skin and breast tissue. Typical: 20 mL 0.2% bupivacaine. Both performed together with ultrasound guidance for breast surgery.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "Describe the transversus abdominis plane (TAP) block: where is the local anesthetic placed, what nerves are targeted, and what are the anatomic boundaries of the injection site?", "answer": "Local anesthetic is placed in the fascial plane between the transversus abdominis and internal oblique muscles. Targets T10-L1 terminal branches of intercostal nerves. Injection site is within the lumbar triangle of Petit (boundaries: costal margin superiorly, iliac crest inferiorly, external oblique anteriorly, latissimus dorsi posteriorly). Subcostal approach targets T7-9. Rare complications: hematoma and intraperitoneal injection with organ injury.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "What is an erector spinae block (ESP), how does it work, and how does it compare to PEC blocks for breast surgery?", "answer": "ESP is placed just inferior to the erector spinae muscle overlying the transverse process. The mechanism is debated - it may block dorsal root nerves or enter the paravertebral space. Provides analgesia along the lateral thoracic or abdominal wall. Used for thoracic, breast, and abdominal surgery. For breast surgery, PEC blocks appear to have an advantage over ESP.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "Compare paravertebral blocks and epidural anesthesia: anatomy, advantages, and complications.", "answer": "Paravertebral: injection into triangular paravertebral space (bordered by parietal pleura anteriorly, vertebral column medially, superior costotransverse ligament posteriorly). Provides ipsilateral dermatomal analgesia while avoiding CNS complications. Main risk: pneumothorax (<1%). Epidural: injection outside subarachnoid space with catheter for continuous infusion. Allows multilevel coverage. Complications: hypotension (up to 33%), bradycardia, spinal headaches, epidural abscess/hematoma, respiratory compromise if intercostal/abdominal muscles blocked.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "General postop issues", "subtopic": "Pain control", "question": "What special considerations apply to opioid management in patients with obstructive sleep apnea (OSA)?", "answer": "OSA patients have increased soft tissue in pharynx/larynx leading to upper airway obstruction. Opioids exacerbate this via: dose-dependent decrease in genioglossus tone, sedative effects promoting airway closure, altered arousal thresholds, and reduced postoperative lung volumes. Recommendations: reduce opioid dose by half or increase dosing interval, continuous pulse oximetry, prolonged PACU observation, early postoperative positive airway pressure therapy, and multimodal non-opioid alternatives.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "General postop issues", "subtopic": "Pain control", "question": "What percentage of hand surgery patients continued opioid use at 90-120 days postoperatively?", "answer": "8-13% of hand surgery patients continued to use opioids at 90-120 days, highlighting the risk of acute postoperative opioid prescriptions leading to chronic use.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "Compare morphine, fentanyl, and hydromorphone: equipotent IV doses, durations, and key side effects.", "answer": "Morphine: 0.1 mg/kg IV, duration 3-4h, oral bioavailability 20-40% (give 3-5x IV dose orally). Causes histamine release/vasodilation; avoid in asthmatics/circulatory compromise. Fentanyl: 0.001 mg/kg IV, duration 0.5-1h. Vagotonic (can cause bradycardia), minimal hemodynamic alterations, but can cause chest wall rigidity from glottic closure. Hydromorphone: 0.01-0.02 mg/kg IV, duration 3-4h, oral bioavailability 50-70%. No histamine release; used when morphine produces too many side effects.", "notes": "Closest match; opioid pharmacology relevant to anesthesia/pain management"}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "Why is codeine no longer recommended, and what is the specific FDA warning?", "answer": "Codeine is a prodrug that must be converted by CYP2D6 to morphine for analgesia. Ultra-rapid metabolizers produce excessive morphine (dangerous), while slow metabolizers get no analgesia. It has a Black Box warning and is contraindicated in pediatric tonsillectomy patients.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "What is the current recommendation for managing buprenorphine perioperatively?", "answer": "Previous guidelines suggested tapering buprenorphine before surgery, but current evidence suggests this can lead to harm. The home dose should be CONTINUED perioperatively, and may need to be increased postoperatively. Standard opioid regimens will NOT be effective because buprenorphine tightly binds opioid receptors but elicits low activity. Multimodal therapy including regional anesthesia is often required. Discussion with anesthesiologist and prescribing physician is essential.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local anesthesia", "subtopic": "Lidocaine, bupivacaine, epinephrine", "question": "What advantage does epidural anesthesia offer specifically for microvascular lower extremity reconstruction?", "answer": "The sympathectomy from epidural anesthesia may enhance blood flow to the extremity, which is beneficial for microvascular flap perfusion. Additionally, thoracic epidurals may spare motor nerves to the lower extremities and micturition pathways, allowing early ambulation and avoidance of prolonged urinary catheter use.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Surgical margins conceptually", "question": "Define R0, R1, and R2 resections in cancer surgery.", "answer": "R0: tumor excision with no evidence of tumor cells (gross or microscopic) at any resection margin on pathological examination. R1: positive microscopic margins. R2: positive macroscopic margins.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Surgical margins conceptually", "question": "What is the approximate size at which a tumor first becomes clinically detectable, and what does this imply about the timeline for evaluation?", "answer": "Tumors are generally not detectable until they reach approximately 1 cm in diameter (~10^9 cells). Depending on doubling time (2-200 days), a tumor may be present for years before becoming palpable. This affords the oncologic team sufficient time to evaluate newly diagnosed patients thoroughly without rushing therapy.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "TNM staging awareness", "question": "Describe the TNM staging system: what does each component represent?", "answer": "T (Tumor): extent of primary tumor measured by size, depth of invasion, or degree of anatomic involvement. N (Node): involvement of lymph nodes, including number of affected nodes or node size. M (Metastasis): involvement of distant organs. Various TNM combinations are aggregated into stage groups (I-IV) with different treatment tailored for each stage.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Compare Clark's and Breslow's classification systems for melanoma.", "answer": "Clark's morphologic classification categorizes melanoma into: lentigo maligna, superficial spreading, nodular, acral, and desmoplastic variants, and histologically by level of invasion into papillary/reticular dermis and subcutaneous fat (subjective, poor inter-rater reliability). Breslow's system objectively quantitates tumor thickness by measurement with a micrometer (more reproducible and clinically relevant for prognosis).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Sentinel lymph node biopsy concepts", "question": "Describe the sentinel lymph node concept: how is it performed, what are the false-negative rates, and what are the advantages over elective lymph node dissection?", "answer": "After injection of radioactive colloid or blue dye into the tumor, the first (sentinel) node draining the basin is excised and examined. The sentinel node status is representative of the entire regional nodal chain. False-negative rates: 0-11%. Advantages: minimizes morbidity (lymphedema rates decreased to 5% vs 35% for complete lymphadenectomy), allows more thorough histologic evaluation of a single node, and avoids unnecessary extensive dissections.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Surgical margins conceptually", "question": "Why do tumors sometimes recur locally despite negative margins on pathologic evaluation?", "answer": "Microscopic tumor deposits may not be detected on routine histology. Studies show cancer cells can be successfully grown in vitro from specimens with negative routine histology. Additionally, if malignant cells represent less than 0.1% of a specimen, identification is challenging unless immunohistochemistry or molecular techniques (PCR) are used. This justifies multimodality treatment even with negative margins.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "BCC/SCC high-risk features", "question": "Describe Lund's classification for basal cell carcinoma and its prognostic significance.", "answer": "Based on descriptive/morphologic features: nodular (well-defined margins), ulcerative, morphea, and sclerosing patterns (indistinct margins). The presence of morphea or sclerosing features is associated with a more aggressive and problematic course.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Pathology", "subtopic": "Breast cancer receptor status at a basic level: ER/PR/HER2 awareness", "question": "What is triple-negative breast cancer and why is it clinically significant?", "answer": "Triple-negative breast cancer is absent for ER (estrogen receptor), PR (progesterone receptor), and HER2 receptors. It has a reproducible and highly specific molecular signature that is clinically aggressive. It lacks targets for hormonal therapy or HER2-directed therapy, making treatment more challenging.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What is neoadjuvant therapy, and how does it affect reconstructive planning?", "answer": "Neoadjuvant therapy = chemotherapy and/or radiation administered BEFORE tumor excision. Goals: shrink unresectable tumors to make them resectable, or decrease magnitude of ablation needed for negative margins. Impact on reconstruction: Mehrara et al. showed neoadjuvant chemo is an independent risk factor for postoperative complications in microvascular breast reconstruction, with increased wound complications if surgery is performed less than 6 weeks after completion of chemotherapy.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "Compare the advantages and disadvantages of neoadjuvant vs adjuvant therapy.", "answer": "Neoadjuvant advantages: can downstage tumors, convert unresectable to resectable, facilitate organ preservation (e.g., sphincter preservation in rectal cancer, breast conservation), response predicts outcome and guides postop chemo. Disadvantages: disease progression before surgery, increased surgical complications from chemoradiation side effects. Adjuvant advantages: decreases locoregional recurrence and systemic disease by treating microscopic deposits after surgery. Both: all attempts should be made for negative margins at surgery regardless.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Radiation effects on wound healing", "question": "Why is radiation most effective at tumor periphery and least effective at the center?", "answer": "Radiation produces free radicals from water, and oxygen increases the half-life of reactive radical species, making radiation most effective in oxygen-rich environments. The periphery of tumors is well-oxygenated, while the avascular center of necrotic tumor masses has poor oxygen tension, making radiation least effective there.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Radiation effects on wound healing", "question": "What is the mechanism by which radiation causes increased wound healing complications?", "answer": "While traditionally thought to be related to harmful effects on local blood supply, the exact cause remains unknown. Recent studies suggest radiation injury causes depletion of local tissue stem cells, and that restitution with stem cell injections can improve tissue healing. Radiation is also an independent risk factor for post-surgical lymphedema and secondary skin malignancies.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Head and neck cancer reconstruction", "subtopic": "Radiation effects on wound healing", "question": "Explain the principle of fractionated radiation therapy and the concept of sublethal damage.", "answer": "Ionizing radiation causes DNA strand breaks. Single-strand breaks are efficiently repaired by cells, but double-strand breaks are less easily handled. When the interval between doses is increased, more cells can repair DNA breaks (sublethal damage). Radiation is therefore delivered in fractionated daily doses (1.8-2.5 Gy) because normal cells have greater ability to repair sublethal damage between fractions than tumor cells.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Surgical margins conceptually", "question": "Compare excisional biopsy, incisional biopsy, core-needle biopsy (CNB), and fine-needle aspiration (FNA).", "answer": "Excisional: removes entire tumor mass with margin of normal tissue, often with curative intent. Incisional: excises a portion of tumor for diagnosis. CNB: obtains less tissue but often sufficient for surgical planning. FNA: minimally invasive, obtains only cells; a positive FNA may guide treatment, but a negative FNA cannot definitively rule out malignancy. Incisional biopsy incisions should be oriented to allow excision with the tumor specimen (e.g., for sarcomas).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What is the evidence regarding melanoma surgical margins? What margin has shown no additional benefit?", "answer": "Margins greater than 2 cm have shown no benefit in the treatment of cutaneous melanoma. This represents the paradigm shift from Halsted-era radical resections to evidence-based conservative approaches combined with multimodality therapy.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Immediate vs delayed reconstruction", "question": "Does breast reconstruction (implant or autologous) delay detection of recurrent disease?", "answer": "No. Data do not support the contention that reconstruction obscures recurrence detection. Neither implant nor autologous reconstruction has been associated with a delay in diagnosis of recurrent disease. Recurrences after TRAM flap reconstruction can be managed with local excision and flap salvage in 80% of cases. Recurrent disease is detectable on physical exam, not mammography.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Sentinel lymph node biopsy concepts", "question": "Compare elective lymph node dissection (ELND) vs therapeutic lymph node dissection (TLND) vs sentinel lymph node biopsy.", "answer": "ELND: performed prophylactically at initial tumor excision. Not routinely recommended because (1) increased morbidity (lymphedema, nerve damage) and (2) no clear survival benefit over TLND for melanoma. TLND: performed when tumor subsequently recurs in a nodal basin. Sentinel lymph node biopsy: minimally invasive staging technique with much lower lymphedema rates (5% vs 35%) that identifies which patients may benefit from further dissection.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What types of immunotherapy are used in melanoma treatment? Describe passive, adoptive, and active approaches.", "answer": "Passive: monoclonal antibodies against tumor antigens (e.g., checkpoint inhibitors like pembrolizumab targeting PD-1, ipilimumab targeting CTLA-4). Adoptive: ex vivo manipulation of autologous tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes with IL-2 to increase cytolytic potential, then reinfusion. Active nonspecific: BCG, cytokines (IL-2, interferon-alpha) - melanoma is the most immunogenic tumor. Active specific: vaccines derived from antigens on patients' cancer cells using dendritic cell presentation.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Timing of reconstruction: immediate vs delayed", "question": "How has the availability of reconstructive techniques influenced cancer treatment paradigms? Give two examples.", "answer": "(1) Breast cancer: availability of autologous and implant-based reconstruction may influence decisions to proceed with mastectomy vs lumpectomy+radiation. Nipple-sparing mastectomy, once unthinkable, is now used with increasing indications. (2) Limb sarcoma: limb preservation for osteosarcomas became possible through neoadjuvant chemotherapy combined with functional reconstructions (allografts/endoprostheses), replacing amputation.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers", "subtopic": "Surgical margins conceptually", "question": "What is the recurrence rate for basal cell cancer with positive margins, and what does this suggest about the body's immune capacity?", "answer": "Recurrence rates are only 20-30% despite positive margins, suggesting the body's immune system has the capacity to destroy small numbers of residual cancerous cells.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Hemostasis, inflammation, proliferation, remodeling", "question": "List the four phases of wound healing and their approximate timelines.", "answer": "(1) Hemostasis: seconds to minutes after injury. (2) Inflammation: begins immediately, lasts ~2-3 days. (3) Proliferation: starts ~3 days, lasts up to 3 weeks. (4) Maturation/Remodeling: begins ~2-3 weeks after injury, can last up to 2 years.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Hemostasis, inflammation, proliferation, remodeling", "question": "Describe the hemostasis phase of wound healing. What forms the provisional matrix?", "answer": "Hemostasis begins within seconds to minutes. A coagulation cascade is activated by fibrin binding platelets. The blood clot serves as a physical barrier to bleeding and induces local vasoconstriction. The clot (consisting of thrombin, fibronectin, collagen, and platelets) serves as a provisional matrix for neutrophils, monocytes, fibroblasts, and endothelial cells to migrate into the wound.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Hemostasis, inflammation, proliferation, remodeling", "question": "Describe the sequence of inflammatory cell arrival during wound healing. What is the role of each cell type?", "answer": "Neutrophils arrive first (within 24-48 hours), activate the complement system, clear pathogens/damaged matrix/cells, then are extruded with eschar or phagocytosed by macrophages. Monocytes infiltrate at ~72 hours, recruited by TGF-beta, ECM fragments, and degraded bacteria products. They differentiate into macrophages which phagocytose dead cells/debris and produce growth factors (TGF-alpha, TGF-beta, PDGF, IGF, IL-1) to transition to the proliferative phase.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Hemostasis, inflammation, proliferation, remodeling", "question": "What are M1 and M2 macrophages, and why is their transition important for wound healing?", "answer": "M1 (proinflammatory) macrophages are responsible for phagocytosis of cells and debris during the inflammatory phase. M2 (anti-inflammatory) macrophages are necessary to transition to the proliferative phase, increasing collagen and ground substance production. Failure of macrophages to transition from M1 to M2 phenotype is associated with the development of chronic wounds.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Hemostasis, inflammation, proliferation, remodeling", "question": "What three essential processes occur during the proliferative phase of wound healing?", "answer": "(1) Granulation tissue deposition: fibroplasia (increased fibroblasts, collagen, elastin, fibronectin production) and angiogenesis (new blood vessels), driven by FGF, VEGF, PDGF, TGF-beta. Granulation tissue established by day 5. (2) Re-epithelialization: basal keratinocytes proliferate and migrate over granulation tissue; epidermal stem cells from hair follicle bulge regions also contribute. (3) Wound contraction: macrophages induce fibroblasts to differentiate into alpha-SMA-expressing myofibroblasts that pull wound edges together.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Collagen types and scar maturation", "question": "During the maturation phase, what happens to collagen and what is the maximum tensile strength achieved?", "answer": "Type III collagen (produced during proliferation) is remodeled to type I collagen over months 6-12. Collagen fibers become increasingly parallel in orientation, orchestrated by matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs) from fibroblasts and macrophages. Wound tensile strength increases but will NEVER return to pre-wounded skin strength.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Angiogenesis and epithelialization", "question": "What is the role of HIF-1-alpha in wound healing, and how do its expression levels affect outcomes?", "answer": "HIF-1-alpha is a transcription factor that stimulates pro-angiogenic pathways through VEGF and nitric oxide signaling. It is crucial for appropriate inflammatory and angiogenic responses and granulation tissue formation. Downregulation leads to chronic wounds; overexpression contributes to fibrosis and excessive scarring. Levels are regulated by oxygen tension.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Wound assessment", "subtopic": "Acute vs chronic wound", "question": "What defines a chronic wound, and what is the pathophysiology that keeps it from healing?", "answer": "A chronic wound has not shown significant progress toward healing within 30 days (or remains open at 3 months). Chronic wounds are trapped in the inflammatory phase and cannot progress to proliferation/maturation. They demonstrate excessive neutrophils and macrophages, prolonged overexpression of proinflammatory cytokines, excess reactive oxygen species (ROS) damaging cell membranes/ECM, and untimely overexpression of MMPs creating a proteolytic environment that degrades necessary growth factors.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "Compare hypertrophic scars and keloids: growth pattern, regression, and histologic features.", "answer": "Hypertrophic scars: raised but do NOT grow beyond boundaries of the original wound; tend to regress over several years. Keloids: extend beyond the original wound border, grow without limitation, and rarely regress. Keloids exhibit increased fibroblast numbers and can form dermal nodules. Both are related to disorders in the inflammatory process. Patients with pigmented skin (Africans, Asians) have higher propensity for keloids (up to 10% following incisions).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Factors impairing healing: smoking, diabetes, infection, ischemia, radiation, malnutrition, steroids, chemotherapy, edema, tension, foreign body", "question": "How does diabetes impair each phase of wound healing?", "answer": "Peripheral vascular disease leads to poor circulation with deficient oxygen and nutrition delivery, especially to extremities. Decreased complement activation and lower cytokine production impair immune response. Hyperglycemia impairs leukocyte function and provides nutrients for bacterial growth. Chronic hypoxia amplifies early inflammatory response, increases oxidative stress, and alters HIF-1-alpha function. Collectively, all four phases of wound healing are impaired.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Factors impairing healing: smoking, diabetes, infection, ischemia, radiation, malnutrition, steroids, chemotherapy, edema, tension, foreign body", "question": "How do systemic corticosteroids impair wound healing, and what can counteract this effect?", "answer": "Corticosteroids inhibit ALL phases: in inflammation, they downregulate cytokines (TGF-beta, PDGF, TNF, IL-1-alpha) and inhibit macrophage infiltration. In proliferation, they reduce TGF-beta and KGF, mitigating fibroblast proliferation and re-epithelialization. In maturation, they impair collagen transformation, disrupt dermal-epidermal junctions, and decrease tensile strength by reducing collagen accumulation. Vitamin A administration can counteract this by stimulating macrophages.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Factors impairing healing: smoking, diabetes, infection, ischemia, radiation, malnutrition, steroids, chemotherapy, edema, tension, foreign body", "question": "What nutritional factors affect wound healing? List the role of key vitamins, minerals, and amino acids.", "answer": "Vitamin A: stimulates fibroblast collagen synthesis, counteracts steroid effects. Vitamin C: supports hydroxylation of proline to hydroxyproline for collagen cross-linking; deficiency reduces collagen synthesis and causes capillary fragility. Vitamin E: protects against oxidative stress, may prevent excessive scarring. Zinc: cofactor for DNA/RNA polymerase, essential for cell division, protein/collagen synthesis. Glutamine: energy source for proliferating cells, improves wound strength. Arginine: promotes immune function, angiogenesis, collagen deposition. Proteins are key building blocks; deficiency decreases leukocyte phagocytosis and increases infection susceptibility.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Labs", "subtopic": "Albumin/prealbumin limitations and nutrition assessment", "question": "How can protein levels be assessed in wound healing patients?", "answer": "Serum albumin and pre-albumin laboratory tests. Protein deficiency affects the immune system by decreasing leukocyte phagocytosis and increasing infection susceptibility, and inhibits angiogenesis, fibroblast proliferation, proteoglycan synthesis, and collagen synthesis. Correction of protein deficiencies improves wound healing.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Wound assessment", "subtopic": "Culture interpretation: colonization vs infection", "question": "Distinguish between wound colonization and wound infection. What is the most common causative organism?", "answer": "Colonization: bacteria exist within the wound without causing overt infection; common from normal flora, other body areas, or external environment. Colonization can shift the immune system to a more inflammatory state. Infection: bacteria multiply and cause tissue damage, prolonged inflammation, and impaired healing. Staphylococcus aureus is the most common infection-causing organism. Bacteria may form biofilms (complex colonies enclosed in protective extracellular polymeric substance) making eradication difficult.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Wound assessment", "subtopic": "When a wound is ready for grafting or closure", "question": "Describe primary, secondary, and tertiary intention wound closure and their indications.", "answer": "Primary intention: wound edges approximated with sutures/staples/adhesives; for clean wounds, ideally closed within 4-6 hours (up to 12 hours possible). Secondary intention: wound left open to heal by re-epithelialization and contraction; for grossly contaminated wounds or those with excessive tension from tissue loss (e.g., deep puncture wounds, heavily soiled lacerations, bite puncture wounds >24 hours). Tertiary intention (delayed primary closure): wound initially treated with dressing changes, then closed later once tissue is confirmed healthy and can be reapproximated without tension.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Acute burn care", "subtopic": "Burn depth: superficial, superficial partial, deep partial, full thickness", "question": "Compare first-degree, superficial second-degree, deep second-degree, third-degree, and fourth-degree burns in terms of depth, sensation, and treatment.", "answer": "First-degree: epithelial layer only; erythematous, painful; heals without sequelae. Superficial second-degree: epidermis + superficial dermis; painful, erythematous, weeping; heals without surgery (topical antimicrobials, daily washing, moist dressings); regeneration from dermal appendages. Deep second-degree: through most of dermis; LESS painful (nerve endings destroyed); requires debridement and grafting. Third-degree: entire dermis; insensate; requires debridement and grafting. Fourth-degree: into subcutaneous tissue and deeper; requires specialized composite reconstruction.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Chronic lower-extremity wounds", "subtopic": "Diabetic foot ulcers", "question": "Outline the treatment algorithm for diabetic foot ulcers (DFUs).", "answer": "(1) Sharp debridement, dressing changes, pressure off-loading, optimize glucose levels. (2) Assess for infection: if present, serial debridement and directed antibiotic therapy. (3) Assess vascular flow (ABI, foot pulses): if not optimized, vascular surgery consult for stent/bypass. (4) If not healing within 1 month: consider NPWT, hyperbaric oxygen, growth factors, skin substitutes. (5) After healing: annual monitoring is necessary as most DFUs recur within 2 years.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Chronic lower-extremity wounds", "subtopic": "Arterial ulcers", "question": "What defines an ischemic ulcer, and what is critical for their treatment?", "answer": "Ischemic ulcers are skin ulcerations (usually lower extremity) in the setting of poor arterial flow, defined by ABI <1, non-compressible arteries, or absent/abnormal waveforms at the ankle. Correction of blood flow (balloon angioplasty or bypass grafting) is critical and dramatically improves healing rates. Complete closure may take >6 months. Patients with ischemic ulcers complicated by osteomyelitis or end-stage renal disease have very poor healing and significantly higher amputation rates.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Chronic lower-extremity wounds", "subtopic": "Venous stasis ulcers", "question": "What are the key treatments for venous stasis ulcers?", "answer": "Lifestyle interventions: leg elevation above heart (~120 min daily) and exercise (daily walking) promote healing. For persistent ulcers: debridement if infected with culture-directed antibiotics (NOT prophylactic systemic antibiotics, which create resistant organisms). Compression therapy improves healing rates and prevents recurrent cellulitis. Moist dressing environment promotes healing but no dressing type (including silver) is proven superior. Skin substitutes may improve closure rate after clean debridement.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Pressure injuries", "subtopic": "Sacral, ischial, trochanteric ulcers", "question": "Where do pressure sores commonly occur, and what is the treatment approach?", "answer": "Common locations: sacrum, ischium, trochanter, calcaneus - overlying bony prominences in patients with limited mobility. Treatment: (1) Address external pressure by off-loading (rotation in bed/wheelchair, cushioning bony prominences). (2) Debride to viable bleeding tissue. (3) Treat infections with biopsy-directed antibiotic therapy. (4) For non-healing wounds with good compliance: surgical debridement with flap reconstruction (though recurrence rates can be as high as 60%).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "What are the current treatment options for keloids?", "answer": "Silicone sheets: worn 24h/day for 3-6 months; improves appearance but not complete resolution. Intralesional corticosteroid injection (triamcinolone): mainstay of treatment; improves scar appearance, height, and symptoms (pain, pruritis). Surgical excision: option but recurrence is common. Radiation therapy: can be used as adjunct. Excision alone has high recurrence rates; best results typically combine excision with adjuvant therapy.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Wound assessment", "subtopic": "Vascularity of wound bed", "question": "What is the relationship between oxygen tension and chronic wound healing? What are the critical oxygen levels?", "answer": "Chronic wounds are remarkably hypoxic (transcutaneous oxygen pressure 5-20 mmHg). Lower extremity wounds will NOT heal if partial oxygen pressure is <30 mmHg. Oxygen promotes angiogenesis, collagen synthesis, growth factor production, ROS generation for bacterial killing, and leucocyte/fibroblast function. Acute hypoxia temporarily increases cell proliferation (beneficial), but prolonged hypoxia leads to abnormal healing through excess ROS, protein/lipid/DNA damage, and impaired progression through healing phases.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Debridement and dressings", "subtopic": "Negative-pressure wound therapy: indications, contraindications, complications", "question": "What are the benefits of negative pressure wound therapy (NPWT) for diabetic foot ulcers compared to standard dressings?", "answer": "NPWT demonstrates faster rates of wound closure and lessens the rate of amputation compared to dressings when applied to adequately debrided wounds in the absence of infection.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Factors impairing healing: smoking, diabetes, infection, ischemia, radiation, malnutrition, steroids, chemotherapy, edema, tension, foreign body", "question": "How does obesity impair wound healing?", "answer": "Obesity causes: (1) general hypovascularity and impaired oxygen delivery, (2) proinflammatory environment, (3) oxidative stress with free radical/antioxidant imbalance, (4) malnutrition (high fat/carb diet missing micronutrients), (5) depleted adiponectin levels (compromising perfusion and re-epithelialization), (6) increased cellular senescence in skin. Common wound complications in obese patients include infections, seromas, wound dehiscence, pressure ulcers, and venous stasis ulcers.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Differences in healing of skin, tendon, bone, nerve, cartilage, and vessels", "question": "How does aging affect each phase of wound healing?", "answer": "Hemostasis: increased platelet aggregation. Inflammation: decreased macrophage and B-lymphocyte infiltration, declined macrophage function. Proliferation: delayed re-epithelialization (keratinocyte migration takes nearly twice as long), slower angiogenesis and collagen synthesis. Maturation: prolonged with diminished healed tissue strength. Additionally, aged skin has flattened rete ridges (decreased dermal-epidermal mechanical strength), reduced dermal collagen/elastin, decreased microcirculation, and increased cellular senescence (fibroblasts/keratinocytes become unresponsive to growth factors).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "What is the Vancouver Scar Scale (VSS) and what four parameters does it assess?", "answer": "The Vancouver Scar Scale is one of the most commonly used scar assessment tools. It evaluates four parameters: (1) Pigmentation (0=normal, 1=hypopigmented, 2=mixed, 3=hyperpigmented), (2) Vascularity (0=normal, 1=pink, 2=red, 3=purple), (3) Pliability (0=normal to 5=contracture), and (4) Height (0=flat to 3= >5mm). Higher total scores indicate worse scarring.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "Name and describe at least three scar assessment scales beyond the Vancouver Scar Scale.", "answer": "(1) POSAS (Patient and Observer Scar Assessment Scale): includes both patient and observer components, assessing vascularity, pigmentation, thickness, relief, pliability, and surface area. (2) VAS (Visual Analogue Scale): simple linear scale for overall scar appearance. (3) SBSES (Stony Brook Scar Evaluation Scale): evaluates width, height, color, suture marks, and overall appearance. (4) MCFONTZL: assesses matte/shiny, contour, flexibility, opacity, numbness, texture, zero point, and level.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Collagen types and scar maturation", "question": "What is the role of fibroblast heterogeneity in scar formation? Describe the difference between papillary and reticular dermal fibroblasts.", "answer": "Fibroblasts are heterogeneous even within the same tissue. Papillary (superficial) dermal fibroblasts are associated with less scarring and more regenerative healing. Reticular (deep) dermal fibroblasts produce more collagen and are associated with fibrotic/scarring responses. Deep dermal injuries that damage the papillary dermis and recruit reticular fibroblasts tend to produce worse scars. The engrailed-1 (En1) fibroblast lineage has been identified as particularly pro-fibrotic.", "notes": "Scar biology detail from Ch16; closest match is collagen/scar maturation"}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Collagen types and scar maturation", "question": "What is the maximum tensile strength a healed wound can achieve compared to unwounded skin?", "answer": "A healed wound reaches approximately 80% of the tensile strength of unwounded skin. It never returns to full pre-injury strength regardless of the duration of remodeling.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "Compare hypertrophic scars and keloids across seven clinical and biological features: boundaries, regression, recurrence, symptoms, collagen pattern, genetics, and common locations.", "answer": "Hypertrophic scars: stay within wound boundaries, may regress over 1-2 years, lower recurrence after excision, related to wound tension/inflammation, collagen in organized parallel bundles, no strong genetic predisposition, occur at high-tension sites. Keloids: extend beyond wound boundaries, rarely regress spontaneously, high recurrence after excision alone (45-100%), often symptomatic (pain/pruritis), collagen in thick disorganized whorls, strong genetic/familial component (higher in African and Asian populations), common on earlobes/chest/shoulders/upper back.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "Outline the first-line, second-line, and third-line treatments for hypertrophic scars.", "answer": "First-line: silicone-based therapy (sheets or gel, worn 12-24 hours/day for 3-6 months) and pressure therapy (pressure garments at 24-30 mmHg). Second-line: intralesional corticosteroid injection (triamcinolone acetonide 10-40 mg/mL, repeated every 4-6 weeks). Third-line: surgical excision combined with adjuvant therapy (intralesional steroids, silicone, or other modalities to prevent recurrence).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "What is the proposed mechanism of action of silicone-based scar therapy?", "answer": "The exact mechanism is not fully understood. Leading theories include: (1) hydration and occlusion of the stratum corneum, which reduces transepidermal water loss and decreases capillary activity/collagen deposition; (2) static electricity generated by silicone may influence collagen alignment; (3) temperature regulation of the scar. Silicone sheets should be worn 12-24 hours/day for at least 3-6 months for optimal effect.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "What are the side effects of intralesional corticosteroid (triamcinolone) injection for abnormal scars?", "answer": "Side effects include: skin/fat atrophy at injection site, hypopigmentation (especially in darker skin), telangiectasia, pain during injection, and potential for rebound scar growth if treatment is discontinued prematurely. Systemic effects are rare but can include menstrual irregularities and adrenal suppression with frequent/high-dose injections.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "Describe the treatment algorithm for keloids, including the role of radiotherapy.", "answer": "First-line: silicone therapy and intralesional corticosteroids (triamcinolone). Second-line: combination therapy with intralesional 5-fluorouracil (5-FU) Â± corticosteroids, cryotherapy, or intralesional bleomycin. Third-line: surgical excision followed by adjuvant radiotherapy (typically within 24-48 hours postop). Radiotherapy is particularly important for keloids because excision alone has recurrence rates of 45-100%, while excision + radiotherapy reduces recurrence to approximately 10-20%. Other adjuncts include verapamil and imiquimod.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "How does intralesional cryotherapy work for keloid treatment, and what are its advantages?", "answer": "Intralesional cryotherapy involves inserting a cryoprobe directly into the keloid to freeze tissue from the inside out, causing vascular damage and ischemic necrosis of the scar tissue. Advantages over external spray cryotherapy include: more uniform freezing of deeper scar tissue, less damage to overlying epidermis (reduced risk of hypopigmentation), and potentially better cosmetic outcomes. It can be combined with intralesional corticosteroid injection.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "What is the role of 5-fluorouracil (5-FU) in keloid and hypertrophic scar treatment?", "answer": "5-FU is an antimetabolite that inhibits fibroblast proliferation and collagen synthesis by blocking thymidylate synthase. It is administered as intralesional injection (50 mg/mL), often combined with triamcinolone to reduce side effects. The combination of 5-FU + triamcinolone has shown superior results compared to triamcinolone alone for keloids. Side effects include pain at injection site, hyperpigmentation, and rarely tissue necrosis.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "What types of lasers are used for scar treatment, and what are their mechanisms?", "answer": "Pulsed dye laser (PDL, 585-595 nm): targets hemoglobin in scar vasculature, reduces erythema and may decrease scar volume by altering collagen remodeling; best for early erythematous/immature scars. Fractional CO2 laser (10,600 nm): creates micro-columns of thermal injury that stimulate wound healing cascade and collagen remodeling; useful for atrophic scars and mature hypertrophic scars. Nd:YAG laser (1064 nm): deeper penetration for thicker scars. Laser therapy is often used as adjunct to other treatments.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Z-plasty and W-plasty design principles", "question": "Describe the Z-plasty technique: what are its components, how does it work, and what theoretical length gains are achieved at different angles?", "answer": "Z-plasty consists of a central limb (along the scar) and two peripheral limbs of equal length angled from each end, creating two triangular flaps that are transposed. Theoretical length gains by angle: 30Â° â†’ 25% gain, 45Â° â†’ 50% gain, 60Â° â†’ 75% gain (most commonly used), 75Â° â†’ 100% gain, 90Â° â†’ 120% gain. The technique reorients the central scar line, breaks up linear scars, and recruits adjacent tissue to lengthen contracted areas.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Z-plasty and W-plasty design principles", "question": "What are the four fundamental functions of Z-plasty?", "answer": "(1) Lengthen a contracted scar or tight structure (the primary indication for scar contractures). (2) Change the direction/orientation of a scar to better align with relaxed skin tension lines (RSTLs). (3) Break up a straight-line scar into an irregular pattern that is less conspicuous. (4) Transpose tissue (move tissue from an area of relative excess to an area of deficiency).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Z-plasty and W-plasty design principles", "question": "Compare Z-plasty and W-plasty: when would you use each technique for scar revision?", "answer": "Z-plasty: best for scar contractures requiring lengthening, scars crossing concavities, and scars that need reorientation to RSTLs. Provides actual tissue lengthening along the central limb. W-plasty: best for long linear scars on flat/convex surfaces where the primary goal is to break up the scar line (camouflage) without significant lengthening. Creates interdigitating triangular flaps that prevent a straight-line shadow. W-plasty does NOT provide lengthening, so it is NOT appropriate for contractures.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Z-plasty and W-plasty design principles", "question": "What is the geometric broken line closure (GBLC) technique, and when is it preferred?", "answer": "GBLC uses randomly arranged geometric shapes (triangles, rectangles, semicircles) on alternating sides of the scar to create an irregular closure line. It is preferred for long scars on convex or flat surfaces, particularly on the face, where a highly irregular line better camouflages the scar by preventing the eye from tracking a single line. It is more technically demanding than W-plasty but may provide superior camouflage in experienced hands.", "notes": "Scar revision technique from Ch16; closest subtopic is Z/W-plasty design"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "What are Langer's lines and relaxed skin tension lines (RSTLs)? Why are they important for scar prevention?", "answer": "Langer's lines were described by Karl Langer in 1861 by puncturing cadaver skin with a round awl and observing the resulting elliptical patterns. Relaxed skin tension lines (RSTLs), described by Borges, represent the lines of minimal skin tension in living tissue, generally perpendicular to the direction of underlying muscle contraction. Scars oriented parallel to RSTLs experience less tension and tend to heal with thinner, less noticeable scars. Surgical incisions should be planned parallel to RSTLs whenever possible.", "notes": "Scar prevention principle; closest match is hypertrophic/keloid prevention"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "What is the recommended timing for scar revision surgery, and why?", "answer": "Scar revision should generally wait until the scar has matured, typically at least 12-18 months after the original wound. Reasons: (1) Scars continue to remodel and improve during maturation, and early revision may be unnecessary. (2) Mature scars are softer, flatter, and less vascular, making surgical revision technically easier. (3) The inflammatory response is diminished in mature tissue. Exceptions include functionally limiting contractures (especially in children) that may warrant earlier intervention.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "What is the role of pressure therapy in scar management? What pressure is recommended and for how long?", "answer": "Pressure therapy (custom-fitted compression garments) is a first-line treatment for hypertrophic scars, especially after burns. Recommended pressure is 24-30 mmHg, worn 23 hours/day for 6-12 months or until scar maturation. Mechanism: reduces blood flow to the scar, creates local hypoxia that decreases fibroblast proliferation and collagen synthesis, and mechanically remodels collagen fibers. Compliance is the major limitation, as garments are uncomfortable and must be worn continuously.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Basic wound healing", "subtopic": "Collagen types and scar maturation", "question": "What is the engrailed-1 (En1) fibroblast lineage, and what is its significance in scarring?", "answer": "Engrailed-1 positive (En1+) fibroblasts are a specific fibroblast lineage identified as being pro-fibrotic and primarily responsible for connective tissue deposition during scarring. Research has shown that inhibiting or depleting En1+ fibroblasts can promote regenerative (scarless) healing. This discovery has implications for potential future anti-scarring therapies. En1+ fibroblasts are primarily found in the reticular dermis.", "notes": "Advanced scar biology from Ch16; closest match is collagen/scar maturation"}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "What factors increase the risk of developing abnormal (hypertrophic or keloid) scars?", "answer": "Patient factors: darker skin pigmentation (African, Asian descent), age (higher risk in younger patients, ages 10-30), genetic predisposition/family history, hormonal changes (puberty, pregnancy). Wound factors: wounds crossing joints or high-tension areas, wounds perpendicular to RSTLs, deep dermal injury, prolonged inflammation, infection, wounds healing by secondary intention, foreign body reaction. Anatomic sites: anterior chest/sternum, shoulders, upper back, earlobes are high-risk locations.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Steroid injection, silicone, pressure therapy, laser, radiation in selected cases", "question": "Describe the use of bleomycin for keloid treatment. What is the typical administration technique?", "answer": "Bleomycin is an antineoplastic antibiotic that inhibits DNA synthesis in fibroblasts. It is administered via multiple needle puncture technique: the keloid surface is punctured with a needle dipped in bleomycin solution (1.5 IU/mL), allowing the drug to penetrate the scar tissue. This is repeated every 4-6 weeks. Advantages: effective for steroid-resistant keloids. Side effects: hyperpigmentation, pain, skin atrophy, and rarely pulmonary fibrosis with systemic absorption (dose-dependent).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Abnormal scars", "subtopic": "Hypertrophic scar vs keloid", "question": "What is the subunit principle in scar revision, and who described it?", "answer": "Described by Burget and Menick (1985) for nasal reconstruction, the subunit principle states that scars are less conspicuous when placed at the borders of aesthetic subunits rather than within them. When planning scar revision (especially on the face), incisions and closures should be designed to fall along natural boundaries between aesthetic subunits (e.g., alar groove, nasolabial fold, lid-cheek junction). This principle extends to placing scars in natural creases or at hairline boundaries.", "notes": "Scar revision principle from Ch16"}, {"topic": "Wound assessment", "subtopic": "Acute vs chronic wound", "question": "What non-surgical treatments can be used for depressed or atrophic scars?", "answer": "Options include: (1) Dermal fillers (hyaluronic acid, calcium hydroxylapatite) for volume restoration â€” temporary effect. (2) Autologous fat grafting â€” provides volume and potentially regenerative stem cell effects. (3) Fractional CO2 laser â€” stimulates collagen remodeling to raise depressed scars. (4) Microneedling â€” induces controlled micro-injury to promote collagen induction. (5) Acellular dermal matrix â€” can be placed beneath depressed scars. (6) Chemical peels â€” for superficial atrophic scars (acne scars).", "notes": "Depressed scar treatments from Ch16; assigned to wound assessment as closest match"}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Z-plasty and W-plasty design principles", "question": "What are the key planning principles when designing a Z-plasty for scar revision?", "answer": "Key principles: (1) The central limb is placed along the scar to be revised. (2) Peripheral limbs should be equal in length to the central limb. (3) Standard angle is 60Â° (provides 75% lengthening with good transposition). (4) Flaps must include adequate subcutaneous tissue thickness to ensure blood supply. (5) The final scar orientation should be planned to fall along RSTLs. (6) Multiple small Z-plasties in series are often better than one large Z-plasty. (7) Flaps should not be undermined too thinly to avoid tip necrosis.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Local flaps", "subtopic": "Z-plasty and W-plasty design principles", "question": "What is a serial (multiple) Z-plasty, and when is it preferred over a single Z-plasty?", "answer": "A serial Z-plasty uses multiple small Z-plasties arranged along a long scar instead of one large Z-plasty. Advantages: (1) Better distribution of tension across the scar. (2) Each individual flap is smaller and has more reliable blood supply. (3) Less distortion of surrounding tissue. (4) The final scar has a more natural, broken-up appearance. Preferred for: long linear scar contractures, web space contractures, and areas where a single large Z-plasty would create excessive tissue distortion.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "Compare split-thickness skin grafts (STSG) and full-thickness skin grafts (FTSG) in terms of composition, contraction, donor site healing, and indications.", "answer": "STSG: contains epidermis + partial dermis; greater secondary contraction at recipient site; donor site heals by re-epithelialization from remaining dermal appendages (7-21 days); used for large wounds, burns, and areas where contraction is acceptable. FTSG: contains epidermis + entire dermis; minimal secondary contraction; donor site must be closed primarily; used for aesthetically (face) or functionally (hand) important areas. Thicker grafts = less contraction but more demanding recipient bed requirements.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "What are the three subtypes of split-thickness skin grafts based on thickness, and what are their eponymous names?", "answer": "Thin STSG (Thiersch-Ollier graft): 0.15-0.3 mm. Intermediate STSG (Blair-Brown graft): 0.3-0.45 mm. Thick STSG (deep graft): 0.45-0.6 mm. Thinner grafts heal faster at the donor site and allow repeat harvest (~2 weeks), but result in more recipient site contraction and typically do not transfer functional appendages. Thicker grafts transfer hair follicles and glands but cause more donor site morbidity.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Graft take physiology: imbibition, inosculation, revascularization", "question": "Describe the three phases of skin graft 'take' and the timeline for each.", "answer": "(1) Serum imbibition (days 0-2): graft survives via diffusion of plasma/nutrients from wound bed through fibrin layer. (2) Revascularization (begins ~24-48 hours): occurs by three mechanisms - anastomosis (reconnection of existing vessels between graft and bed), neovascularization (new vessel ingrowth from recipient into graft), and endothelial cell ingrowth (recipient endothelial cells proliferate along pre-existing graft vascular basal lamina as graft endothelial cells degenerate). (3) Maturation (weeks to years): remodeling, collagen deposition/cross-linking, fibroblast repopulation, myofibroblast-driven contraction, and regression of immature blood vessels.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Graft take physiology: imbibition, inosculation, revascularization", "question": "What are the three causes of skin graft failure, and how can each be prevented?", "answer": "(1) Hematoma/seroma: fluid collection separates graft from wound bed, preventing imbibition and revascularization. Prevention: meticulous hemostasis, meshing or pie-crusting the graft for fluid egress, compressive/bolster dressings, or vacuum-assisted closure. (2) Infection: bacteria destroy graft tissue and prevent vascular ingrowth. Prevention: adequate wound bed debridement, antimicrobial dressings, topical agents (silver nitrate, mafenide acetate). (3) Shearing/instability: disrupts fragile new blood vessels. Prevention: bolster dressings, splinting, immobilization, fibrin glue, conscientious postoperative handling.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "What tissues are NOT suitable as recipient beds for skin grafts, and why? What is the exception?", "answer": "Tissues with inadequate blood supply cannot support graft revascularization: irradiated tissue, ischemic tissue, scar tissue, exposed bone, and exposed tendon. The exception is when intact vascularized periosteum or peritenon is present â€” grafting can sometimes succeed over these surfaces. For areas of exposed bone/tendon without periosteum/peritenon, vacuum-assisted closure can encourage granulation tissue formation before grafting, or dermal substitutes can be applied.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Meshing ratios and indications", "question": "What is skin graft meshing? Describe the available ratios and the trade-offs of increasing mesh expansion.", "answer": "Meshing involves placing systematic slits in an STSG to allow expansion, with templates ranging from 1:1 to 1:9. Benefits: covers larger wound areas with limited donor skin, allows fluid egress preventing seroma/hematoma. Trade-offs of increasing mesh ratio: greater wound contracture, longer re-epithelialization time (keratinocytes must fill wider gaps), higher risk of hypertrophic scarring, uneven cobblestone-like skin relief, and increased graft fragility. For functional/aesthetic areas, surgeons typically prefer 1:1.5 to 1:2 maximum.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Meshing ratios and indications", "question": "What is the Meek technique, and when is it indicated?", "answer": "The Meek technique involves dividing a skin graft into small skin squares (originally 0.8 x 0.8 mm using a Meek-Wall microdermatome) that can be spread out to cover a much larger surface area, with expansion ratios up to 1:100. It is indicated when donor skin is extremely scarce, such as in massive burns with limited unburned skin. The technique can be combined with aerosolized epithelial cells (RECELL) to improve healing time between graft islands.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "What is a composite graft? Where is it most commonly used?", "answer": "A composite graft includes epidermis, dermis, AND a layer of subcutaneous fat tissue. The fat is less vascularized and more prone to ischemia, so optimal wound bed vascularity is critical for survival. Composite grafts are most frequently used for reconstruction of the nasal tip, nasal alar, and columella in patients with cleft lip. Due to their thickness, they have the highest nutritional demands of any graft type.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Donor site selection and healing", "question": "Describe common donor sites for STSG and FTSG, and the principles guiding donor site selection.", "answer": "STSG donor sites: lateral thighs and trunk (areas easily covered by clothing). FTSG donor sites: lower abdomen, inguinal crease, retro-auricular region; for facial defects, scalp, neck, and supraclavicular areas provide the best color match. Selection principles: (1) choose sites that allow good color/texture match to recipient, (2) FTSG donors must have enough laxity for primary closure, (3) consider aesthetic implications of donor scarring, (4) for burns, use whatever donor site is available, sparing face and hands.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Graft take physiology: imbibition, inosculation, revascularization", "question": "What is serum imbibition, and why is it critical for early skin graft survival?", "answer": "Serum imbibition is the first phase of graft take (days 0-2) during which the graft receives oxygen and nutrients via passive diffusion through the plasma/fibrin layer between the graft and wound bed. This is the sole means of graft survival before revascularization begins. Any barrier that disrupts this process (hematoma, seroma, infection, necrotic tissue) will result in graft ischemia and failure. Excessive serum accumulation (seroma) is also harmful, which is why grafts are meshed or pie-crusted.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "How does skin graft thickness affect the transfer of cutaneous appendages (hair, sweat glands, nerves)?", "answer": "Thin STSGs: do NOT transfer whole cutaneous appendages â€” no hair growth or sweat gland function. Thick STSGs: transfer some hair follicles and glandular structures; may develop hair growth and sweat gland function months after grafting. FTSGs: transfer the full complement of appendages. Neural regrowth occurs in grafted skin with similar histologic structures, but patients often report abnormal sensation (hypersensitivity, decreased sensation, pain) for prolonged periods. Sweat glands can reactivate ~3 months post-grafting after neural reconnection but remain abnormal compared to native skin.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Graft fixation: bolster, tie-over, NPWT", "question": "Describe the methods of skin graft fixation and when each is preferred.", "answer": "(1) Absorbable sutures: for smaller grafts or patients who cannot tolerate removal. (2) Skin staples: efficient for large grafts but painful on removal. (3) Bolster (tie-over) dressing: bulky dressing secured by sutures tied over it; ideal for difficult-to-dress areas, concavities, and small grafts (face, hand). (4) Vacuum-assisted closure (VAC): provides continuous compression and fluid removal over a petroleum gauze/silicone interface; excellent for large or uneven grafts over joints. (5) Fibrin glue: sprayed on wound bed before graft placement, acts as provisory extracellular matrix. Dressings are left 3-8 days to minimize shearing.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "Why should FTSG be 'defatted' before application, and how is this done?", "answer": "Defatting removes subcutaneous fat from the dermal surface of the FTSG. This is necessary because fat is poorly vascularized and acts as a barrier to revascularization from the wound bed, compromising graft take. Technique: the graft is spread dermis-side-up over a finger or basin, and fat tissue is trimmed tangentially from the dermis using scissors. Care must be taken not to damage dermal appendages or the dermal-hypodermal junction during defatting.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Donor site selection and healing", "question": "How does a split-thickness skin graft donor site heal, and what factors affect healing time?", "answer": "STSG donor sites heal by re-epithelialization from residual dermal appendages (hair follicles, eccrine glands, sebaceous glands) left in the remaining dermis. Epidermal stem cells in the hair follicle bulge region and glandular epithelium proliferate and migrate to resurface the wound. Healing time: 7-21 days depending on graft thickness taken, size of harvest, and patient age. Thinner grafts allow faster donor healing and repeat harvest (~2 weeks). Children and elderly require thinner harvests due to thinner native skin.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Skin substitutes: Integra, AlloDerm, cultured epithelial autograft", "question": "Compare four skin substitutes: Integra, AlloDerm, Epicel, and RECELL. Include their composition, origin, and application.", "answer": "Integra: bovine tendon type I collagen on a silicone sheet (xenogeneic); applied to wound bed, vascularizes in ~3 weeks, silicone removed and STSG placed on top. AlloDerm: human acellular lyophilized cadaver dermis (allogeneic); off-the-shelf, skin graft placed after vascularization. Epicel: cultured epidermal autograft (autologous); keratinocytes expanded from patient biopsy over several weeks in lab, then grafted. RECELL: autologous cell suspension (epidermis + dermis); bedside kit creates spray from patient donor skin in ~30 minutes for immediate application.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Skin substitutes: Integra, AlloDerm, cultured epithelial autograft", "question": "What is the role of acellular dermal matrices (ADMs) in wound reconstruction? What are the key considerations?", "answer": "ADMs are decellularized human, animal, or synthetic tissues that serve as scaffolds for host cell migration and tissue regeneration. They minimize antigenicity while providing structural support. Indications: wounds where contracture prevention is critical, protection of exposed sensitive structures, and cosmesis. ADMs come as powders, suspensions, woven sheets, or full decellularized tissue. Key considerations: (1) they require vascularization before skin grafting, (2) they have significant additional cost, (3) composition and architecture vary widely between products.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Skin substitutes: Integra, AlloDerm, cultured epithelial autograft", "question": "What is the role of cadaveric allograft skin, and why does it ultimately fail?", "answer": "Cadaveric allograft serves as a temporary biologic dressing, particularly valuable in acute treatment of large thermal burns where it minimizes mortality and enhances healing. However, allogeneic tissue is antigenic and will ultimately elicit an immunogenic rejection response. Tissue matching can extend survival, but without immunosuppression, all allografts are eventually rejected. Additional concerns: differing harvest, processing, and preservation techniques between tissue banks can affect viability and contamination risk.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "What is 'pie-crusting' of a skin graft, and when is it performed?", "answer": "Pie-crusting is the creation of multiple small perforations in a non-meshed skin graft using a scalpel. Purpose: allows egress of blood and serum from beneath the graft, preventing hematoma/seroma formation that would separate the graft from the wound bed and compromise take. It is performed on sheet (unmeshed) grafts, particularly when grafting functional areas such as the hands where a meshed appearance would be aesthetically unacceptable but fluid drainage is still needed.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "Describe the five layers of the epidermis from superficial to deep and their key features.", "answer": "(1) Stratum corneum: terminally differentiated anuclear corneocytes; primary permeability barrier. (2) Stratum lucidum: only in glabrous skin (palms/soles); contributes to thickness. (3) Stratum granulosum: rich in keratohyaline; keratinocytes transition to corneocytes and release lipid-rich ECM. (4) Stratum spinosum: keratinocytes anchored by tonofilaments to desmosomes; contains Langerhans cells (tissue-resident macrophages for antigen presentation). (5) Stratum basale (germinal layer): proliferative keratinocytes, melanocytes, and Merkel cells; semi-differentiated stem cells with self-renewal capacity; turnover cycle ~40-60 days.", "notes": "Skin anatomy relevant to grafting depth from Ch17"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "Describe the dermal-epidermal junction: its layers, key components, and why it matters for skin grafts.", "answer": "The DEJ consists of: (1) Basal lamina - lamina lucida (integrins, laminins) and lamina densa (collagen IV). (2) Basal reticularis - meshwork of collagen III interacting with basal lamina via collagen VII and fibrillin anchoring fibrils. Keratinocytes anchor via hemidesmosomes; papillary dermis anchors through basal reticularis. The DEJ has a corrugated cross-section (interlocking papillae) increasing surface area for shear resistance and diffusion. Significance for grafts: absence of intact DEJ in skin grafts makes them unstable against mechanical forces, contributing to graft fragility and susceptibility to shearing.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "What is the difference between papillary and reticular dermis, and why is this relevant for skin grafting?", "answer": "Papillary dermis: superficial, interfaces with basement membrane, responsible for anchoring DEJ and metabolic exchange with epidermis. Reticular dermis: deeper, thicker, composed of dense irregular connective tissue rich in collagen and elastic fibers; provides primary elasticity; contains most dermal appendages (glands, Pacinian and Ruffini corpuscles, nerves, vascular perforators). Relevance to grafting: graft thickness determines how much dermis is included â€” thin STSGs take only papillary dermis, thick STSGs include some reticular dermis, and FTSGs include the full dermis to the dermal-hypodermal junction.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "What considerations guide the choice between STSG and FTSG for facial reconstruction?", "answer": "FTSGs are preferred for facial reconstruction because they provide: (1) minimal secondary contraction (preventing distortion), (2) better color and texture match (especially from supraclavicular, retro-auricular, upper eyelid, or scalp donors), (3) transfer of functional appendages, and (4) superior aesthetic outcome. STSGs on the face result in significant contracture and poor cosmesis but may be necessary when FTSG donor sites are unavailable (e.g., large burn patients). For full-thickness defects, the subunit principle should guide graft placement at aesthetic unit borders.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "STSG vs FTSG: thickness, contraction, donor healing", "question": "What is the expected blood loss during wound excision for skin grafting, and how is hemostasis achieved?", "answer": "Blood loss of 100-200 mL is expected for every 1% of body surface area excised. Hemostasis methods: cautery or suture ligation for larger vessels; topical agents of thrombin and epinephrine for general oozing; tumescent solution of dilute epinephrine injected pre-excision to reduce bleeding. Hemostasis must be achieved before graft placement, as any blood collection (hematoma) between graft and wound bed will impair graft take.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Graft take physiology: imbibition, inosculation, revascularization", "question": "How does autologous fat grafting improve previously grafted skin?", "answer": "Penetrating (percutaneous) fat grafts beneath previously grafted or scarred skin have been demonstrated to: (1) enhance overlying skin quality, (2) improve vascularity, (3) increase skin mobility by releasing tethered scars, (4) improve contour irregularities, and (5) improve resistance to shear and trauma. The mechanism is thought to involve both volume restoration and regenerative effects from adipose-derived stem cells within the fat graft.", "notes": "Soft tissue augmentation after grafting from Ch17; assigned to graft physiology as closest match"}, {"topic": "Skin grafts", "subtopic": "Skin substitutes: Integra, AlloDerm, cultured epithelial autograft", "question": "What is RECELL and how does it differ from cultured epidermal autograft (Epicel)?", "answer": "RECELL: a bedside kit that creates an autologous cell suspension (keratinocytes and other cells) from a small donor skin sample in ~30 minutes, delivered as a spray. Can be used immediately intraoperatively. Epicel: requires a skin biopsy to be sent to a lab where keratinocytes are cultured and expanded over several weeks before being returned as sheets for grafting. Key difference: RECELL provides immediate intraoperative use with minimal delay, while Epicel requires weeks of lead time but provides more organized epithelial sheets. RECELL is particularly useful as an adjunct over widely meshed grafts to accelerate re-epithelialization.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the three types of cartilage? Describe their composition, properties, and where each is found.", "answer": "(1) Hyaline cartilage: most common type, composed of type II collagen and rich in glycosaminoglycans, providing stiffness for compressional loading. Found in costal cartilage, articular surfaces, trachea, and nose. Covered by perichondrium (except articular cartilage). (2) Fibrocartilage: bundles of thick collagen fibers (types I and II) with intervenient cartilage islands, providing high tensile strength. Found in meniscus, intervertebral discs, symphyseal joints, bone-tendon junctions. (3) Elastic cartilage: abundant elastic fibers forming a network with collagen, providing great flexibility and resistance to repeated bending. Found in external ear, larynx, and epiglottis. Covered by perichondrium.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Why does cartilage graft survive relatively easily when transplanted compared to other tissue grafts?", "answer": "Cartilage is a unique tissue with a low metabolic rate due to: (1) sparse cell population (chondrocytes are few), (2) avascular structure â€” cartilage has no intrinsic blood supply, and (3) near-anaerobic glycolytic metabolism with low oxygen consumption. Because cartilage is nourished by tissue fluid diffusion rather than direct blood supply, a transplanted cartilage graft can survive by diffusion from the surrounding recipient bed without requiring revascularization. Additionally, cartilage is considered 'immunologically privileged,' meaning allogeneic cartilage elicits less immune rejection than other tissue types.", "notes": "Cartilage graft biology from Ch19; closest match in topic list"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is the perichondrium? Describe its structure and role in cartilage repair.", "answer": "The perichondrium is a layer of dense irregular connective tissue surrounding most cartilage (except articular cartilage). It consists of two layers: (1) Outer fibrous layer: composed of collagen fibers and fibroblasts. (2) Inner chondrogenic layer: contains partially undifferentiated mesenchymal stem cells and chondrogenic progenitor cells. The inner layer can generate new cartilage (neochondrogenesis), which is why perichondrial grafts are used for cartilage reconstruction. Free perichondrial grafts can regenerate cartilage tissue when transplanted to appropriate recipient sites.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Compare the three autologous cartilage graft donor sites: auricular, nasal septal, and rib cartilage. Include advantages, limitations, and applications for each.", "answer": "Auricular (elastic) cartilage: most versatile graft; easily fashioned/contoured; harvested under local anesthesia with minimal donor deformity if technique is careful; limited quantity. Used for ear reconstruction, nasal reconstruction, tarsal/nipple reconstruction. Nasal septal (hyaline) cartilage: limited amount available; accessed via hemitransfixion incision; MUST preserve L-shaped strut for nasal support. Used for dorsal augmentation, eyelid reconstruction, tip grafts. Rib (hyaline) cartilage: greatest available quantity and mechanical strength; can be contoured into any shape; higher donor morbidity (pain, chest wall deformity, pneumothorax risk). Used for total ear framework, major nasal reconstruction, tracheal repair.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is the L-shaped strut in septal cartilage harvesting, and why must it be preserved?", "answer": "The L-shaped strut is a structural support of septal cartilage that must be maintained during harvesting of nasal septal cartilage grafts. It consists of: (1) a dorsal strut along the nasal dorsum, and (2) a caudal strut along the anterior nasal septum. Preservation is critical to maintain nasal structural support and prevent nasal collapse (saddle nose deformity). The amount of L-strut cartilage needed varies depending on the strength, thickness, and dimensions of the native septum and other nasal support structures (upper/lower lateral cartilages, nasal bones). Only the non-supportive posterior quadrangular cartilage can be freely harvested.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the potential complications of rib (costal) cartilage graft harvesting?", "answer": "Complications include: (1) Pneumothorax â€” the most serious intraoperative complication, occurring during posterior perichondrial dissection. (2) Chest wall pain â€” most common complaint, peaks in first week and gradually diminishes over 3 months. (3) Chest wall clicking. (4) Donor site scarring. (5) Chest wall contour deformity â€” particularly with Nagata's method requiring harvest of 4-6 costal cartilages. Prevention: careful technique keeping elevator tip against cartilage during posterior dissection, preserving perichondrium, intercostal nerve block with 0.25% bupivacaine, and returning unused cartilage fragments to the perichondrial sleeve.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the five techniques for managing the auricular donor site after composite graft harvest, based on graft size?", "answer": "Technique 1 (<1 cm graft): harvest from root of helix, primary closure with dog-ear run anteriorly into hairline. Technique 2 (1-1.5 cm): larger graft from helical base, closure by running dog-ear anteriorly and posteriorly with cartilage wedge removed from triangular fossa. Technique 3 (wide but short): harvest from anteroinferior helical rim, dog-ear run superiorly and inferiorly. Technique 4 (1-1.2 cm): helical base harvest with helical rim advancement and postauricular scaphomastoid suture to prevent overprojection. Technique 5 (>1.5 cm): V-shaped wedge with half-star cartilage pattern at apex plus postauricular incision with scaphomastoid suture to prevent ear cupping/distortion.", "notes": "Surgical technique for auricular composite graft donor management from Ch19"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the three major components required for tissue-engineered cartilage?", "answer": "(1) Seed cells: the cellular component responsible for matrix production, deposition, and tissue formation (chondrocytes, or stem cells induced to chondrogenic lineage). (2) Scaffold: a three-dimensional structure (e.g., PGA nonwoven fibers, polylactic acid, fibrin polymer) providing architecture for cells to reside, proliferate, and produce matrix. The scaffold degrades over time as new tissue forms. (3) Tissue formation environment: the appropriate in vitro or in vivo conditions (culture medium, growth factors, mechanical stimuli) needed for cell proliferation, matrix production, scaffold degradation, and tissue remodeling into mature engineered tissue.", "notes": "Cartilage tissue engineering from Ch19; closest match is reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is a composite chondrocutaneous graft, and what limits its available size as a free graft?", "answer": "A composite chondrocutaneous graft contains both cartilage and overlying skin harvested as a single unit, most commonly taken from the ear for nasal reconstruction. The size of free auricular composite grafts is limited by the lack of immediate blood supply after transplantation â€” the graft must survive initially by diffusion until revascularization occurs. Larger grafts have greater risk of central necrosis. To overcome this size limitation, microvascularly transferred auricular composite grafts based on the superficial temporal vessels can be used, with reported flap survival rates of 97% even for large nasal defects.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "How has CAD/CAM technology been applied to cartilage tissue engineering for auricular reconstruction?", "answer": "The process: (1) CT scan of patient's normal ear collects 3D geometric data. (2) CAD system generates mirror-image data of the normal ear. (3) CAM system 3D-prints a mold with the ear's 3D structure. (4) Scaffold material (PGA fibers coated with polylactic acid) is shaped using the mold, achieving >97% structural similarity to the original ear. (5) Chondrocytes are seeded onto the scaffold and cultured in vitro for 12 weeks, forming mature cartilage tissue with ~82.6% morphological similarity. This approach potentially allows patient-specific auricular reconstruction without the need for costal cartilage harvest.", "notes": "Tissue engineering application from Ch19"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Compare intramembranous and endochondral ossification. Where does each occur?", "answer": "Intramembranous ossification: direct condensation of mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs) that differentiate into osteoblasts, depositing bone without a cartilaginous intermediate. Creates flat bones of the craniofacial skeleton. Endochondral ossification: MSCs first form a hyaline cartilage template that is subsequently replaced by bone through chondrocyte hypertrophy, calcification, vascular invasion, and osteoblast-driven bone deposition. Creates long bones of the appendicular skeleton, vertebral column, and pelvis. Both processes occur during fracture repair.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Compare cortical and cancellous bone: structure, location, and function.", "answer": "Cortical (compact) bone: accounts for 80% of skeleton; dense and strong; forms the outer shell; primary unit is the osteon (haversian system) with concentric lamellae around central haversian canals containing vessels/nerves; Volkmann's canals connect horizontally. Covered by periosteum (outer fibrous layer + inner cambium/osteogenic layer) and lined by endosteum. Cancellous (trabecular) bone: 20% of skeleton; porous; located in medullary cavity at ends of long bones; bony trabeculae oriented along lines of stress; greater surface area for remodeling and higher metabolic activity; provides internal support for bone marrow.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the three cell types in bone? Describe their morphology, location, and function.", "answer": "Osteoblasts: rounded, basophilic cells on external bone surfaces at areas of active formation. Derived from MSCs. Produce osteoid (bone matrix), facilitate mineralization. 20% become osteocytes; rest undergo apoptosis or become bone-lining cells. Osteocytes: stellate cells with thin processes embedded in lacunae. Communicate via gap junctions through canaliculi. Functions include mechanosensing, mineral homeostasis, and bone resorption regulation. Terminally differentiated from osteoblasts. Osteoclasts: large, multinucleated cells with ruffled border on endosteal/periosteal surfaces. Derived from hematopoietic stem cells. Function: bone resorption. Stain positive for tartrate-resistant acid phosphatase (TRAP).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is the chemical composition of bone?", "answer": "Bone is composed of 60% inorganic matter, 30% organic matter, and 10% water. Inorganic phase: primarily hydroxyapatite (Ca10(PO4)6(OH)2) crystals; serves as mineral reservoir (calcium, phosphate, potassium, magnesium, sodium). Organic phase (osteoid): deposited by osteoblasts; primarily type I collagen (two alpha-1 chains + one alpha-2 chain forming right-handed helix); undergoes hydroxylation, glycosylation, and cross-linking by lysyl oxidase (copper-dependent enzyme). Bone strength derives from interactions between collagen fibers and inorganic minerals.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Compare primary and secondary (callus) bone repair. When does each occur?", "answer": "Primary bone repair: direct cortical healing WITHOUT cartilaginous intermediate (similar to intramembranous ossification). Requires anatomic reduction with rigid internal fixation and minimal interfragmentary strain. Cutting cones of osteoclasts burrow through cortex, followed by MSC-derived osteoblasts creating new haversian systems. Woven bone â†’ lamellar bone over weeks to months. Secondary (callus) bone repair: healing WITH cartilaginous intermediate. Occurs in fractures treated with external/intramedullary fixation, casts, or untreated fractures. Three phases: inflammatory (7 days), reparative (weeks-months, callus formation with endochondral + intramembranous ossification), and remodeling (years, woven â†’ lamellar bone).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Describe the three phases of secondary (callus) bone healing.", "answer": "(1) Inflammatory phase (~7 days, peaks at 48 hours): hematoma forms providing fibrin scaffold and signaling molecules; platelets release PDGF and TGF-beta; neutrophils, lymphocytes, monocytes, and macrophages remove debris and stimulate angiogenesis. (2) Reparative phase (weeks to months, begins day 3-4): fracture callus forms from cartilage, woven bone, osteoid, fibrous tissue, and blood vessels; undergoes endochondral (week 2, cartilage calcification â†’ bone) and intramembranous ossification. (3) Remodeling phase (months to years): woven bone replaced by lamellar bone; osteoclasts resorb poorly located trabeculae; new bone forms along lines of stress via Wolff's law.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Define osteoinduction, osteoconduction, and osseointegration.", "answer": "Osteoinduction: process by which undifferentiated pluripotent cells are stimulated to differentiate into the osteoblast lineage and form new bone. Can occur naturally (fracture repair) or be induced by BMPs, growth factors, or bioactive materials. Osteoconduction: ability of a material to serve as a scaffold onto which bone cells can attach and grow; requires porosity for ingrowth of bone and fibrovascular tissue. Examples: allografts, calcium phosphate, collagen. Osseointegration: stable structural and functional connection between native bone and an implant without cartilaginous intermediate; requires bioinert (e.g., titanium) or bioactive implant surface; enhanced by surface roughness.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Compare cancellous and cortical bone grafts: properties, incorporation, and indications.", "answer": "Cancellous grafts: little immediate structural strength but HIGHER osteogenic, osteoinductive, and osteoconductive properties; rapidly incorporated and revascularized (~2 weeks) via creeping substitution; indicated for gaps <6 cm in non-stress-bearing areas. Sources: iliac crest, cranial diploe, proximal tibia, distal radius. Cortical grafts: provide IMMEDIATE structural support but limited osteogenic potential; slower incorporation (1-2 months); rely on plasmatic imbibition; can bridge defects up to 12 cm; require rigid fixation to prevent fracture. Used for onlay augmentation. Sources: fibula, rib, iliac crest.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is distraction osteogenesis? Describe its three stages and key parameters.", "answer": "Distraction osteogenesis is the formation of new bone by gradual controlled separation of osteotomized bone segments, pioneered by Ilizarov. Three stages: (1) Latency (1-7 days post-osteotomy): bone healing initiates, periosteal integrity restores, callus begins forming. Shorter in younger patients. (2) Activation/distraction: gradual separation by turning a screw at a predetermined rate, inducing membranous ossification. Mineralization starts 10-14 days from osteotomy fronts, proceeding centrally. (3) Consolidation: immature bone remodels into mature lamellar bone; period from end of distraction to device removal. Success requires: device stability, adequate latency, gradual distraction, and sufficient consolidation.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the three arterial systems supplying a long bone?", "answer": "(1) Diaphyseal nutrient artery: primary blood supply to the inner two-thirds of cortex and medullary cavity; enters through cortex and divides into ascending and descending medullary branches. (2) Metaphyseal and epiphyseal arteries: arise from arteries supplying adjacent joints; deliver blood to cancellous bone at the ends of long bones. (3) Periosteal arteries: supply the outer one-third of cortex. Blood flows centrifugally through bone (endosteum to periosteum) driven by high intramedullary pressure. These three systems interconnect extensively, providing redundancy.", "notes": "Bone vascular anatomy from Ch20"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "List the autologous bone graft donor sites and their key advantages and complications.", "answer": "Ilium (most common): large amount of corticocancellous bone; versatile; easily accessible. Complications: chronic pain, paresthesias (lateral femoral cutaneous nerve), gait abnormalities. Preserve ASIS by stopping 3 cm posterior. Calvarium: rapid revascularization due to rich diploic vessels; less resorption; ideal for craniofacial/orbital reconstruction. Risk: intracranial injury; stay >1 cm from coronal, >1.5 cm from sagittal suture. Rib: flexible, easy to contour; minimal cancellous bone; pneumothorax risk. Fibula: mainly used as vascularized transfer for mandible reconstruction. Tibia: limited to small cancellous amounts (e.g., alveolar grafting).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What seven principles should be followed when handling bone grafts to optimize survival?", "answer": "(1) Minimize air exposure time (ideally <1 hour to maintain cell viability). (2) Cover graft in blood-soaked sponge with moist saline to extend viability 4-6 hours. (3) Keep grafts cool â€” temperatures >42Â°C cause cell death. (4) Use antibiotic washes cautiously â€” they are also cellucidal. (5) Avoid dead space around the graft. (6) Place cancellous portion of graft in contact with cancellous bone in the bed. (7) Place graft in a previously prepared vascularized bed to increase survival.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is creeping substitution, and how does it differ between cancellous and cortical bone grafts?", "answer": "Creeping substitution is the process by which transplanted bone graft is gradually resorbed and replaced by new bone via vascular ingrowth. In cancellous grafts: occurs rapidly (~2 weeks) because the porous trabecular architecture allows quick vascular ingrowth; viable surface osteoblasts and endosteal cells contribute directly; serves primarily as osteoconductive scaffold. In cortical grafts: occurs slowly (1-2 months) because the dense structure limits vascular penetration; the graft relies on plasmatic imbibition to sustain outer osteocytes initially; replacement proceeds from outside inward; requires rigid fixation during the prolonged incorporation period.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the characteristics of an ideal bone substitute? Name three categories of bone substitutes.", "answer": "Ideal bone substitute characteristics: (1) chemically inert, (2) hypoallergenic/no foreign body reaction, (3) easily contoured, (4) stable and durable shape retention, (5) non-carcinogenic, (6) capable of incorporation into or replacement by living bone. Three categories: (1) Cement pastes: calcium phosphate cements (BoneSource, Norian) â€” malleable, set intraoperatively. (2) Osteoactive materials: bioactive glass (NovaBone) and demineralized bone matrix (DBM) â€” recruit and stimulate osteoprogenitor cells. (3) Prefabricated polymers: synthetic materials shaped prior to implantation. Additionally: the ideal ceramic should be biodegradable, macroporous, mechanically stable, osteoconductive, and suitable as a growth factor carrier.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are bone morphogenetic proteins (BMPs) and their clinical significance in bone repair?", "answer": "BMPs are members of the TGF-beta superfamily with at least 15 known isoforms. They are potent osteoinductive agents that stimulate mesenchymal cells to differentiate into osteoblasts. BMPs are expressed early in fracture repair by mesenchymal cells, osteoblasts, and osteoclasts. Clinical applications: exogenous recombinant BMPs (especially BMP-2 and BMP-7) can heal critical-sized bone defects, stimulate ectopic bone formation, and potentially accelerate fracture repair. BMP-2 combined with VEGF shows synergistic effects on bone formation. BMPs are delivered on carriers/scaffolds (collagen sponges, calcium phosphate) to the defect site.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Why are calvarial bone grafts preferred for craniofacial reconstruction? Describe the harvest technique.", "answer": "Calvarial grafts are ectomesenchymal with a rich diploic vascular system allowing rapid revascularization, less resorption, and better structural maintenance compared to endochondral bone grafts. Technique: coronal incision through scalp and galea; can harvest split-thickness (outer table only) or full-thickness; corticotomy must stay >1 cm from coronal suture and >1.5 cm from sagittal suture; be aware of perforating vessel posteriorly near sagittal suture. Indications: calvarial, midfacial, nasal, and orbital reconstruction. Limitation: split grafts may not be feasible in young children due to thin calvarium.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is the role of VEGF in bone repair, and how does it interact with other growth factors?", "answer": "VEGF is a potent regulator of both vasculogenesis and angiogenesis, critical for bone maturation and repair. Hypertrophic chondrocytes at growth plates express high levels of VEGF. Anti-VEGF antibodies inhibit vascular invasion and impair bone formation. VEGF acts synergistically with BMP-2: combined BMP-2 gene therapy + VEGF protein significantly increases bone formation compared to either alone. VEGF deficiency in osteoblast precursors leads to reduced bone mass and increased marrow fat (osteoporosis phenotype). HIF-1-alpha pathway couples angiogenesis with osteogenesis; skeletal angiogenesis may be rate-limiting for bone growth.", "notes": "Bone healing biology from Ch20; best fit under tissue healing differences"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What factors negatively affect fracture healing?", "answer": "Blood supply: disrupted vascularity impairs healing; angiogenesis is critical for bone repair. Motion: excessive movement at fracture site causes delayed/non-union, though controlled micromotion can enhance healing. Age: pediatric fractures heal faster than adult fractures due to superior angiogenic potential, more robust periosteum, and greater MSC activity. Other factors: infection, smoking, diabetes, radiation, malnutrition, corticosteroids. Specific to distraction osteogenesis: insufficient device stability, inadequate latency period, too-rapid distraction rate, and insufficient consolidation time all impair new bone formation.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Describe the Seddon and Sunderland classifications of nerve injury. What did Mackinnon add?", "answer": "Seddon (1943) â€” three types: (1) Neurapraxia: focal demyelination/conduction block; full recovery within 3 months. (2) Axonotmesis: direct axonal damage with intact basal lamina; Wallerian degeneration occurs but recovery is possible. (3) Neurotmesis: complete nerve transection; no spontaneous recovery. Sunderland â€” five degrees: 1st (neurapraxia), 2nd (axon damage, basal lamina intact, full recovery at 1mm/day), 3rd (axon + basal lamina damaged, partial recovery), 4th (neuroma-in-continuity, no recovery), 5th (complete transection, no recovery). Mackinnon added 6th degree: combination of different degrees of injury in different fascicles within the same nerve.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is Wallerian degeneration, and in which nerve injury types does it occur?", "answer": "Wallerian degeneration is the degeneration of the axon and myelin sheath DISTAL to the site of nerve injury. It occurs in axonotmetic (Sunderland 2nd-4th degree) and neurotmetic (5th degree) injuries, but NOT in neurapraxia (1st degree). The process involves: axonal fragmentation, myelin breakdown, Schwann cell proliferation to form bands of BÃ¼ngner (guides for regenerating axons), and macrophage recruitment to clear debris. It begins within hours and is largely complete by 3 weeks, which is why electrodiagnostic signs (fibrillations, positive sharp waves) may not appear until 3 weeks post-injury.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is the rate of nerve regeneration, and why is 'time is muscle' an important concept?", "answer": "Nerve regeneration occurs at a maximum rate of approximately 1 mm/day (or ~1 inch/month). 'Time is muscle' means that irreversible muscle atrophy occurs as early as one year after denervation â€” the motor endplates degenerate and fibrosis replaces muscle fibers. Therefore, the distance from the site of injury to the target muscle is the most important prognostic factor. 'Time is pathway' is also critical: with advancing time, the quality of cellular support (Schwann cells) for nerve regeneration along the pathway worsens. Patients can lose up to 70-80% of motor units before a clinical deficit is noted, due to collateral sprouting.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is the gold standard for nerve repair, and when should repair be performed?", "answer": "Primary neurorrhaphy (direct end-to-end repair) remains the gold standard. Timing: Sharp penetrating injuries with nerve deficit should be explored within 72 hours. Repair within 48 hours = primary repair. Delayed repair (2-7 days) requires freshening of nerve ends. After first week = secondary repair, with decreasing likelihood of achieving primary neurorrhaphy. For closed injuries (crush/traction), wait 3-4 months with serial clinical exam and EMG â€” if no motor unit potentials by 3-4 months, surgical exploration is warranted. The advantage of early repair: cleaner surgical field, distal stimulation still possible, topographic landmarks visible.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Compare the options for bridging a nerve gap: autograft, acellular allograft, conduit, and nerve transfer.", "answer": "Nerve autograft ('bronze standard'): contains Schwann cells + ECM scaffold; results decrease >6 cm; donor site morbidity/sensory loss. Sural nerve most common donor; alternatives include MABC (up to 28 cm). Acellular nerve allograft (ANA): retains 3D scaffold without immunogenicity; no donor morbidity; limited to small-diameter, non-critical, short gaps (â‰¤3 cm); no Schwann cells; expensive. Conduit (synthetic/biological): guides regeneration; limited to non-critical sensory deficits <3 cm; no Schwann cells or matrix. Nerve transfer: expendable donor fascicle reinnervates recipient closer to target; converts proximal to distal injury; faster recovery; requires knowledge of internal topography.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is the importance of tension in nerve repair, and how should it be managed?", "answer": "Excessive tension across a nerve repair increases scarring at the coaptation site and impairs axonal regeneration. In an uninjured nerve, just 15% strain reduces microvascular flow. Clinically, any tension is meticulously avoided. Management: (1) Mobilization of proximal/distal nerve ends can overcome gaps <5 mm. (2) If primary repair cannot be achieved tension-free, two neurorrhaphy sites (with interpositional graft) are preferable to one under tension. (3) Postural manipulation of the extremity to reduce tension is NOT recommended â€” it increases dehiscence risk and stiffness from immobilization. (4) Harvested nerve grafts should be 15-20% longer than the gap to ensure tension-free coaptation.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the advantages of nerve transfers over nerve grafting and tendon transfers?", "answer": "Advantages over nerve grafting: (1) Surgery performed outside the zone of injury (cleaner surgical field). (2) Converts proximal high-level injury to distal low-level injury, shortening regeneration distance. (3) Only one neurorrhaphy site (vs. two for graft). (4) Earlier functional recovery. Advantages over tendon transfers: (1) Can restore sensibility in addition to motor function. (2) A single transfer can reinnervate multiple muscle groups. (3) Does not disrupt muscle-tendon insertion/attachment, maintaining original function and tension. (4) Not limited to one function or straight line of pull. Synergistic nerve transfers are preferred for easier rehabilitation.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What is the supercharge end-to-side (SETS) nerve transfer technique, and when is it used?", "answer": "SETS involves transferring a donor nerve fascicle to the side of an injured nerve distally to provide early motor axons while awaiting proximal regeneration from a high-level injury. It does not sacrifice the injured nerve's potential for recovery. Used for: (1) Proximal Sunderland 2nd-3rd degree injuries where long regeneration distance means prolonged time to muscle reinnervation. (2) Severe cubital tunnel syndrome or high ulnar nerve injuries where some spontaneous recovery is anticipated. The distal anterior interosseous nerve (AIN) motor branch is commonly used as the donor for ulnar nerve SETS transfer.", "notes": "Nerve transfer technique from Ch21"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "How are electrodiagnostic studies (nerve conduction study and EMG) used to evaluate nerve injuries?", "answer": "Nerve conduction study: provides quantitative data â€” conduction velocity reflects myelination; CMAP (compound muscle action potential) and SNAP (sensory nerve action potential) amplitudes measure the number of functional axons. EMG: provides qualitative data on nerve-muscle unit function. Key timing: fibrillations and positive sharp waves from axonal injury don't appear until ~3 weeks post-injury (after Wallerian degeneration), so early studies are NOT useful except to document pre-injury pathology. Serial testing is critical: EMG changes precede clinical recovery by months. If no motor unit potentials (MUPs) by 3-4 months in closed injuries, surgical intervention is warranted.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What prognostic factors affect recovery following peripheral nerve injury?", "answer": "Patient factors: age (younger = better recovery), comorbidities. Injury factors: mechanism (sharp transection > crush > avulsion), location (distal injuries have better prognosis â€” shorter distance to target), degree of injury (Sunderland classification). Treatment factors: timing of repair (earlier = better), method of repair (tension-free > tension), alignment accuracy. Distance from injury to end-target muscle is the SINGLE most important prognostic factor (nerve regenerates at maximum 1 mm/day). Additional factors: Schwann cell senescence increases with graft length (poor outcomes >6 cm for autografts, >3 cm for allografts); 50% of regenerating axons may never reach the correct end-target.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Describe the techniques of nerve repair: epineurial vs perineurial. What suture size is optimal?", "answer": "Epineurial repair: preferred method; sutures placed through the outer epineurium to coapt nerve ends. External landmarks (longitudinal vessels, fascicular patterns) used for alignment. Fewest sutures needed for accurate alignment is recommended. Perineurial (fascicular) repair: individual fascicular groups are aligned and sutured through perineurium. Advantage: potentially better alignment. Disadvantages: extensive dissection and permanent intraneural sutures increase fibrosis. Clinical studies show both techniques are equally effective if fascicles are not overlapped. Optimal suture: 9-0 nylon for major peripheral nerves (10-0 snaps under tension, 8-0 pulls through tissue). Fibrin glue can supplement/replace sutures for tension-free repairs.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the beneficial characteristics of autologous fat grafts, and what cell types are present in grafted fat?", "answer": "Beneficial characteristics: low donor site morbidity, procedural simplicity, low cost, results in living autologous tissue, and bioactive properties. Cell types present in cannula-harvested adipose tissue: mature adipocytes, adipose-derived stem cells (ASCs)/preadipocytes, fibroblasts, vascular endothelial cells, pericytes, and various immune cells. The stromal vascular fraction (SVF) â€” the non-adipocyte cellular component â€” contains ASCs that improve graft survival through angiogenic properties and have applications in tissue engineering and regenerative medicine.", "notes": "Fat grafting basics from Ch22"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Describe the Coleman method of structural fat grafting: the three key steps and their principles.", "answer": "(1) Harvesting: gentle extraction using blunt-tip cannula (3-4 mm) with minimal suction to preserve adipocyte architecture; any depot can be used (abdomen, love handles, thighs). Infiltrate with tumescent solution (0.2% lidocaine with 1:200,000 epinephrine, 1:1 superwet ratio). (2) Refinement: centrifugation at 3000 rpm (1200 g) for 3 minutes in 10 mL syringes; remove aqueous layer (blood/anesthetic) from bottom and oil from top; preserves viable fat with near-normal cellular enzyme activity. (3) Placement: inject small aliquots through 17-gauge blunt Coleman cannula in multiple tissue planes during cannula withdrawal; maximize surface area contact with surrounding tissue for revascularization.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "Why is fat placed in small aliquots during fat grafting, and what happens when large globules are injected?", "answer": "Small aliquots maximize the contact surface area between grafted fat and surrounding tissue, allowing revascularization from the recipient bed â€” similar to skin graft survival, fat grafts depend on initial diffusion and then neovascularization. Large globules result in central necrosis (the center is too far from blood supply for diffusion), with subsequent resorption and volume loss, or formation of oil cysts and calcifications. Fat should be built up with tiny parcels rather than large deposits that are molded afterward. Molding can displace fat or cause necrosis.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are adipose-derived stem cells (ASCs), and what is their clinical significance?", "answer": "ASCs are multipotent stem cells found within adipose tissue, surrounding blood vessels and in the connective tissue framework. They are isolated from the stromal vascular fraction (SVF) via enzymatic collagenase digestion (~2-5 x 10^5 nucleated SVF cells per gram of fat). ASCs can differentiate into multiple mesenchymal lineages (adipose, bone, cartilage, muscle) and even ectodermal/endodermal lineages. Clinical significance: (1) improve fat graft survival through angiogenic properties, (2) have regenerative effects on damaged/irradiated tissue, (3) do not express MHC-II (potential for immunomodulation), (4) being researched for tolerance induction in vascularized composite transplantation.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What is the oncologic safety evidence for fat grafting to the breast after cancer surgery?", "answer": "Clinical evidence supports safety: systematic reviews of >3600 patients show fat necrosis is the most common complication (4.4%), biopsy of subsequent lumps needed in 2.7%, and meta-analyses show NO significant difference in oncologic event rates between fat-grafted and non-fat-grafted groups. Local recurrence rates (~2.2%) are LOWER than baseline breast cancer recurrence rates (5.2-10.6%). Fat grafting does not interfere with cancer surveillance. HOWEVER, basic science studies show strong ASC-cancer cell interactions in vitro â€” this discrepancy is attributed to use of immortalized cell lines (from distant metastases) that do not represent primary cancer behavior. The ASPS originally banned breast fat grafting in 1987 but reversed this position.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the indications for fat grafting in reconstructive surgery?", "answer": "Reconstructive indications: (1) Facial rejuvenation and volume restoration. (2) Breast reconstruction after cancer surgery (lumpectomy defects, implant replacement, total breast reconstruction). (3) Mitigating radiation damage â€” irradiated tissue can be restored to more normal consistency/texture. (4) Post-traumatic deformities and scar contracture improvement. (5) Congenital anomalies (hemifacial microsomia, Treacher Collins syndrome). (6) Burn injury reconstruction. (7) Breast capsular contracture. (8) Amputee stump remodeling for prosthetic fit. (9) Iatrogenic deformities from prior cosmetic surgery. Fat grafting has regenerative effects: downregulates TGF-beta pathways in scarred tissue.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What are the complications of fat grafting, and what is the expected retention rate?", "answer": "Average retention rate: ~63% at 9 months (varies between individuals â€” some are 'good responders,' others are 'poor responders'). Unpredictable resorption is the most significant risk. Complications: fat necrosis, oil cyst formation, calcification, contour irregularities (excess fat visible as lumps under thin skin), overcorrection, scarring. Rare but serious: fat embolism from intravascular injection, allergic reaction to local anesthetic, perioperative bleeding, blood clots, infection. Multiple sessions are often required. Weight loss after grafting leads to volume loss. Unwanted parcels are difficult to remove.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "How does fat grafting differ at different tissue levels, and what effects does placement depth achieve?", "answer": "Subdermal: improves skin quality, decreases wrinkling, reduces pore size, may reduce scarring. Requires caution â€” surface irregularities are more apparent, especially under thin skin (e.g., lower eyelid). Supraperiosteal: changes shape related to underlying bony skeleton; used for skeletal augmentation effects. Intramuscular: builds bulk and volume. The surgeon determines placement level based on desired effect. Fat is deposited in small aliquots during cannula withdrawal, with multiple passes in multiple tissue planes. As tissue quality improves after initial grafting, subsequent sessions may achieve even better results.", "notes": "Fat grafting technique details from Ch22"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue types and healing differences", "question": "What early research by Peer established about fat graft survival, and how does this inform modern technique?", "answer": "Lyndon Peer (1950s) systematically studied transplanted fat and demonstrated: (1) Fat grafts lose about 45% of weight and volume at one year. (2) Surviving fat cells maintain their native volume. (3) Improper handling decreases graft survival. (4) Graft SIZE affects survival â€” a single walnut-sized graft loses volume more rapidly than multiple smaller grafts of similar total weight, because smaller grafts have greater surface area for revascularization. (5) Revascularization is essential for graft survival. These findings directly inform Coleman's principles: gentle handling, small aliquot placement in multiple planes, and maximizing surface area contact with vascularized tissue.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "Define an angiosome. What are the two types of connections that link adjacent angiosomes?", "answer": "An angiosome is a composite three-dimensional block of tissue (skin, muscle, bone, and other soft tissues) supplied by a single source (segmental or distributing) artery and its accompanying vein(s). Adjacent angiosomes are linked by: (1) Reduced-caliber choke anastomotic vessels â€” the most common connection, featuring narrowed arteries matched by avalvular (oscillating) veins that allow bidirectional flow. (2) True anastomoses â€” vessels that connect adjacent territories WITHOUT reduction in caliber. True anastomoses are most common along cutaneous nerves or in areas of mobile skin. The body consists of approximately 40-61 angiosomes (depending on subdivisions) that fit together like a jigsaw puzzle.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What are the two types of cutaneous perforators? How do they differ in course and relative proportion?", "answer": "Direct cutaneous perforators (~40%): Pass between deep tissues before piercing the deep fascia; their main destination is the skin. They tend to be larger in diameter with larger vascular territories (e.g., circumflex scapular artery). Subtypes include direct cutaneous (axial) vessels and septocutaneous vessels that follow intermuscular septa. Indirect cutaneous perforators (~60%): Emerge from the deep fascia as terminal branches of arteries that primarily supply muscles and other deep tissues. The majority are musculocutaneous perforators that pass through muscle before reaching the skin. There are approximately 400 cutaneous perforators in the human body (diameter â‰¥0.5 mm).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "List and explain the key anatomic concepts related to flap design (Box 23.1).", "answer": "(1) Vessels follow the connective tissue framework of the body â€” fundamental to fasciocutaneous/septocutaneous flap design. (2) Arteries radiate from fixed to mobile areas; veins converge from mobile to fixed areas â€” perforators emerge where skin is anchored to deep fascia. (3) Vessels 'hitchhike' with nerves â€” basis for neurovascular flaps. (4) Vessel size and orientation are products of tissue growth and differentiation. (5) Vessels interconnect to form a continuous 3D network of vascular arcades. (6) Vessels obey the law of equilibrium â€” if one vessel is small, its neighbor is reciprocally large. (7) Vessels have a relatively constant destination but variable origin. (8) Venous networks consist of linked valvular and avalvular channels. (9) Muscles are prime movers of venous return.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "Explain the 'law of equilibrium' as it applies to vascular anatomy. Give a clinical example.", "answer": "The law of equilibrium (described by Debreuil-Chambardel and Salmon) states that the anatomical territories of adjacent arteries bear an inverse (reciprocal) relationship to each other â€” if one vessel is small, its partner is large to compensate, and vice versa. Yet they combine to supply the same region. Clinical example: The superficial inferior epigastric artery (SIEA) and the deep inferior epigastric artery (DIEA) perforators to the lower abdomen. When the SIEA territory is large, the DIEA perforator territory is relatively smaller, and vice versa. This is clinically important: if a large superficial inferior epigastric VEIN is noted, the drainage of the inferior portion of the DIEAP flap may depend on the superficial venous drainage system.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What is the delay phenomenon? Describe the physiologic mechanism and time course.", "answer": "The delay phenomenon is the only documented method to increase skin flap survival. It involves strategic division of some vascular pedicles to the planned flap before the definitive transfer. Mechanism: When a flap is elevated/delayed, the reduced-caliber choke anastomotic vessels that link adjacent cutaneous perforator territories enlarge to match the caliber of the arteries they connect. This is an ACTIVE process involving multiplication and hypertrophy of cells in each layer of the vessel wall. Time course: Initial vasoconstriction immediately post-elevation â†’ gradual dilation during first 48 hours â†’ dramatic dilation from 48-72 hours (maximal effect) â†’ plateau then gradual continued increase. The effect is PERMANENT and IRREVERSIBLE. Without delay, one adjacent vascular territory can be safely captured; with delay, additional territories can be included.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What determines the survival length of a skin flap?", "answer": "Skin flap survival depends on: (1) The caliber and length of the dominant vessels on which the flap is based. (2) The caliber and span of the adjacent captured artery/arteries and vein(s). (3) The caliber and length of the connecting choke vessels. (4) An anatomically favorable or unfavorable venous return. (5) The volume of flap tissue. Where perforators are large and widely separated, each territory is large and a long flap can be raised safely (characteristic of loose skin areas of torso/scalp). Where perforators are small and close together (e.g., sole of foot), the viable length is short unless the source vessel is included. Flap survival can be extended by strategic delay procedures and by including the underlying source vessels through intramuscular/intermuscular dissection.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "Why should deep fascia be included in flaps of the extremities but is unnecessary in flaps of the torso?", "answer": "In the extremities (and scalp), the skin is relatively fixed to the deep fascia, and the dominant cutaneous vessels course ON or adjacent to the deep fascia for considerable distances â€” they 'hug' the fascial surface. Therefore, including the deep fascia in a fasciocutaneous flap preserves these vessels and ensures reliable perfusion. In the loose skin areas of the torso (e.g., over pectoralis major, iliac fossa, breast), the direct cutaneous vessels course only briefly near the deep fascia before being 'plastered to' the undersurface of the subcutaneous fat. They pierce the fat obliquely and travel within the integument for long distances in the subdermal plexus. Therefore, the deep fascia is unnecessary in torso flaps because the major cutaneous vessels have already left its surface.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What is a propeller flap? Describe its design principles.", "answer": "A propeller flap is a local island fasciocutaneous flap based on a single dissected cutaneous perforator. The flap is likened to the blades of a propeller â€” it has two 'blades' of unequal length on either side of the perforator. Design: The largest adjacent uninjured perforator to the wound is identified (often with Doppler); the longer blade covers the wound while the shorter blade covers the donor site. Key principles: (1) The perforator must not be injured during elevation. (2) The deep fascia around the perforator must be released to prevent kinking during rotation. (3) Gentle tissue handling is critical. (4) The flap can be designed throughout the body in various orientations. The propeller concept is an extension of the perforator flap concept.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "How does the venous architecture affect flap design? Describe the three types of muscle venous drainage.", "answer": "Venous drainage parallels arterial anatomy but consists of linked valvular (directional) and avalvular (oscillating/bidirectional) segments. Where arterial choke vessels define arterial territories, they are matched by oscillating veins. If a flap's venous valves are oriented AWAY from the pedicle, drainage is 'anatomically unfavorable' (risk of congestion). Three muscle types by venous architecture: Type I â€” single venous territory draining in one direction (favorable regardless of skin paddle placement). Type II â€” two territories draining from an oscillating vein in opposite directions. Type III â€” three or more territories draining in multiple directions. For type II/III muscles, a distally-placed skin paddle may have valves oriented opposite to the pedicle drainage, creating unfavorable venous return.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What are the clinical implications of the angiosome concept for flap design?", "answer": "Three key clinical implications: (1) Each angiosome defines the safe anatomic boundary of tissue in each layer that can be transferred as a composite flap (skin + muscle, muscle + bone, etc.) on the source vessels. The adjacent angiosome territory can usually be safely captured. (2) The junctional zone between adjacent angiosomes occurs WITHIN muscles (not between them), so muscles provide important anastomotic bypass shunts if the main source artery or vein is obstructed. (3) Most muscles span two or more angiosomes and receive supply from each territory â€” this enables capture of a skin island from one angiosome by muscle supplied in the adjacent territory, providing the basis for musculocutaneous flap design.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What is the neurovascular classification of muscles (Types I-IV)? Give examples of each.", "answer": "Based on nerve supply pattern: Type I â€” single unbranched nerve entering the muscle (e.g., latissimus dorsi, extensor indicis, plantaris). Type II â€” single nerve that branches BEFORE entering the muscle (e.g., deltoid, gluteus maximus, trapezius, vastus lateralis, serratus anterior). Type III â€” multiple motor branches from the SAME nerve trunk (e.g., gastrocnemius, sartorius, tibialis anterior, subscapularis, triceps). Type IV â€” multiple motor nerves from DIFFERENT nerve trunks (e.g., rectus abdominis, internal oblique, digastric, erector spinae, levator scapulae). Clinical relevance: This classification helps determine whether a muscle can be subdivided into independent neurovascular functional units for partial muscle transfer while leaving viable muscle behind.", "notes": "Muscle classification from Ch23; best fit under flap vascular anatomy"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "Why is the anterior tibial compartment particularly vulnerable to compartment syndrome? How does angiosome anatomy explain this?", "answer": "The anterior tibial compartment is supplied EXCLUSIVELY by the anterior tibial artery â€” all muscles (tibialis anterior, extensor digitorum longus, extensor hallucis longus, peroneus tertius) lie in ONE territory. The compartment has rigid walls across which vascular connections are sparse. This is particularly true medially, where the tibia is subcutaneous â€” the only connections between anterior and posterior tibial arteries are through the periosteum and the cutaneous network. This isolated single-artery supply within a rigid fascial compartment makes these muscles most vulnerable to ischemia, explaining why the anterior compartment is most commonly affected in exercise-related compartment syndrome ('shin splints').", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What are the three methods of preoperative assessment of cutaneous perforators? Compare their advantages and limitations.", "answer": "(1) Handheld Doppler: Simple, inexpensive, portable; provides limited information; significant inter-observer variability; may detect background vessels; less reliable in obese patients. (2) Color duplex Doppler: Greater resolution; accurately detects vessel diameter and flow velocity; no IV contrast, lower cost, no radiation; requires trained technician. (3) CT angiography (CTA): Most accurate method; identifies perforators as small as 0.3 mm; provides detailed 3D information on perforator position, diameter, and course; enables grid-based reporting for communication between radiologist and surgeon. Disadvantages: cost, radiation exposure, contrast allergy risk, claustrophobia. CTA is more accurate than handheld Doppler. CTA has become the preferred modality, with proponents citing reduced operating time.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "How does the evolution from TRAM flap to DIEAP flap illustrate the progression of flap surgery?", "answer": "The evolution: Pedicled TRAM flap â†’ Free TRAM flap â†’ Muscle-sparing free TRAM flaps â†’ DIEAP (deep inferior epigastric artery perforator) flap. This progression reflects: (1) Greater understanding of the precise anatomy of musculocutaneous perforators. (2) Reduced donor site morbidity â€” the DIEAP flap preserves the entire rectus abdominis muscle and its fascia by dissecting the perforator through the muscle, eliminating the risk of abdominal wall hernia and weakness. (3) The perforator flap concept: large skin flaps can be raised reliably based on musculocutaneous perforators alone, gaining the advantage of large vessel size without unnecessary muscle bulk or function loss. The DIEAP flap is one of the core perforator flaps for breast reconstruction.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What is the perforator flap nomenclature system? Explain using the DIEAP flap as an example.", "answer": "The nomenclature system names all perforator flaps according to the source vessel supplying the flap. The letters 'AP' are added to indicate artery perforator. When the perforating vessels can pass through different muscles, a suffix with the muscle initials is added. For septocutaneous perforators, the suffix '-s' is used. Example: DIEAP-ra = Deep Inferior Epigastric Artery Perforator through Rectus Abdominis. Other examples: LCFAP-vl (lateral circumflex femoral artery perforator through vastus lateralis = anterolateral thigh flap), TAP-ld (thoracodorsal artery perforator through latissimus dorsi), SGAP-gm (superior gluteal artery perforator through gluteus maximus), PIOAP-s (posterior interosseous artery perforator, septocutaneous).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "Describe the vascular anatomy of the head and neck as it relates to flap design. What makes scalp flaps different from neck flaps?", "answer": "The head/neck has 13 angiosomes from branches of the external carotid, internal carotid, and subclavian arteries. The SMAS/galea/platysma layers form a rich continuous anastomotic vascular layer extending from occiput across the head and face to the neck. Key differences: Scalp â€” rich vascular arcades between occipital, postauricular, superficial temporal (external carotid) and supraorbital, supratrochlear, dorsal nasal (internal carotid) arteries. Most scalp veins are avalvular, so flaps can be based in any direction. Neck â€” blood supply is more sparse; main perforators emerge from fixed skin sites (borders of trapezius and SCM, along hyoid bone, clavicle); platysma provides the vascular link between external carotid (superiorly) and subclavian (inferiorly). The tongue has an avascular midline raphe with poor crossover, risking tip necrosis if ipsilateral lingual artery is sacrificed.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "What is the vascular significance of the soleus muscle in the lower leg?", "answer": "The soleus muscle has critical vascular significance because it receives large branches from the popliteal artery that LINK the branches of the posterior tibial and peroneal vessels within the muscle substance. This makes soleus an important anastomotic link in the leg. This explains Salmon's observation that ligation of the popliteal artery DISTAL to the take-off of its branches to the soleus had little effect on perfusion of the leg â€” the rich intramuscular anastomoses within the soleus provide collateral blood flow. By contrast, ligation of the popliteal artery PROXIMAL to the sural arteries has a major effect on distal leg blood supply because few muscle bellies cross the knee joint and the main anastomoses around the knee are extramuscular (geniculate vessels).", "notes": "Lower leg vascular anatomy from Ch23"}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "Name the core group of standard perforator flaps and their source vessels.", "answer": "(1) DIEAP flap (deep inferior epigastric artery perforator) â€” workhorse for breast reconstruction. (2) Anterolateral thigh (ALT) flap â€” based on descending branch of lateral circumflex femoral vessels through vastus lateralis; called the 'ideal free flap' for its versatility. (3) Submental artery flap (SMAP). (4) Posterior interosseous flap (PIOAP-s) â€” septocutaneous. (5) Thoracodorsal artery perforator flap (TAP-ld) â€” through latissimus dorsi. (6) Superior gluteal artery perforator flap (SGAP-gm). (7) Inferior gluteal artery perforator flap (IGAP-gm). Additionally, local perforator flaps are increasingly utilized for wound closure, providing good color match and contour while potentially avoiding free tissue transfer.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "Explain why pretibial lacerations have a high incidence of skin flap necrosis, using vascular anatomy.", "answer": "The subcutaneous periosteal surface of the tibia contains anastomoses between the posterior tibial and anterior tibial arteries. Most pretibial lacerations occur superficial to the periosteum and 'shear off' the cutaneous arteries that emerge from this periosteal plexus. Because the tibia is subcutaneous in this region (skin is directly fixed to periosteum/bone with no intervening muscle), the cutaneous blood supply relies on these periosteal vessels. When they are disrupted by the shearing mechanism of injury, the overlying skin flap loses its blood supply, resulting in the high incidence of traumatic skin flap necrosis in this area.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "Compare axial, random, fasciocutaneous, musculocutaneous, septocutaneous, and perforator flaps.", "answer": "Axial flap: based on a known named cutaneous artery providing reliable blood supply along the flap's axis. Random flap: based on unnamed vessels of the dermal/subdermal plexus without a specific axial vessel; survival limited by length-to-breadth ratios. Fasciocutaneous flap: includes deep fascia; vessels course on or adjacent to deep fascia (useful in limbs/scalp). Septocutaneous flap: based on vessels traveling along intermuscular septa to the skin (a subtype of direct cutaneous supply). Musculocutaneous flap: skin supplied by perforators that pass THROUGH underlying muscle; includes muscle bulk. Perforator flap: skin flap based on any cutaneous perforator (musculocutaneous or septocutaneous), with the perforator dissected free of surrounding tissue to spare muscle/function. All are fundamentally based on the same cutaneous vascular architecture described by Manchot and Salmon.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "How does the vascular anatomy of the forearm relate to safe harvest of a radial forearm flap?", "answer": "When the radial forearm flap is harvested, the only muscles lying solely within the radial artery angiosome are brachioradialis, ECRL, and ECRB (supplied by the radial recurrent branch). However, the radial recurrent branch has an excellent anastomosis with the profunda brachii artery. Therefore, dissection can proceed safely right up to the radial artery origin from the brachial artery with either division of the recurrent branch or inclusion with one of the 'mobile mass' muscles. By contrast, proximal dissection of the ulnar artery to its brachial origin is MORE dangerous â€” the flexor digitorum profundus and FCU are supplied solely by the ulnar artery and its interosseous branches, and collateral pathways are less developed. Most forearm muscles span at least two angiosomes, providing redundant blood supply.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Vascular anatomy and flap physiology", "question": "How does the concept 'vessels hitchhike with nerves' apply to flap design?", "answer": "Throughout the body, cutaneous nerves are accompanied by a longitudinal system of arteries and veins â€” either a single long artery or a chain-linked system of perforators joined by true anastomoses. This neurovascular relationship provides the basis for long axially-oriented neurovascular flaps with the added potential of providing sensation at the repair site. Examples: the saphenous neurovascular flap and sural flap (PontÃ©n's original long fasciocutaneous flaps), supraorbital/infraorbital/occipital neurovascular bundles in the head, intercostal neurovascular bundles on the torso. The veins accompanying nerves are frequently large 'venous freeways' (cephalic, basilic, saphenous systems). Many current 'axial' or 'fasciocutaneous' flaps are in fact neurovascular flaps.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "Describe the Mathes-Nahai classification of muscle flaps (Types I-V). Give an example of each.", "answer": "Type I â€” one vascular pedicle (e.g., tensor fascia lata, gastrocnemius, vastus lateralis). Type II â€” dominant pedicle + minor pedicle(s); most common pattern in human muscle (e.g., gracilis, soleus, sternocleidomastoid, trapezius, rectus femoris). Type III â€” two dominant pedicles from separate vascular sources; can be split (e.g., gluteus maximus, rectus abdominis, serratus anterior, temporalis). Type IV â€” segmental vascular pedicles; division of >2-3 pedicles risks distal necrosis (e.g., sartorius, tibialis anterior, extensor digitorum longus). Type V â€” one dominant pedicle + secondary segmental pedicles; can be elevated on either system, has two arcs of rotation (e.g., latissimus dorsi, pectoralis major).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What is the Mathes-Nahai classification of fasciocutaneous flaps (Types A, B, C)?", "answer": "Type A â€” direct cutaneous pedicle that courses initially beneath, then superficial to the deep fascia, providing numerous fasciocutaneous perforators. Long, relatively superficial course permits evaluation by palpation/Doppler. Often called 'axial' flaps (e.g., groin flap, scalp flaps, saphenous flap). Type B â€” septocutaneous pedicle coursing between major muscle groups in an intermuscular septum. Fairly constant in location (e.g., anterolateral thigh, radial forearm, lateral arm, scapular flaps). Type C â€” based on dominant musculocutaneous perforators entering the deep fascia, without incorporating the underlying muscle. Increasing pedicle length requires proximal dissection through muscle. This is the anatomic model for perforator flaps in microsurgical transplantation (e.g., DIEP, nasolabial flap).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What are the 'six Cs' of the complete flap classification system? Briefly explain each.", "answer": "(1) Circulation â€” the source of blood supply (direct vs. indirect vessels); the most important characteristic. (2) Constituents (composition) â€” the tissues included: skin, fascia, muscle, bone, nerve, viscera, etc. (3) Contiguity (destination) â€” local, regional, or distant (free). (4) Construction (flow) â€” unipedicle, bipedicle, antegrade, retrograde (reverse), turbocharged, supercharged, or arterialized venous. (5) Conditioning (preparation) â€” delay, tissue expansion, prefabrication, sensate/functional nerve coaptation, or none. (6) Conformation (shape) â€” special shapes, tubed, combined/compound flaps, or none. Default values (unipedicle, antegrade, no conditioning, no special conformation) can be omitted from the nomenclature.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What is the 'perforasome' concept? List the four major characteristics described by Saint-Cyr.", "answer": "The perforasome is the vascular territory of a single cutaneous perforator â€” an evolution from the angiosome (territory of a source vessel) to the perforator as the basic vascular unit for flap design. Four characteristics: (1) Each perforasome is linked with adjacent perforasomes by direct linking vessels (communicating directly between adjacent perforators) and indirect linking vessels (communicating through the subdermal plexus). (2) Flap design and skin paddle orientation should follow the direction of linking vessels â€” axial in the extremities, perpendicular to the midline in the trunk. (3) Filling occurs within perforasomes of the SAME source artery first, then to adjacent source arteries. (4) The mass vascularity of a perforator found adjacent to an articulation flows AWAY from that articulation.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "Define and differentiate: composite, conjoined, and chimeric compound flaps.", "answer": "Composite flap (solitary vascularization) â€” multiple tissue components (e.g., skin + muscle + bone) en bloc, all dependent on a single vascular source. Classic musculocutaneous and osteocutaneous flaps are examples. Conjoined flap (combined vascularization) â€” at least two anatomically distinct territories, each with independent vascular supply, joined by a common physical boundary. Subtypes: perforator-based or branch-based (with independent or common source vessels). Chimeric flap (combined vascularization) â€” multiple independent flaps each with independent vascular supply, but all pedicles linked to a larger common source vessel. Subtypes: perforator-based, branch-based, or fabricated (sequential â€” attached at terminus of source vessel, or internal â€” attached to an indigenous branch). Example: subscapular system chimeric flap combining scapular flap, latissimus dorsi, and serratus anterior.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What are the five types of perforators defined by the Gent consensus document? How do they differ surgically?", "answer": "Type 1 â€” Direct perforators: perforate the deep fascia ONLY (no traversal of other structural tissues). Type 2 â€” Indirect muscle perforators predominantly supplying subcutaneous tissues (pass through muscle but mainly feed skin). Type 3 â€” Indirect muscle perforators predominantly supplying muscle with secondary branches to subcutaneous tissues. Type 4 â€” Indirect perimysial perforators: travel within the perimysium between muscle fibers before piercing the deep fascia. Type 5 â€” Indirect septal perforators: travel through the intermuscular septum before piercing the deep fascia. Surgical significance: Type 1 requires only fascial dissection; Types 2-4 require intramuscular dissection of varying difficulty and duration; Type 5 requires septal dissection only (generally easier). These distinctions guide the technical approach and expected operative time.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What determines a muscle flap's arc of rotation? How is it inversely related to the number of vascular pedicles?", "answer": "Arc of rotation is determined by: (1) the extent of elevation of the muscle from its anatomic bed, (2) the ability of the muscle to reach adjacent areas without devascularization, (3) the number and location of vascular pedicles relative to the muscle's origin and insertion. The closer the dominant pedicle is to either the origin or insertion, the greater the arc of rotation. Arc of rotation is INVERSELY proportional to the number of pedicles: Type IV muscles (segmental pedicles like sartorius) have limited arc because dividing pedicles risks distal necrosis. Type V muscles (like latissimus dorsi, pectoralis major) have the WIDEST arc â€” their dominant pedicle is near the insertion with additional segmental pedicles near the origin, giving two arcs of rotation (standard arc on dominant pedicle, reverse arc on segmental pedicles).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "Compare the reconstructive ladder, reconstructive triangle, and reconstructive elevator concepts.", "answer": "Reconstructive ladder (1982) â€” step-ladder approach from simple to complex: direct closure â†’ skin graft â†’ local flap â†’ distant flap â†’ microvascular flap â†’ tissue expansion. Limitation: assumes simpler is always better; does not consider form and function. Reconstructive triangle â€” emphasizes selecting a technique that safely achieves form AND function. Three sides: flaps, microsurgery, and tissue expansion, balanced by safety, form, and function considerations. Reconstructive elevator (Gottlieb & Krieger) â€” the surgeon 'jumps to the most appropriate floor' based on specific requirements of the patient, wound, and circumstances rather than climbing sequentially. A simpler option may not produce optimal results. Requires creative thought to achieve the best form and function. This paradigm does not eliminate the ladder concept but replaces it for modern reconstruction.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap physiology", "question": "What is the no-reflow phenomenon? Describe its pathogenesis and clinical significance.", "answer": "The no-reflow phenomenon is the failure to restore blood flow to ischemic tissue despite successful restoration of arterial inflow. After prolonged ischemia, the point of irreversibility is reached (~12 hours) and the flap cannot be salvaged. Pathogenesis: (1) Ischemia causes swelling of endothelial and parenchymal cells, narrowing capillary lumens. (2) Intravascular aggregation of blood cells occurs. (3) Intravascular fluid leaks into interstitial space causing edema. Three mechanisms: (1) Oxygen-derived free radicals damage endothelial and parenchymal cell membranes. (2) Cell membrane damage allows Ca2+ influx causing intracellular overload. (3) Altered arachidonic acid metabolism: decreased vasodilating/antithrombotic PGI2 production by endothelium and increased vasoconstricting/thrombotic TXA2 by platelets. Clinical: tPA injected into the flap artery may help by dissolving microvascular clots, but once true no-reflow is established, the flap cannot be salvaged.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap physiology", "question": "What are the common causes of flap failure? Which is the most common?", "answer": "Technical error is the MOST COMMON cause of flap failure. Mechanical/technical causes include: (1) Kinking of the pedicle. (2) Pressure on the pedicle from tight dressings or an insufficiently wide tunnel. (3) Damage to the pedicle during dissection. (4) Over-tightness of closure. (5) Overstretching of the flap. (6) Placing the drain too close to the pedicle (negative pressure can compress it). Pathophysiologic causes include: vasospasm and thrombosis from surgical trauma, insufficient distal vascularity, and the no-reflow phenomenon. Vasoactive substances released during surgical trauma include norepinephrine (sympathetic nerves), thromboxane A2, leukotriene B4, and serotonin (platelets), and hemoglobin (red blood cells) â€” all causing vasoconstriction. Traumatized endothelium decreases synthesis of vasodilating prostacyclin and nitric oxide (EDRF/NO).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap physiology", "question": "Explain the difference between supercharging and turbocharging a flap.", "answer": "Supercharging: Using an EXTERNAL (unrelated/distant) vascular source to augment either the inflow or outflow of a flap in addition to its original vascular source. Analogy: using an external power source to boost the engine. Example: A superiorly pedicled TRAM flap salvaged by anastomosing a thoracic or upper extremity vascular source to the CONTRALATERAL deep or superficial inferior epigastric vessels. Turbocharging: Using the flap's own MAIN vascular source to connect to an additional pedicle from the SAME flap, creating direct flow to the vascular territory of the connected branch. Analogy: using the engine's own exhaust for additional power. Example: Directly connecting the ipsilateral and contralateral deep inferior epigastric vessels of a TRAM flap to improve the vascular supply to the whole flap.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What is an arterialized venous flap? Describe the three theories of survival and the Woo classification.", "answer": "An arterialized venous flap uses a subcutaneous vein for BOTH arterial inflow and venous outflow â€” replacing the normal artery â†’ capillary â†’ vein pathway. Advantages: no donor site artery needed, very thin harvest, rapid elevation. Three survival theories: (1) A-V shunting â€” retrograde flow from venous system to arterial system via paralyzed arteriovenous shunts. (2) Reverse flow â€” flow from venules into capillaries. (3) Capillary bypass â€” flow through venous system without entering arterial side until neovascularization. Woo classification: Type I â€” 'through-and-along-valve' with straight or Y-shaped pattern (mimics standard vein graft flow). Type II â€” 'against-valve' with arterial inflow against valve through afferent vein (reversed Y or H pattern). Type III â€” mixed pattern, venous outflow drains through efferent veins against intravenous valves. Commonly used for hand/finger soft tissue reconstruction.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What is a retrograde (reverse) flow flap? Give three clinical examples.", "answer": "A retrograde flow flap is one in which the orthograde (antegrade) pedicle is ligated proximally, and the flap survives on reverse flow through the distal portion of the major pedicle, via anastomotic connections. Examples: (1) Distally based radial forearm flap â€” relies on retrograde flow through the deep palmar arch, with rotation point at the wrist; useful for hand reconstruction. (2) Reverse sural flap â€” sural artery/nerve ligated proximally, flap survives on retrograde flow from the peroneal artery via distal anastomoses; covers heel, ankle, and dorsum of foot. (3) Reversed first dorsal metacarpal artery flap â€” for hand reconstruction. Disadvantages: risk of venous congestion (despite venous connections); increased complications in patients with venous insufficiency or advancing age; poor cosmesis of donor site (often requires skin graft).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "Compare the advantages and disadvantages of muscle/musculocutaneous flaps versus fasciocutaneous/perforator flaps.", "answer": "Muscle/musculocutaneous ADVANTAGES: reliable specific pedicles, pedicle often outside zone of injury, provides bulk for deep defects, malleable, resistant to bacterial inoculation, often one-stage, can restore motor/sensory function. DISADVANTAGES: donor site function loss, aesthetically undesirable donor site, excessive bulk, muscle atrophy over time, contour deformities. Fasciocutaneous/perforator flap ADVANTAGES: thin and pliable, reliable blood supply, minimal functional donor morbidity, muscle-sparing, ability to restore sensation, many donor sites, reduced donor morbidity, improved recovery. DISADVANTAGES: lack of bulk for deep defects, technically more challenging (pedicle dissection, often requires microvascular techniques), size limitations, arc of rotation sometimes limited, may require skin graft closure, steep learning curve, variable perforator anatomy.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What are the five elevation planes for perforator flaps? How do they differ in thickness?", "answer": "From deep to superficial: (1) Subfascial â€” immediately under and including the deep fascia (same as fasciocutaneous structure); thickest flap. (2) Suprafascial â€” immediately above and excluding the deep fascia. (3) Superthin â€” elevated on the superficial fascia (fascia-like film layer between deep and superficial fat). (4) Ultrathin â€” elevated on a fascia-like pseudofascia within the superficial fat layer. (5) Subdermal (pure skin perforator/PSP) â€” thinnest flap, elevated just beneath the dermis. The subcutaneous fat is divided into a superficial fat layer (small lobules) and a deep fat layer (large lobules) separated by the superficial fascia. Each plane has unique properties and challenges; the surgeon must understand the anatomy and potential pitfalls to safely elevate at each level.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap physiology", "question": "What are the two theories explaining the delay phenomenon, and what is the clinical technique?", "answer": "Two theories: (1) Ischemic tolerance â€” delay acclimatizes the flap to ischemia through adaptive metabolic changes at the cellular level, allowing survival with less blood flow. (2) Vascular reorganization â€” delay improves vascularity by increasing flow through pre-existing vessels and reorganizing blood flow patterns to more ischemic areas. Both mechanisms likely contribute. Clinical technique: Standard delay â€” incisions at the periphery of the planned cutaneous territory with minimal/partial undermining, then closure. Flap elevated after 10-14 days (blood flow maximizes at 1 week). Strategic delay â€” pedicle ligation: incisions at the border of planned flap, dissection to reach and divide selected pedicles, enhancing perfusion through remaining pedicles. Advocated for high-risk patients (smokers, obese, irradiated). Disadvantages: requires preliminary operation, risk of inadvertent pedicle injury, scar tissue may impair subsequent manipulation.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Autologous reconstruction options", "question": "Describe the TRAM flap for breast reconstruction: vascular anatomy, advantages, disadvantages, and contraindications.", "answer": "Vascular anatomy: Rectus abdominis is Type III muscle with two dominant pedicles â€” superior epigastric artery (superiorly based) and deep inferior epigastric artery (inferiorly based). Transverse skin island placed between umbilicus and pelvis. Advantages: (1) Sufficient bulk without prosthetic implant. (2) Acceptable suprapubic horizontal donor scar. (3) Single operative position. (4) Large skin dimensions. (5) Simultaneous abdominoplasty with direct closure. Disadvantages: Risk of abdominal hernia/weakness after rectus harvest. Relative contraindications: extremely thin patient, nulliparous woman in childbearing years, history of abdominal hernia, extreme obesity, heavy smoker, lower abdominal scars. Absolute contraindication for superiorly based pedicled TRAM: prior division of superior pedicle (e.g., from superior transverse laparotomy incision).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Autologous reconstruction options", "question": "Trace the evolution of abdominal-based breast reconstruction from TRAM to DIEP flap. What drove each step?", "answer": "Evolution: (1) Pedicled TRAM flap (Hartrampf 1982) â€” entire rectus muscle transferred on superior epigastric pedicle to carry skin island. Issue: sacrifice of entire rectus muscle, abdominal weakness/hernia risk. (2) Free TRAM flap â€” entire rectus transferred on inferior pedicle (dominant blood supply) with microsurgical anastomosis. Improved: perfusion (dominant pedicle used). (3) Muscle-sparing free TRAM â€” partial rectus harvest preserving a portion of muscle. Improved: reduced abdominal wall morbidity. (4) DIEP flap (Koshima/Allen) â€” skin and fat flap based on a single musculocutaneous perforator dissected through the rectus without taking any muscle or fascia. Improved: COMPLETE muscle and fascial preservation, eliminates hernia/weakness risk. Driving force at each step: greater understanding of perforator anatomy â†’ ability to preserve more muscle â†’ reduced donor site morbidity while maintaining reliable flap perfusion.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What is the free-style perforator flap approach? How does it differ from the classic approach?", "answer": "Classic approach: the source vessel is identified first, then dissection proceeds toward the perforator (from deep to superficial). The flap is designed around a known perforator anatomy. Free-style approach: the skin island is selected first based on the defect requirements, then the most appropriate perforator WITHIN that chosen skin island is identified (often with Doppler), and dissection proceeds from the perforator proximally toward the source vessel. This reverses the classic sequence. Advantages: maximum freedom in flap design â€” not limited to a specific donor site or source artery; can handle unexpected variations; any perforator anywhere on the body can potentially be used. The supermicrosurgery extension (perforator-to-perforator anastomosis) further simplifies this by allowing short-pedicle flaps without extensive proximal dissection. A learning curve is required to be comfortable with this approach.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What are the commonly transferred vascularized bone flaps? Name the source artery for each.", "answer": "(1) Fibula â€” based on the peroneal artery (multiple arcuate branches along shaft + nutrient vessel to mid-third); head/epiphysis supplied by anterior tibial artery branches. Most widely used bone flap, especially for mandible and long bone reconstruction. Can include skin island. (2) Iliac crest â€” based on deep circumflex iliac artery. (3) Scapula â€” based on circumflex scapular artery or thoracodorsal artery. (4) Radius â€” based on radial artery. (5) Calvarium â€” based on superficial temporal artery or occipital artery. (6) Medial femoral condyle (genicular osseous-periosteal flap) â€” based on articular branch of descending genicular artery; provides periosteum + thin cortical bone for fracture non-union, avascular necrosis, and small bone defects of the hand.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What is a keystone flap? Describe its design and blood supply.", "answer": "The keystone flap (described by Behan) is a curvilinear-shaped trapezoidal-design local flap, essentially two V-Y advancement flaps along the long axis of the flap. The longitudinal tension is released, creating laxity and redundancy in the midportion, allowing horizontal movement toward the defect with minimal tension. Blood supply: because of the large size of the flap, identification of a specific vascular source is NOT necessary. It is presumed to have various blood supplies from perforators entering from the deep fascia (essentially a random-pattern concept applied with large flap dimensions). However, when perforators ARE identified using a Doppler, it can be called a 'keystone-design perforator island flap.' Used for larger wounds on the trunk and extremities when a simple random flap would be insufficient.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap monitoring and postoperative care", "question": "What are the key principles of postoperative flap management and monitoring?", "answer": "Positioning: Avoid pressure on flap base; elevate the flap area when possible; use air-fluidized beds for spinal cord patients. Avoid constricting bandages near pedicle. For head/neck free flaps: NOTHING placed circumferentially around head or neck (no nasal cannulas, oxygen masks, glasses, tracheostomy collars). Immobilization: Splint extremities proximal and distal to inset; avoid circular casts. Monitoring: Clinical observation (skin color, turgor, temperature, capillary refill, pinprick). Adjunctive: laser flowmeter, implantable Doppler, O2 probes, duplex scans. Ideal monitor: reliable, reproducible, sensitive, cost-effective, user-friendly, continuous. Anticoagulation: Evidence shows anticoagulants do NOT make a significant difference in flap outcome; common regimens (aspirin, heparin, dextran) used by many surgeons. Dextran may actually be detrimental. Mobilization: Most patients ambulatory by POD1 (except perineum/lower extremity); extremity elevation/immobilization for 10 days then non-weight-bearing for 6 weeks.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What is the clinical significance of the Mathes-Nahai muscle classification for flap selection?", "answer": "The classification directly determines: (1) Whether the muscle can survive as a flap â€” Type I (single pedicle) is most reliable; Type IV (segmental) is most precarious with limited arc. (2) Arc of rotation â€” Type V muscles (latissimus, pectoralis major) have widest arc due to pedicle location near insertion. Type IV (sartorius) has most limited arc. (3) Ability to split the muscle â€” Type III muscles (gluteus maximus, rectus abdominis) can be split into two independent segments on separate pedicles, allowing partial harvest while preserving function. (4) Reverse arc of rotation â€” Type V muscles can be elevated on either dominant or segmental pedicles, providing two different arcs. (5) Identifying which pedicle to preserve â€” knowing the dominant vs. minor pedicle guides safe flap elevation and predicts viability after dividing specific vessels.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "How are visceral tissues classified as flaps? Give examples and their Mathes-Nahai type.", "answer": "Visceral flaps fall into the muscle classification system: Jejunum â€” Type I (single vascular arcade); can transfer 7-25 cm on one pedicle; lumen diameter 3-5 cm; used for esophageal and pharyngeal reconstruction. Colon â€” Type I; 20-25 cm length with 8 cm lumen diameter; used for esophageal and vaginal reconstruction. When a longer segment extends beyond one arcade, two arcades (Type III pattern) are included. Omentum â€” Type III (based on either right or left gastroepiploic vessels); variable size up to 40x60 cm; used for extraperitoneal defects; has immunologic and angiogenic properties. The appendix (Type I on appendiceal artery) has been used for urethral and voice reconstruction. Laparoscopic harvest now reduces donor site morbidity. Donor site complications include abdominal wall infection and hernia.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "What is a nerve flap? How does it differ from a 'vascularized nerve graft'?", "answer": "A nerve flap is a sensory nerve harvested with its vascular supply intact, based on perforating vessels from a proximal source vessel. The nerve has: Extrinsic blood supply â€” arteriae nervorum arising from perforating vessels that enter the nerve intraneurally. Intrinsic blood supply â€” longitudinally oriented arterioles in the epineurium, perineurium, and endoneurium that communicate with the extrinsic arteriae nervorum. The term 'vascularized nerve graft' is a misnomer â€” since the nerve has its own defined vascular source, it is properly called a 'nerve flap.' Examples: superficial radial nerve flap (based on radial artery), saphenous nerve flap (proximally based on femoral artery branches, distally on saphenous artery), sural nerve flap (based on superficial sural artery). When the arterial supply is absent, the accompanying vein can be arterialized.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap classification", "question": "List the eight general guidelines for selecting a specific muscle flap for reconstruction.", "answer": "(1) The muscle should be ADJACENT to the defect (for local flaps). (2) Sufficient SIZE and BULK to cover the defect; finalize design only after complete debridement (defects are often larger than anticipated). (3) The muscle should be EXPENDABLE (synergistic muscles can compensate); otherwise use muscle-splitting techniques. (4) Vascular pedicle STATUS must be confirmed preoperatively (arteriography if prior surgery near pedicle, or if motor paralysis noted). (5) Donor site DEFORMITY must be considered (skin graft requirements, scar location preference). (6) Cutaneous territory must be sufficient SIZE and acceptable TEXTURE/match (non-hair-bearing if needed). (7) Select flaps capable of SENSORY or MOTOR restoration if required (e.g., serratus, rectus, latissimus). (8) Consider OSTEOMUSCULOCUTANEOUS flaps if vascularized bone is also needed. (9) The operation should be technically straightforward.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Flaps", "subtopic": "Flap physiology", "question": "What systemic factors increase the risk of flap complications and failure?", "answer": "Known risk factors: obesity, smoking, hypertension, immunosuppression, heart failure, diabetes, hypercoagulability, peripheral vascular disease, and chronic renal insufficiency. These affect both donor and recipient sites and increase rates of flap failure. However, with continued advances in microsurgical instruments and techniques, these risk factors have become less significant to flap survival outcomes. Nevertheless, they should be controlled preoperatively to minimize complications. Strategic delay (ligation of pedicles before definitive flap elevation) is advocated specifically for patients with risk factors for flap ischemia (smoking history, obesity, radiation therapy, abdominal scars). For flap design, preoperative CT angiography is the gold standard for imaging the vascular anatomy of both donor and recipient sites.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "Define microsurgery and supramicrosurgery. What vessel diameters does each address, and what are the primary clinical applications of supramicrosurgery?", "answer": "Microsurgery: surgical coaptation of small vessels (~1 mm diameter) under microscope magnification; also applies to nerves and lymphatics. Supramicrosurgery (Koshima): anastomosis of vessels ~0.5 mm diameter (range 0.3-0.8 mm). Supramicrosurgery applications: (1) lymphatic reconstruction (lymphaticovenular anastomosis), (2) perforator-to-perforator anastomosis/repair, (3) distal digital replantation. Supramicrosurgery requires extremely fine instruments, 11-0 to 12-0 sutures, and high-magnification microscopy.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "What suture sizes are used for microvascular anastomosis, and how is the choice determined by vessel diameter?", "answer": "9-0 nylon on 100 µm needle: vessels ≥2 mm diameter. 10-0 nylon on 70-100 µm needle: vessels 1-2 mm diameter. 11-0 nylon on 50-75 µm needle and 12-0 nylon on 50 µm needle: vessels <1 mm (supramicrosurgery). The choice is based on vessel wall thickness and diameter. Microneedles are typically three-eighths circle with round, tapered (most common), or spatula tips. Non-resorbable nylon is standard due to low tissue reactivity and knot-holding ability; polypropylene is an alternative preferred by some for better tissue sliding.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "Describe the microvascular anastomotic coupling device (Synovis COUPLER): mechanism, indications, contraindications, and patency rates.", "answer": "Mechanism: two disposable high-density polyethylene rings with 6-8 evenly spaced stainless-steel pins (0.16 mm diameter). Vessel ends are threaded through rings and impaled on pins in an everting fashion; rings are approximated via reusable applicator. Sizes: 1-4 mm ring diameter (vessels 0.8-4.3 mm). Patency rates: up to 100% (99.4% in 1000 consecutive venous anastomoses in breast reconstruction). Anastomotic time: 2-6 minutes. Advantages: fast, does not disturb intima. Contraindications: PVD, active radiation therapy, active infection, concurrent diabetes, corticosteroid therapy, thick-walled vessels that don't evert, diameter discrepancy >1.5:1, non-pliable vessels, arteries <1.5 mm. Primarily used for venous anastomoses but also effective for arterial.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "Compare end-to-end versus end-to-side microvascular anastomosis: indications, advantages, and patency outcomes.", "answer": "End-to-end: most common method using interrupted sutures. Simple, appropriate for most anastomoses. Preferred in atherosclerotic vessels (less plaque exposure). End-to-side: indicated when (1) significant vessel size or wall thickness discrepancy, (2) need to preserve distal circulation (single-vessel leg), (3) may be less prone to vasospasm in lower extremity. Technique: arteriotomy (triangular, elliptical, or longitudinal slit) in recipient vessel; stay sutures at heel and toe. Godina advocated this technique for higher success rates and technical simplicity. Patency: study of >2000 anastomoses showed both techniques equally effective when properly applied, approaching 100%. End-to-side venous anastomosis may have slightly higher success rate than end-to-end.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "What are the key principles of vessel preparation before microvascular anastomosis?", "answer": "(1) Inspect lumens for intimal tears/separation, thrombi, atherosclerotic plaques, friable calcified walls. (2) Remove debris by gentle irrigation or atraumatic removal with microforceps. (3) Cut back to healthy vessel if needed (inadequate debridement is a major cause of flap failure). (4) Trim adventitia 3-4 mm from anastomotic site to improve visualization and prevent adventitia falling into lumen (avoid overly aggressive stripping which causes vessel wall necrosis and false aneurysms). (5) Gently dilate lumens in two planes for 1 second to aid suturing, prevent vasospasm, and flush intraluminal blood. (6) Irrigate with heparinized saline; cover vessels with 2-4% lidocaine or 3% papaverine-soaked gauze to prevent desiccation and vasospasm.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "What techniques can be used to manage vessel size discrepancy during microvascular anastomosis, and up to what ratio can end-to-end repair handle?", "answer": "Mismatches up to 4:1 can be anastomosed end-to-end with sufficient skill. Techniques: (1) Gently stretch/dilate the smaller vessel to match, placing sutures further apart on larger vessel. (2) Fish-mouth incision on smaller vessel to increase circumference. (3) Oblique cut on smaller vessel (angle not >30° to avoid kinking). (4) Perform anastomosis distal to a side branch, opening the V-shape as vessel end. For discrepancy >3:1: consider (5) end-to-side anastomosis, (6) vein graft to graduate discrepancy, (7) use side branch of larger vessel as size match. Last resort: dilate smaller vessel maximally, suture as widely as possible, close remaining gap with oblique surgical clip to taper and minimize turbulence.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Flap monitoring and salvage", "question": "What is the gold standard for free flap monitoring? Describe the clinical signs assessed and a typical monitoring schedule.", "answer": "Gold standard: clinical observation by experienced nursing and medical staff. Signs assessed: (1) Color (pink = adequate arterial inflow; white/pale = arterial insufficiency; dark blue/purple = venous congestion). (2) Capillary refill (normal brisk; absent = arterial problem; instant/dark = venous congestion). (3) Turgor. (4) Surface temperature (difference of 1.8°C between flap and control is 98% sensitive and 75% predictive of vascular compromise; temp <30°C indicates failure). (5) Pinprick test for color and speed of bleeding if capillary refill unclear (scratch dermis only). Typical schedule: every 30 minutes for first 24 hours, 1-2 hourly for next 24 hours, then 4-hourly for next 48 hours. Minimum close monitoring for first 72 hours.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Flap monitoring and salvage", "question": "Compare the monitoring methods available for free flaps: implantable Doppler, hand-held Doppler, laser Doppler, and tissue oximetry.", "answer": "Hand-held pencil Doppler: most commonly used technology; applied over marked cutaneous perforator (away from pedicle to avoid false positives); noninvasive. Implantable Doppler: placed around pedicle vessel (most accurate on vein); useful for buried flaps and those without skin perforator; sensitive but HIGH false-positive rate causing unnecessary re-explorations; can differentiate arterial from venous thrombosis by signal pattern. Laser Doppler: measures reflected light waveforms from moving RBCs in capillaries; objective measurement; can distinguish venous obstruction from arterial occlusion; no false positives or negatives when interpreted by experienced clinicians. Tissue oximetry: identifies pulsatile flow and arterial saturation; has GREATEST impact on clinical decision-making — surgeons most willing to act on concerning oximetry findings. All are adjuncts to clinical monitoring, which remains the gold standard.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Flap monitoring and salvage", "question": "A free flap begins to show signs of compromise in the early postoperative period. Outline the systematic approach to assessment and salvage.", "answer": "Step 1 — Address systemic factors at bedside: correct hypotension, hypovolemia, hypothermia, and sympathetic overdrive from pain. Step 2 — Address local factors: release compressive dressings, evacuate hematoma, loosen tight wound closure/release sutures. Step 3 — Reassess flap after corrections. Step 4 — If no improvement, bedside vessel exploration: relieve twist/kink, assess anastomotic patency, open second pedicle vein for congestion. Step 5 — Prompt return to OR if thrombosis confirmed: resection and reanastomosis, or Fogarty balloon thrombectomy. Step 6 — Intraoperative thrombolysis (urokinase or tPA) for refractory cases. Step 7 — For venous congestion refractory to surgical salvage: medicinal leeches (Hirudo medicinalis), which inject hirudin anticoagulant and cause bleeding for up to 10 hours. Give prophylactic antibiotics against Aeromonas hydrophila with leech use. Monitor hemoglobin daily.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Thrombosis and anticoagulation in microsurgery", "question": "Compare the three most commonly used antithrombotic agents in microsurgery: heparin, dextran, and aspirin.", "answer": "HEPARIN: activates antithrombin III (deactivates factors II, IX, X, XI; indirectly V, VIII), reduces platelet aggregation, lowers blood viscosity, has direct vasodilatory properties. Most important for atherosclerotic/injured vessels and vein grafts. Used universally as irrigation solution. Risk: hematoma formation, HIT. DEXTRAN-40: polysaccharide volume expander; increases electronegativity of RBCs/platelets/endothelium (reduces aggregation), decreases factor VIII-Ag, reduces viscosity. Risks: anaphylaxis, volume overload, pulmonary/cerebral edema, acute renal failure; 3.9-7.2x increased systemic complications vs aspirin. ASPIRIN: inhibits cyclooxygenase, reduces thromboxane (vasoconstrictor/platelet aggregator). Low-dose (75 mg/day) selectively inhibits thromboxane while preserving endothelial prostacyclin. Less effective than heparin. Risks: gastric hemorrhage, renal failure, prolonged bleeding. No agent has definitive RCT evidence; protocols vary by surgeon preference.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Thrombosis and anticoagulation in microsurgery", "question": "Describe the pathophysiology of arterial vs venous thrombosis in free flaps: timing, mechanism, and presentation.", "answer": "ARTERIAL thrombosis: majority occur within first 24 hours; mechanism is platelet aggregation at the anastomotic site (white thrombus); presentation = pale/white flap, absent capillary refill, no Doppler signal, longitudinal (non-expansile) pulsation. VENOUS thrombosis: presents later (but most pedicle thromboses occur within 48 hours); mechanism is formation of fibrin clot (red thrombus); more often responsible for flap compromise than arterial thrombosis; presentation = congested/purple flap, rapid/dark capillary refill, engorged secondary veins, continuous dark bleeding from flap edges, blood column darker than recipient vessel. Risk of thrombosis greatest within first 48 hours, decreases to 10% after 72 hours. Anticoagulant goals: interfere with platelet function (arterial), counter thrombin effects on fibrinogen (venous), reduce viscosity/increase flow.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "What is vasospasm in microsurgery? Describe its incidence, causes, and treatment options.", "answer": "Incidence: 5-10% of microsurgical procedures. Timing: intraoperatively or up to 72 hours postop (intraoperative more problematic). Veins: less susceptible but harder to resolve and more detrimental once established. General causes: low core temperature (<36°C), hypotension, sympathetic response to pain, hypovolemia. Local causes: vessel trauma, tight adventitia, myogenic response to local hemorrhage, desiccation, vascular disease. Treatment: (1) Wait a few minutes for spontaneous resolution. (2) Pharmacologic — topical papaverine (30 mg/mL, phosphodiesterase inhibitor), lidocaine (2-4%, Na-Ca exchange pump), calcium channel blockers (verapamil, nifedipine, nicardipine — may be more effective than papaverine). (3) Mechanical — gentle dilation with blunt vessel dilator or needle holders. (4) Adventitial stripping (sympathectomy effect). (5) If intractable: aggressively resect vessel until normal vessel reached; may require vein graft or alternate recipient vessel.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Ischemia-reperfusion injury", "question": "Explain ischemia-reperfusion injury and the no-reflow phenomenon in free flap surgery.", "answer": "Ischemia-reperfusion (I/R) injury: after prolonged ischemia, reperfusion compounds the insult through buildup of oxygen free radicals during ischemic period. These cause: (1) cellular membrane damage through oxidizing/reducing potentials, (2) intense inflammatory reaction recruiting leukocytes, neutrophils, platelets, and cytokines (IL-1β, TNF-α), (3) suppression of protective molecules (nitric oxide synthase, prostacyclin, thrombomodulin), (4) increased complement C3 deposition, apoptosis, interstitial edema, decreased total antioxidant capacity. No-reflow phenomenon: severe I/R injury causes irreversible vasoconstriction; inability to reperfuse flap DESPITE PATENT anastomoses. Mechanism: ischemia-induced endothelial injury → cellular swelling → interstitial edema → exposed subendothelial collagen → platelet-leukocyte aggregation → reduced blood flow → thrombosis. Ischemic tolerance varies by tissue (most to least tolerant): skin > nerve > bone > muscle > intestine. Within composite flap, overall tolerance equals LEAST tolerant component. Ischemia beyond 3 hours increases risk.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Recipient and donor vessel selection", "question": "What are the principles for selecting and preparing recipient vessels in free flap surgery?", "answer": "Ideal recipient vessel: (1) healthy with soft wall and easily dissected vascular sheath, (2) away from zones of trauma, irradiation, inflammation, fibrosis, and scarring, (3) appropriate size with good flow, (4) adequate length for tension-free anastomosis. Assessing vessel quality: expansile pulsation suggests adequacy, confirmed by healthy spurting from divided vessel. If poor spurt with normotension: relieve vasospasm first, then cut back until healthy spurting encountered. Veins: should be at least as wide as flap vein (smaller causes bottle-neck effect). Test with flushing heparinized saline through catheter — low resistance confirms adequate drainage. Preoperative assessment: CTA/angiography indicated for abnormal distal pulses or history of trauma, DVT, longstanding diabetes, atherosclerosis. Perforating branches of main vessels can be used as recipients (breast, extremity reconstruction). After dissection, cover vessels with lidocaine/papaverine-soaked gauze.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "What are the indications for interpositional vein grafts in microsurgery, and what principles govern their use?", "answer": "Indications: (1) recipient vessel out of pedicle reach or under tension, (2) considerable size mismatch, (3) need to place anastomosis outside zone of injury/radiation, (4) re-explorations, (5) vessel-depleted neck. Principles: Harvest with loupe magnification; caliber should match vessels being anastomosed. Workhorse: great/lesser saphenous vein (advantages: length, two-team approach). Alternatives: cephalic vein, comitant veins of flap, volar forearm veins, dorsal foot veins. Critical: direction must ensure antegrade flow (valves present even in short segments) — mark proximal end with surgical clip. Hydrodilatation stretches graft to length, untwists vein, relieves vasospasm, reveals bleeding points. Anastomose open end first, release clamp to verify correct direction and non-redundant length. Arterial grafts have advantages (no valves, anatomical taper, similar wall thickness, more prostacyclin) but haven't shown significant superiority in microsurgery.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "Describe the patency tests used to assess microvascular anastomosis after completion.", "answer": "Clinical assessment: expansile pulsation = good (longitudinal pulsation in vessel's long axis = partial/complete thrombosis). Good venous flow with natural round diameter = patent vein (engorged and dark blood = thrombosed vein). Two formal tests: (1) UPLIFT TEST: gently hook up thin-walled vessel until blood column almost occluded; if patent, alternate filling and collapsing with each pulse is visible. (2) EMPTY-AND-REFILL TEST (Acland): occlude vessel distal to anastomosis, use second forceps to empty a segment by running it in direction of flow, release proximal forceps — immediate refill confirms patency; sluggish or absent refill = not patent. This test is more traumatic and should be performed preferably on veins not arteries (minimize spasm/intima separation). Side branches provide atraumatic alternative. Modern: ICG (indocyanine green) angiography via microscope-mounted infrared cameras or hand-held devices — easier and more accurate.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Free flap principles and planning", "question": "What patient factors should be evaluated preoperatively for free flap surgery, and which are true contraindications?", "answer": "Age: NOT a contraindication (outcomes comparable in extremes of age, though elderly have more medical complications). Smoking: does not significantly affect vessel patency or flap survival, but increases donor site complications; advise stopping 4 weeks preoperatively. Obesity (BMI >30): increases hemorrhage, hematomas, total flap loss, seromas, donor site complications (TRAM data). Diabetes: NOT an independent risk factor for flap failure, but 1.76x increased perioperative complications. Alcohol: withdrawal related to increased flap failure; identify and treat high-risk patients prophylactically. Liver cirrhosis: risk factor for perioperative complications; higher risk of neck hematoma with advanced disease. Immunosuppression: prednisone correlates with operative morbidity. Collagen vascular diseases (Raynaud, SLE, scleroderma): increased DVT risk but NOT increased microvascular thrombosis risk with standard anticoagulant prophylaxis. Irradiated recipient site: increased risk of reoperation/complications but does not definitively preclude free flap; site anastomosis outside irradiated field when possible.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Free flap principles and planning", "question": "What is the Godina principle regarding timing of free flap reconstruction, and what does current evidence support?", "answer": "Godina (1986) recommended free flaps within 72 hours of injury for lower extremity reconstruction, reporting lower complication and failure rates with early coverage. Current evidence: retrospective review of 358 soft-tissue free flaps (1979-2016) for below-knee trauma confirmed Godina's findings — early reconstruction within 3 days had superior outcomes compared to delayed (4-90 days), BUT the safe early window can be extended to within 10 days without adverse outcome effects. In practice: timing depends on surgeon experience, wound/patient condition, healthcare logistics. Key principle: adequate debridement creates a fresh surgical wound reconstructable at any time. Immediate cover mandatory if vital structures exposed. For oncologic reconstruction: immediate reconstruction performed at same time as ablation (may modestly delay adjuvant therapy). For breast reconstruction with PMRT: optimal approach is delayed autologous reconstruction after radiation; delayed-immediate with tissue expansion considered when PMRT status uncertain.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Free flap principles and planning", "question": "What factors determine the choice of free flap for a given defect?", "answer": "First question: 'Does this defect NEED a free flap?' If yes, consider: (1) Size and tissue components of defect (skin, muscle, bone, nerve). (2) Goals of reconstruction — functional vs aesthetic priorities (e.g., young patient with benign mandible tumor: vascularized bone for dental implants; edentulous elderly with poor-prognosis cancer: soft-tissue flap with reconstruction plate). (3) Recipient vessel availability — length and caliber of flap pedicle must match; minimize need for vein grafts. (4) Donor site morbidity — favor sites allowing primary closure; consider muscle weakness, herniation risk, sensory loss, fracture susceptibility. (5) Flap tailorability — free flaps can be customized in size, form, tissue components, and function. (6) Two-team approach feasibility — lower extremity donor flaps advantageous. (7) Patient factors: prior surgery, body habitus, comorbidities. Principle: 'replace like with like' for superior functional and aesthetic results.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Free flap principles and planning", "question": "Should the artery or vein be anastomosed first in free flap surgery? What are the arguments for each approach?", "answer": "No consensus exists; dictated by ischemia time and vessel position (deeper/harder-to-reach vessel repaired first). ARTERY FIRST advantages: (1) shortens warm ischemia time, (2) re-establishment of circulation reveals dominant venous drainage aiding vein selection, (3) detects twist/kink/compression in pedicle. ARTERY FIRST disadvantages: flap bleeding during venous repair, venous congestion with free radical buildup (mitigated by intermittently releasing second vein for drainage). VEIN FIRST advantages: (1) better adjustment of pedicle length, (2) no venous congestion/bleeding during arterial repair. VEIN FIRST disadvantage: delays flap revascularization. Practice at high-volume centers (>1000 free flaps/year): routinely repair artery first and leave unclamped during venous repair; temporary congestion managed by allowing less dominant comitant vein to drain freely. Single vs dual venous anastomosis: Khouri reported 4.3% failure with single vs 0% with two veins, but sound judgment required — single adequate vein provides sufficient drainage.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Free flap principles and planning", "question": "Describe prefabrication and prelamination of flaps. How do they differ, and what are their applications?", "answer": "PREFABRICATION: Two-stage process. Stage 1: implant an axial vascular pedicle into desired donor tissue to allow neovascularization (~8 weeks). Stage 2: transfer neo-vascularized tissue based on its implanted pedicle to reconstruct the defect. Allows creation of large, thin skin flaps retaining donor site qualities; modifiable with various combinations of vascular pedicles, donor tissues, and geographic locations. PRELAMINATION: Two-stage process. Stage 1: add one or more tissues (skin, bone, cartilage, mucosa) to a reliable vascular bed to create a multilayered composite flap (~2 weeks maturation). Stage 2: transplant the mature composite flap. The delay allows prelaminating layers to heal, stabilize, and assume expected structures. Key difference: prefabrication creates a new vascular supply TO a tissue; prelamination adds tissue components ONTO an existing vascular bed. Applications: reconstruction of esophagus, penis, oral lining, ear, nose, neourethra, trachea, larynx, and complex head/neck defects requiring specific contours.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Perforator flap concepts", "question": "What is a free-style free flap, and how does it differ from a traditional perforator flap?", "answer": "Traditional perforator flap: based on well-described, anatomically studied musculocutaneous perforators (e.g., DIEP, ALT) with known vascular anatomy. Free-style free flap (Wei concept): harvest of a skin paddle based on ANY audible perforator detected by hand-held Doppler (or optimized duplex sonography) in an area that may NOT have been previously studied anatomically. Technique: (1) identify perforator with Doppler at fascia level through exploratory incision, (2) if sizeable (≥0.5 mm with visible pulsation), dissect retrograde to parent vessel, (3) raise flap as free flap. Advantages: can design flap almost anywhere on body, opens door to ~400 potential perforator flaps, alleviates concerns about vascular anomaly, tailored to defect location. Limitations: small-caliber vessels, small-to-medium skin paddles, pedicle length not critical. Requires supramicrosurgery skills for small vessel anastomosis.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Perforator flap concepts", "question": "What are the methods of flap thinning, and what vascular anatomy makes primary thinning possible?", "answer": "Skin is nourished by a subdermal plexus from branches of the main pedicle plus recurrent dermal branches, allowing safe thinning. Three methods: (1) STANDARD THINNING: thin to ~3-4 mm thickness in Asians, leaving unthinned area of 2 cm around pedicle; reduces need for secondary revisions. (2) MICRODISSECTION THINNING: dissect blood vessels in adipose layer under microscopic magnification, remove surrounding adipose tissue while preserving vessels. (3) SCARPA'S FASCIA-LEVEL HARVEST: harvest flap at the level of Scarpa's fascia (superficial circumflex artery perforator flap is flap of choice for this method); utilizes 'hot/cold zone' concept. Color-coded duplex sonography (CCDS) guides harvest at different levels above muscular fascia, allowing accurate assessment of perforator subcutaneous course and planning subfascial/epifascial/suprafascial harvest depth. Thinning avoids secondary debulking procedures and improves aesthetic outcomes.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Flap monitoring and salvage", "question": "What causes anastomotic failure in microvascular surgery? List the principal technical faults.", "answer": "Principal technical faults (Acland): (1) TEARING: from excessive tension at repair site or overly meticulous adventitial stripping (head/neck veins especially fragile). (2) LEAKING: gaps between sutures too large, unnoticed tears, or tiny branches near anastomotic site; even small leaks precipitate intraluminal thrombus. (3) NARROWING: oversized bites, entangled knots, or continuous suture too tight; tight sutures damage media — if ≥1/3 of wall undergoes necrosis, re-endothelialization fails and occlusion follows. (4) THROUGH-STITCHING: inadvertent bite of back wall causes luminal obstruction; prevented by constant luminal irrigation and raising anterior wall with microforceps. (5) ADVENTITIA INCLUSION: prolapsed adventitia from inadequate preparation becomes nidus for thrombus. (6) DESICCATION: drying of vessel wall. Prevention: meticulous technique, constant irrigation, proper adventitial trimming, visualizing lumen at all times, tying knots by SIGHT not feel.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Flap monitoring and salvage", "question": "How are medicinal leeches used in free flap salvage? Describe mechanism, protocol, and required precautions.", "answer": "Indication: venous congested flaps when surgical and pharmacological salvage fails. Mechanism: Hirudo medicinalis leeches bite into congested flap and inject (via saliva): local anesthetic, vasodilator, and hirudin (anticoagulant). They feed on blood, increasing perfusion within congested flaps. After falling away when full, bleeding continues for up to 10 hours due to combined vasodilator and anticoagulant effect. Protocol: apply new leeches when bleeding slows or flap appears congested again. Continue therapy until flap re-establishes effective venous drainage through new vessel ingrowth around flap margins. Precautions: (1) Significant blood loss — usually limit to small-to-medium flaps, monitor hemoglobin DAILY. (2) Prophylactic antibiotics required against Aeromonas hydrophila (present in leech digestive tract). (3) Blood transfusion may be necessary.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Free flap principles and planning", "question": "What are the advantages of free microvascular tissue transfer over conventional reconstruction methods?", "answer": "Advantages: (1) Freedom of choice of donor tissue components — replace 'like with like' for superior functional and aesthetic results. (2) Flap tailorable to recipient site requirements in size, form, tissue components, and function. (3) Often single-stage procedure (vs. multistage for pedicled/distant flaps) — earlier mobilization, return to work, reduced hospitalization and costs. (4) Better cutaneous blood flow and vascularity — enhances wound healing and reduces infection. (5) Increasing flap repertoire with primary-closure donor sites minimizing donor morbidity. Disadvantages/risks: (1) Long surgery and anesthesia time. (2) Risk of vasospasm and microvascular thrombosis. (3) Potential need for re-exploration. (4) Flap failure (total or partial). Current success rates: 96-100% in experienced centers (vs. 74-91% in earlier era).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Flap monitoring and salvage", "question": "When a free flap fails completely, what systematic approach guides the decision for a second free flap?", "answer": "Three issues to consider (Oliva et al.): (1) REASONS FOR FAILURE: reversible causes (technical error, suboptimal postop management, delayed diagnosis) favor repeat attempt; irreversible factors (systemic vascular disease, radiation, lack of healthy vessels) require careful risk-benefit analysis. (2) INDICATIONS: does the defect need another free flap? Mandatory when: loss would lead to limb loss, expose major neck vessels, delay adjuvant chemo/radiotherapy, or significantly decrease quality of life. (3) CURRENT WOUND STATUS: vital structure exposure = life-threatening, mandates prompt coverage. Planning: choose flap with good vascularity and LONGER pedicle (larger defect after debridement, new recipient vessels likely further from defect). Avoid reusing previous recipient vessels (inflamed, friable). Contralateral same flap preferred when available. Success rates: head/neck 94.1%, extremity 82-87.5%. Downgrade reconstruction only if patient unfit, overwhelming infection, poor prognosis with already low QoL.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Free flaps and microsurgery", "subtopic": "Microsurgical technique basics", "question": "What are the key considerations for microvascular anesthesia, and how does anesthetic management differ from standard procedures?", "answer": "Requirements: (1) Stable anesthesia by team FAMILIAR with microsurgery. (2) Good pain, temperature, and sympathetic control throughout — prevents vasospasm and vasoconstriction. (3) Fine-tuned blood pressure: kept LOW during flap dissection (bloodless field), then brought UP gradually during hemostasis and anastomosis (ensures good recipient inflow and flap perfusion). (4) Adequate fluid management: slight hemodilution to maintain high cardiac output and low systemic vascular resistance. (5) Avoid hypothermia (<36°C causes vasospasm); constantly monitor temperature. (6) Avoid tachycardia (sympathetic overdrive causes vasospasm). (7) Blood transfusion: NOT a risk factor for flap failure — decision based on intraoperative blood loss, hemodynamic status, and underlying morbidities. Postop: normalize BP, keep patient warm, hydrated, and pain-free; good hyperglycemic control; prophylactic antibiotics; LMWH for DVT prophylaxis.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue expansion", "question": "What is mechanotransduction, and how does it apply to tissue expansion? What cellular changes occur?", "answer": "Mechanotransduction is the conversion of mechanical forces into biochemical signals. In tissue expansion, skin stretched beyond physiological limits activates mechanotransduction pathways that increase: (1) mitotic activity, (2) collagen synthesis, (3) cell growth, (4) formation of new tissue and skin surface area. Specific molecular events: mechanical stress activates mechanosensitive ion channels, G-proteins, protein kinases, integrin-matrix interactions. Fibroblasts proliferate in response to mechanical stretch. Collagen and elastin realign in parallel fashion in direction of stretching. VEGF, PDGF, and bFGF are significantly higher in expanded vs non-expanded tissue, leading to increased vascularity and allowing harvest of larger flaps.", "notes": "Tissue expansion is not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue expansion", "question": "Describe the different types of tissue expanders and their port systems.", "answer": "Types by valve system: (1) REMOTE VALVE: connected by flexible filling tube to expander; can be palpated under skin; lower risk of puncturing balloon during inflation; beneficial when pocket too firm or overlying skin very thin. (2) INTEGRATED VALVE: inflation reservoir on expander surface; avoids mechanical problems/bacterial colonization of tubing, but higher risk of accidentally piercing expander during inflation; use magnetic metal-finding or ultrasonic devices to locate. (3) SELF-INFLATING: hydrogel (vinyl pyrrolidone and methyl methacrylate) absorbs extracellular fluid via osmosis, expanding over 6-8 weeks; decreases pain and clinic visits; disadvantage: potential expansion beyond tissue vascularity. Also CO2 self-inflating (remote radio-controlled). Special types: BECKER EXPANDER-IMPLANT: double-lumen, inner chamber filled with saline during expansion, outer chamber pre-filled with gel; can be left as permanent implant after detaching remote valve. Shapes: circular, rectangular, crescentic (50-1000 cc).", "notes": "Tissue expansion is not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "Compare smooth versus textured breast implant surfaces: manufacturing, clinical behavior, capsular contracture rates, and BIA-ALCL risk.", "answer": "SMOOTH: produced by dipping mandrel into liquid silicone creating multilayers, cured in laminar flow oven. Can move within capsule without visible change. Massage starts 4-5 days postop. TEXTURED: proprietary processes vary (sodium chloride, sugar, soak/scrub, pressure stamping, loss-salt, imprint stamping with PU foam). Provides friction, reduces malposition. Anatomic implants MUST be textured to prevent rotation. Massage is CONTRAINDICATED (increases fluid around implant). Capsular contracture: theory that irregular surface prevents parallel collagen fiber alignment; preliminary studies supported lower CF rates with textured, but recent long-term studies show negligible difference. BIA-ALCL: textured implants associated with 67-421x increased risk of developing this T-cell lymphoma. Barr classification of texture: macro-, micro-, meso-, and nano-textured surfaces.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "Describe the implant placement options in breast augmentation: subglandular, subfascial, and the three types of dual plane.", "answer": "SUBGLANDULAR: over pectoralis muscle, beneath skin/fat/glandular tissue. Advantages: less implant movement during activity, less immediate postop pain. Disadvantages: higher capsular fibrosis risk, visible edges/rippling/wrinkling, causes breast parenchyma atrophy. Choose when pinch test >2 cm. SUBFASCIAL: between pectoral muscle fascia and muscle; better tissue coverage with less visible edges, but fascia is extremely thin and fragile. DUAL PLANE (all partially submuscular): Type I: minimal release of pectoralis from lower attachments at IMF level; classic partial submuscular. Type II: greater pectoralis release up to nipple level; overlying breast parenchyma released partway to nipple; optimal for very slight sagging. Type III: greatest pectoralis release; muscle and parenchyma released all the way to nipple level. Pinch test <2 cm favors subpectoral placement. Submuscular placement causes pectoralis major atrophy but NOT breast parenchyma atrophy.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "What is breast implant-associated anaplastic large cell lymphoma (BIA-ALCL)? Describe presentation, risk factors, diagnosis, and management.", "answer": "BIA-ALCL: potentially fatal T-cell lymphoma associated with breast implants. Risk factors: TEXTURED implants (67-421x increased risk vs smooth); first reported 1997, incidence increasing (possibly due to improved awareness). Presentation: late-onset seroma (>1 year after implantation, incidence 0.9-1.8%) not explainable by infection or trauma is the hallmark; may also present as mass or lymphadenopathy. Diagnosis: fine-needle aspiration of periprosthetic fluid, flow cytometry, CD30-positive/ALK-negative immunohistochemistry. Management: NCCN guidelines recognized by FDA emphasize critical role of complete surgical ablation (total capsulectomy with implant removal). Adjunct chemotherapy for advanced disease with lymph node involvement. National registries created in multiple countries for tracking. FDA has released report linking ALCL specifically to textured implants.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "What are the common malposition complications after breast augmentation, and how do they present?", "answer": "BOTTOMING OUT: inferior implant displacement with high-riding nipple; lower pole longer than it should be. DOUBLE BUBBLE: double convexity of lower pole due to visible disruption of old IMF; two parallel transverse folds across lower breast pole. Caused by spontaneous implant migration, capsular fibrosis, or glandular ptosis. Treatment: capsulorrhaphy, neosubpectoral pocket, acellular dermal matrices, or conversion subpectoral to subglandular. WATERFALL/SNOOPY DEFORMITY: superior implant-to-nipple malposition; full upper pole with natural breast tissue ptosing off the implant inferiorly. SYMMASTIA: rare; excessive midline dissection creating one continuous capsular pocket; implants confluence beyond midline with no natural sinus. Caused by oversized implants or placement too close to midline. Treatment: medial capsulorrhaphy reattaching capsule to sternum, or neosubpectoral pocket. Prevention: anatomical approach during pocket dissection preserving superficial and deep attachments of pectoralis fascia at IMF.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "Compare silicone-filled versus saline-filled breast implants: properties, advantages, disadvantages, and rupture presentation.", "answer": "SILICONE-FILLED: medical-grade cohesive silicone gel; cohesiveness varies with cross-linking density (less cross-linked = softer, more elastic; more cross-linked = firmer). Feel more natural and softer. Modern 3rd-5th generation have phenyl/trifluoropropyl groups on shell to reduce gel bleed. Rupture: usually 'silent' (intracapsular, gel remains within scar capsule); best detected by MRI; may not cause symptoms. Larger incision needed. SALINE-FILLED: can use smaller incision (filled after insertion). Subpectoral placement preferred (subglandular shows wrinkling). Rupture/deflation: immediately noticeable (implant collapses as saline leaks via valve leak or shell tear). Can only be used with transumbilical approach. Silicone implant rupture rates increase after 6-8 years; by 13 years, 11.8% have ruptured. Round implants available in both; anatomic implants are silicone-only.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "Describe Tebbetts' 'High Five System' for breast implant selection. What are the five critical preoperative decisions?", "answer": "The High Five System is a tissue-based planning system for breast augmentation. Five critical preoperative decisions: (1) Implant coverage/pocket planning (subglandular vs submuscular vs dual plane, guided by pinch test: <2 cm favors subpectoral). (2) Implant size/volume (based on measurements plus patient wishes; ~100 cc per cup size increase; must respect chest wall width to preserve anterior axillary line, cleavage, intermammary distance). (3) Implant type (round vs anatomic, smooth vs textured, silicone vs saline). (4) Inframammary fold position (predicted from nipple-to-fold distance under maximal stretch compared to reference chart for selected implant; lowering may be required). (5) Incision (inframammary, periareolar [if areola >3.5 cm and volume <300 cc], transaxillary [blunt or endoscopic], transumbilical [limited to saline]). Variables analyzed: patient base width, implant base width, anterior pulled skin stretch, nipple-to-fold distance.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue expansion", "question": "What is the tissue expansion protocol: timing of initial inflation, serial expansion schedule, and key principles to avoid complications?", "answer": "Initial inflation: performed intraoperatively immediately after skin closure; fill 15-20% of expander volume to ensure full deployment. Serial inflation: begins 1-2 weeks after surgery when skin is completely healed. Technique: 23-gauge or smaller needle; inflate with saline per patient tolerance and tissue vascularity. Repeat weekly until desired size reached and adequate soft tissue generated. For breast expanders: OVERINFLATION is commonly performed to achieve natural ptosis after permanent implant placement. Key principles to avoid complications: (1) preserve major axial vessel in expanded tissue, (2) avoid overly aggressive inflation (risk ischemia/necrosis), (3) incisions along one margin of flap to reduce suture line tension, (4) place valve remote from incision, (5) pocket base should equal expander base (prevent movement), (6) sterile technique during inflation (late infection risk from iatrogenic bacterial introduction).", "notes": "Tissue expansion is not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "What is capsular fibrosis (capsular contracture)? Describe pathophysiology, incidence, risk factors, classification, and treatment.", "answer": "Capsular fibrosis: foreign body response to implant causing fibrotic encapsulation by excessive deposition of collagen and extracellular matrix. Pathophysiology: initial T-cell and macrophage migration, followed by increased (myo-)fibroblast activity leading to fibrosis. Overall incidence: 10.6%. Risk factors (controversially discussed): smooth (vs textured) implants, subglandular (vs submuscular) placement, silicone- (vs saline-) filled implants, bacterial contamination. Baker Classification: Grade I (soft, natural), Grade II (slightly firm, implant palpable), Grade III (firm, implant visible/palpable distortion), Grade IV (hard, painful, obvious distortion). Treatment: surgical â€” implant exchange with capsulectomy or capsulotomy. Modern approach: micro- and nanoscale surface topographies influence cellular behavior and immune response; Barr classification (2017) categorizes textures as macro-, micro-, meso-, nano-textured to guide surface development.", "notes": "Baker classification not explicitly detailed in this chapter text but is standard knowledge referenced"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "What is breast implant illness (BII)? Describe the symptoms, proposed mechanisms, and current evidence.", "answer": "BII: a cluster of systemic symptoms associated with breast implants that do not fit any classic disease diagnosis â€” a diagnosis of EXCLUSION. Symptoms: fatigue, dizziness, myalgia, arthralgia, rash (FDA-recognized), plus numbness/tingling in extremities, hair loss, memory loss/cognitive problems, dry eyes/blurred vision, breast pain, food sensitivity/intolerance, flu-like symptoms/low-grade fever, difficulty breathing (Wee et al. 2020). Proposed mechanisms: multifactorial including psychosomatic factors; 'autoimmune/inflammatory syndrome induced by adjuvants' (ASIA/Shoenfeld's syndrome) â€” silicone may induce autoimmune-like phenomena. Variables: material composition, anatomic position, duration of implant, genetics, comorbidities, medications, lifestyle. Current evidence: NO definitive scientific evidence of primary association between implants and rheumatologic/connective tissue diseases. Multiple cohort studies and meta-analyses report associations but not causation. Treatment: explantation often improves or completely resolves symptoms.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Tissue expansion", "question": "How does tissue expansion differ in head and neck reconstruction compared to other body areas? Describe the surgical technique for scalp expansion.", "answer": "Head/neck expansion differs due to: hair-bearing skin, different textures with varying skin quality, aesthetic subunits of face. Commonly used in children's scalp repair to avoid skin transplantation. Technique: (1) Exact preoperative planning of incision line, depth, positioning with attention to aesthetic subunits and hair-bearing areas. (2) One or two incisions made anteriorly and/or posteriorly to expanded area (use scar for incision if present). (3) Skin bridge of at least 3 cm included if defects expected; incisions adjacent and medial to bone defects. (4) Deepen incision to subgaleal plane â€” scalp easily undermined in this layer. (5) Create pocket with base as large as expander base (prevents movement). (6) Place valve on opposite part of pocket without contact to incision lines. (7) Initial inflation: 15-20% volume intraoperatively. (8) Further filling 1-2 weeks after complete skin healing; amount depends on patient tolerance and skin vascularity.", "notes": "Tissue expansion is not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "Differentiate acute versus late radiation toxicity: timing, mechanism, reversibility, and examples of each.", "answer": "ACUTE toxicity: occurs during treatment or shortly after (peaks 7-10 days post-completion); affects cells with rapid turnover (oral mucosa, skin epithelium); mechanism is depletion of progenitor/stem cells; REVERSIBLE (heals fast after completion). Examples: skin erythema/desquamation, oral mucositis, esophagitis, diarrhea, cystitis. Exception: consequential damage from very high dose destroying basement membrane with complete stem cell depletion (causes chronic ulcers). SUBACUTE: 6 weeks to 6 months after treatment; also reversible (e.g., radiation pneumonitis, Lhermitte's syndrome). LATE toxicity: >6 months after RT; affects cells with slow renewal (connective tissue, nervous tissue, endothelium, osteoblasts, chondroblasts); mechanism is self-perpetuating TGF-beta-driven myofibroblast activity causing IRREVERSIBLE progressive fibrosis; strongly correlated with fraction size. Examples: subcutaneous fibrosis, osteoradionecrosis, brachial plexopathy. Acute toxicity does NOT predict late toxicity.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "Describe the molecular mechanism of radiation-induced fibrosis and its implications for surgical wound healing.", "answer": "Radiation causes DNA damage (direct double-strand breaks and indirect via reactive oxygen species). This triggers ATM gene-mediated signal transduction pathway for DNA repair. A cascade of cytokines follows: IL-1, IL-6, TNF-alpha cause inflammatory response and coagulation. TGF-beta is the key driver: (1) causes fibroblast-to-myofibroblast differentiation, (2) stimulates collagen production, (3) modifies extracellular matrix qualitatively and quantitatively, (4) downregulates thrombomodulin in endothelium causing platelet aggregation, (5) platelets release more TGF-beta creating a SELF-PERPETUATING cycle. Unlike traumatic wounds where remodeling occurs over years, irradiated tissue LOSES capacity to remodel and develops reactive fibrosis. Surgical implications: decreased wound-breaking strength, delayed wound healing, damaged microvasculature, decreased cellular elements. Optimal surgical window: 3-10 weeks after RT completion (after acute reaction resolves, before excessive fibrosis develops). Complications related to total dose, dose per fraction, timing and extent of surgery.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What are the indications for postmastectomy radiation therapy (PMRT)?", "answer": "PMRT indicated when: (1) Tumor >=5 cm (based on prechemotherapy size if neoadjuvant, i.e., cT3). (2) Positive margins or margins <1 mm. (3) Regional lymph node metastases (definitely for >=4 positive nodes; controversial for 1-3 nodes). (4) Lymphovascular invasion (predicts local recurrence). Chest wall irradiation is ALWAYS indicated with nodal involvement even if primary tumor is small, as the most common failure pattern is local chest wall failure. NOT indicated when: tumor <5 cm with negative margins and no nodal spread. Standard dose: 50 Gy in 1.8-2 Gy fractions (conventional fractionation remains standard for PMRT). Boost: additional 10-16 Gy to tumor bed/scar for high-risk features (positive margin, close margin + multiple risk factors). For left-sided cancers: DIBH technique or proton therapy to minimize cardiac dose (7.4% increased ischemic cardiac disease risk per Gy mean heart dose, linear no-threshold relationship).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "How does radiation therapy affect breast reconstruction planning? What is the recommended coordination between radiation oncology and plastic surgery?", "answer": "Key principles: (1) If PMRT indicated/likely, upfront multidisciplinary evaluation (surgical oncology, radiation oncology, medical oncology, plastic surgery, physical therapy) is STRONGLY recommended. (2) Autologous reconstruction (e.g., DIEP, latissimus) preferred over implant-based after radiation (implants more prone to contracture and reconstructive failure in irradiated field). (3) Optimal interval: at least 12 months from RT to autologous reconstruction to minimize complications. (4) If expander placed at mastectomy: expand skin to promote memory, then DEFLATE before RT for improved dosimetry; contralateral expander may also need partial deflation to improve beam angles. (5) For proton therapy: expander port must be OUTSIDE treatment field (causes dose distribution uncertainty with protons; not an issue with photons). (6) Two-stage approach common: expander at mastectomy, RT with deflated expander, then delayed reconstruction. (7) LYMPHA procedure should be coordinated if axillary dissection planned (dramatically lowers lymphedema rates).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "Compare preoperative versus postoperative radiation therapy for soft-tissue sarcoma: doses, field sizes, and complication profiles.", "answer": "Based on Canadian NCIC-SR-2 trial: PREOPERATIVE RT: 50 Gy in 25 fractions, shorter duration (5-5.5 weeks), SMALLER field size (just tumor + margin), reduced late fibrosis/edema/joint stiffness. BUT: higher major wound healing complications (35% vs 17%), especially in lower extremity. POSTOPERATIVE RT: 60-66 Gy in 30-33 fractions, longer duration (6-6.5 weeks), LARGER field size (must cover entire operative footprint), increased late fibrosis and edema, decreased wound complications. Higher dose needed postop due to decreased oxygenation/vascularity of tumor bed. LOCAL CONTROL equivalent between approaches. Many institutions favor preoperative because wound complications are reversible while late fibrosis/edema are permanent. IMRT has subsequently reduced wound complications in preop setting. Indications for RT: tumors >5 cm, intermediate/high grade regardless of margins, low-grade with positive margins, local recurrence, or challenging location for salvage. Key: spare longitudinal strip of skin/subcutaneous tissue for lymphatic drainage.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What is osteoradionecrosis (ORN)? Describe risk factors, presentation, and the most commonly affected site.", "answer": "ORN: necrotic wound in irradiated bone persisting without healing for 3-6 months, in absence of tumor recurrence. Most commonly affects the MANDIBLE after head and neck cancer RT. Presentation: clinically exposed bone (sometimes painless); radiologic evidence of necrosis on CT/MRI (may mimic disease recurrence) at 1-3 years after radiation. Radiation risk factors: fraction size >2 Gy, volume of bone irradiated, total dose to bone >60 Gy, re-irradiation. Modality matters: particle therapy (electrons, neutrons, protons), brachytherapy, and kilovoltage energy cause higher bone absorbed doses than megavoltage photons. Non-radiation risk factors: poor oral hygiene, dental extraction, concurrent chemotherapy (worsens mucositis/xerostomia), bisphosphonates. Prevention: dental clearance before RT, dental extractions before starting treatment, radiation oncologist delineates mandible/maxilla/salivary glands with dose constraints, life-long daily fluoride treatments post-RT, pristine dental hygiene. Incidence: historically 6.8%, now 0-2% with modern conformal techniques (IMRT, IGRT).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What is the Bragg peak, and why is proton beam therapy advantageous over photon therapy for certain tumors?", "answer": "Bragg peak: protons enter the body with low steady-dose deposition, then near the end of their range, dose peaks SHARPLY and falls off rapidly to nearly ZERO. This allows: (1) precise high-dose distribution homogeneously covering target volume, (2) protection of critical structures BEYOND the Bragg peak (no exit dose), (3) dose intensification. Photons by contrast deposit Dmax at ~1.5 cm then attenuate steadily (~5%/cm), always having exit dose. Ideal proton indications: skull base tumors (chordomas, chondrosarcomas â€” high dose needed near optic chiasm/spinal cord), craniospinal irradiation for pediatric cancers (spares heart, kidneys, bowel, lungs, pelvic organs), pelvic sarcomas (fertility preservation), left-sided breast cancer with nodal irradiation (cardiac sparing), re-irradiation. Limitations: dose uncertainty from tissue heterogeneity changes (sinus congestion, postop edema, bowel gas, weight changes); high-Z hardware (titanium) causes dose shadowing (carbon fiber hardware preferred). Skin reaction may be more marked than photons.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "Describe the radiation treatment-planning process: from simulation to treatment delivery.", "answer": "Steps: (1) SIMULATION: patient positioned and immobilized (mesh mask for head/neck, vacuum splints for body, casts for extremities); CT scan in treatment position; localizing tattoos placed for daily alignment. (2) CONTOURING: radiation oncologist delineates GTV (gross tumor volume), CTV (clinical target volume including microscopic disease risk), PTV (planning target volume accounting for motion/variation), and OAR (organs-at-risk with dose constraints). (3) TREATMENT PLANNING: dosimetrists and radiation oncologist select beam arrangement to homogeneously cover PTV while sparing OAR; dose-volume histograms calculate constraints (e.g., V20 of lung >35% predicts pneumonitis). (4) QUALITY ASSURANCE: physicist verifies plan is technically feasible. (5) VERIFICATION: dry run with patient in immobilization device; portal imaging compared to DRRs; CBCT for precise alignment (IGRT). (6) TREATMENT: daily fractions with verification (usually daily CBCT). Timeline: 10-14 days for curative setup, 3-10 days complex palliation, 0-3 days simple palliation.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What are the common radiation fractionation schemes, and when is each used?", "answer": "CONVENTIONAL fractionation: 1.8-2 Gy/day, 5 days/week. Used for curative intent (e.g., 66-70 Gy for head/neck SCC, 80 Gy for prostate, 50 Gy for adjuvant breast). HYPOFRACTIONATION: >2 Gy/fraction (typically >2.4 Gy/day). Uses smaller total dose but larger dose per fraction. Used for: breast conservation (40 Gy in 15 or 42.5 Gy in 16 fractions), palliation, melanoma (6 Gy twice/week x 5-6 fractions). HYPERFRACTIONATION: twice daily fractions 6 hours apart. Maximizes normal tissue repair while allowing dose escalation for rapidly dividing tumors; used for head/neck cancers, re-irradiation, patients who can't tolerate cisplatin. SBRT/Radiosurgery: 1-5 (up to 8) fractions of very large doses (10-18+ Gy) using highly conformal planning. For small tumors (lung, liver, spine). PALLIATIVE: 8 Gy x 1, 20 Gy in 5, or 30 Gy in 10 fractions. EQD2 and BED calculations allow comparison between regimens. Key principle: higher dose per fraction increases both tumor kill AND late toxicity risk.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What are the head and neck-specific acute and late toxicities of radiation therapy?", "answer": "ACUTE (during treatment, reversible): Mucositis (starts weeks 2-3, confluent by end; exacerbated by smoking, alcohol, concurrent chemotherapy; causes dysphagia requiring PEG tube placement before starting treatment); skin erythema (weeks 3-4) progressing to moist desquamation; xerostomia (radiation damages parotid glands, changes saliva consistency to thick mucoid secretions); taste changes; weight loss; fatigue. LATE (>6 months, PERMANENT, progressive): Fibrosis of subcutaneous tissues, musculature, joints causing trismus, neck stiffness, aching, swallowing difficulties; permanent xerostomia if parotid/submandibular receives >26 Gy (exacerbates dental problems); voice changes from laryngeal edema/cartilage damage; osteoradionecrosis (mandible most commonly). Treatment modifications to reduce toxicity: IMRT for parotid sparing reduces permanent xerostomia; submandibular gland-sparing IMRT; proton therapy for unilateral neck minimizes contralateral fibrosis. Key timing: postoperative RT should start within 6 weeks of surgical resection.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What are the risk factors and mechanisms of radiation-induced lymphedema, and what is the incidence after breast cancer treatment?", "answer": "Mechanism: radiation-induced fibrosis compresses lymph vessels, impairing drainage. Always exclude recurrent disease before attributing edema to treatment. Incidence: 42% 5-year cumulative incidence in breast cancer survivors (prospective population-based study), but majority (23%) is mild; only 2% develop chronic severe edema. With modern sentinel lymph node biopsy: ~10% with breast-conserving surgery and axillary RT. Independent risk factors: (1) radiation treatment of the axilla, (2) extent of axillary lymph node dissection, (3) type of breast surgery, (4) presence of regional lymph node metastases, (5) history of infection/injuries, (6) BMI. Greatest risk: COMBINATION of RT and axillary lymph node dissection. Key prevention strategies: AMAROS trial showed axillary RT has less lymphedema than ALND with equivalent survival; LYMPHA procedure (lymphatic microsurgical preventing approach) at time of axillary dissection dramatically lowers rates; spare longitudinal strip of skin/subcutaneous tissue in sarcoma RT.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What are the relative and absolute contraindications to radiation therapy?", "answer": "ABSOLUTE contraindications: pregnancy (high risk of fetal damage; pregnancy testing required in women of childbearing age). RELATIVE contraindications: (1) Chromosomal fragility syndromes (Li-Fraumeni syndrome, Rb gene carriers, ATM gene carriers) â€” exquisitely susceptible to radiation damage with frequent and earlier secondary malignancies. (2) Previous radiation therapy â€” requires assessment by radiation oncologist of current tumor relationship to prior field, total dose delivered, time interval between treatments, tumor radiosensitivity. (3) Active connective tissue diseases (especially scleroderma) â€” may have increased acute and late toxicities. (4) Multicentric breast disease involving multiple quadrants (breast conservation RT contraindicated â€” significant cosmetic deformity). (5) Inflammatory breast disease (absolute for breast conservation). (6) Poor performance status/patient preference may shift curative intent to observation or non-radical RT. Young age requires weighing benefit against late sequelae including second malignancy risk.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Radiation and chemotherapy implications", "question": "What is the risk of radiation-induced secondary malignancy? What factors influence this risk?", "answer": "Three mechanisms: (1) DNA damage and mutation, (2) disturbance of cellular defense/control mechanisms, (3) chronic ongoing damage to irradiated tissue. Timing: rare within first 5 years; typically presents many years later (except leukemia: 5-8 years; solid tumors: much later). Most sensitive organs: bone marrow and thyroid. Dose-response patterns: carcinomas arise at periphery (lower-dose volume); sarcomas arise in heavily irradiated tissue (dose-response effect). Thyroid cancer unlikely if gland received >30 Gy. Age is critical: adolescent girls aged 10-16 have up to 136-FOLD increased breast cancer risk from mantle radiation. Hodgkin lymphoma survivors with mantle RT: 4x breast cancer risk. Smoking markedly increases lung cancer risk even from tiny scattered doses. Genetic predisposition: Li-Fraumeni (p53), ATM, RB gene carriers are exquisitely susceptible. Chemotherapy (especially alkylating agents) is also carcinogenic and additive with RT. IMRT concern: conformal high-dose but larger low-dose volume from multiple beam entry may increase second cancer risk.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Radiation therapy for skin cancers", "question": "Describe the role of radiation therapy in treating skin cancers: BCC, SCC, melanoma, and Merkel cell carcinoma.", "answer": "BCC: primary RT for non-surgical candidates or when surgery risks function/cosmesis; 40-50 Gy in 10-20 fractions; 30-40% of incompletely excised BCCs recur, salvageable with surgery or RT. SCC: higher doses needed (60-66 Gy in 2 Gy fractions); adjuvant RT reduces recurrence risk; assess for perineural invasion (may require treating along neural pathways). MELANOMA: considered relatively radioresistant (broad shoulder on cell survival curve = large capacity for sublethal repair); overcome with hypofractionation â€” 6 Gy twice/week, total 30-36 Gy; adjuvant RT for desmoplastic histology, depth >4 mm with ulceration/satellites, positive margins, recurrent disease; improves local control 50% to 87% without affecting survival. MERKEL CELL CARCINOMA: rare neuroendocrine tumor; adjuvant RT recommended for nearly all non-metastatic patients; 45-50 Gy with boost to 60-66 Gy for residual disease; large treatment fields (3-5 cm) due to propensity for in-transit and regional lymphatic spread. Best superficial delivery: kV equipment (100% dose at surface) or electrons with bolus.", "notes": "Closest topic match; radiation for skin cancers not a standalone subtopic"}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "Describe the microscopic anatomy of the lymphatic system: how do capillary lymphatics differ from collecting lymphatics in structure and function?", "answer": "CAPILLARY LYMPHATICS: located in dermis; single layer of lymphatic endothelial cells (LECs) with little/no basement membrane; cells tethered to surrounding tissue by ANCHORING FILAMENTS and to each other by overlapping BUTTON-LIKE junctions. When tissue fluid increases, anchoring filaments cause LECs to separate, allowing fluid entry; once fluid enters, overlapping regions reestablish preventing leak. No smooth muscle. COLLECTING LYMPHATICS: located in deeper dermis/subcutaneous tissue; have continuous 'ZIPPER-LIKE' endothelial junctions preventing leak; have BASEMENT MEMBRANE; covered by SMOOTH MUSCLE CELLS that contract to propel fluid forward; have BICUSPID VALVES every 1-2 mm ensuring one-way flow. The functional unit is the LYMPHANGION: segment of collecting lymphatic between two valves.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "What are the two types of forces that drive lymphatic flow? How do they differ?", "answer": "1) PASSIVE compressive forces: arise from external sources â€” muscle contractions, respiration, regional arterial pulsation, gravity. Passively propel fluid centrally. In normal limbs, passive forces (massage, muscular contractions) do NOT significantly increase collecting lymphatic pressure or flow. 2) ACTIVE compressive forces: arise from INTRINSIC contraction of smooth muscle cells surrounding collecting lymphatics. These muscle cells have features of BOTH smooth AND striated muscle with basal myogenic activity. Similar to the heart, responsive to preload and afterload changes. Contraction frequency and strength modulated by vasoactive substances (histamine, substance P). Key: increases in preload/afterload increase contraction up to a point; PERSISTENT increases beyond this point lead to PUMP FAILURE and vessel dilatation.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "Classify primary lymphedema by timing of presentation. What genetic mutations are associated with each?", "answer": "CONGENITAL LYMPHEDEMA (presents at birth): more common in females; more commonly lower extremities; 10-25% of all primary lymphedema. Milroy's disease: sex-linked, inactivating mutations in VEGFR-3 (FLT4 gene); accounts for 2-3%; hypoplastic lymphatic vessels with variable agenesis. LYMPHEDEMA PRAECOX (before age 35): most common form; unilateral lower extremity; 4:1 female:male ratio; often symptomatic at puberty (sex-hormone link); decreased capillary lymphatics, hypoplastic low-caliber collecting vessels. Associated with FOXC2 mutations (lymphedema-distichiasis syndrome â€” also causes double row of eyelashes). LYMPHEDEMA TARDA (after age 35): diagnosis of EXCLUSION; infrequent; most commonly lower extremities in women; associated with FOXC2 loss-of-function mutations. Other genetic syndromes: Hennekam (CCBE1), Emberger (GATA2), Proteus (AKT1).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "What is the most common cause of lymphedema globally versus in high-income countries? What are the incidence rates?", "answer": "GLOBALLY: parasitic infection with Wuchereria bancrofti (filariasis) â€” estimated 200 million affected in low-income countries. Roundworms transmitted by mosquitos; adults grow in tissues and release microfilariae into bloodstream; cause chronic lymphatic obstruction and inflammatory reactions; treatment limited to antiparasitic medications that only kill developing larvae (not adult worms). HIGH-INCOME COUNTRIES: cancer treatment is the most common cause. Breast cancer survivors are the largest affected group. Incidence: 15-40% after axillary lymph node dissection (ALND); 5-7% even after sentinel lymph node biopsy (SLNB) alone. Other tumor incidences: melanoma 16%, sarcoma 30%, gynecologic tumors 20%, genitourinary 10%, head and neck 4%. Meta-analysis: nearly 1 in 6 patients treated for solid tumors develops lymphedema. Lymphedema is the most common long-term complication of cancer treatment.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "Describe the role of CD4+ T cells and Th2 differentiation in lymphedema pathophysiology.", "answer": "Lymphedema develops after lymphatic injury in response to induced infiltration and differentiation of CD4+ cells into Th2 cells in tissues. The degree of Th2 inflammatory response correlates with lymphedema severity. CD4+ cell responses are NECESSARY for BOTH initiation and maintenance of lymphedema (demonstrated by antibody depletion studies and knockout mice). Th2 cells regulate FOUR overlapping pathological mechanisms: (1) LYMPHATIC PUMP FAILURE â€” Th2-derived cytokines cause CD4+ T cells to accumulate around lymphatic vessels producing nitric oxide (NO), causing vessel dilatation and decreased pumping force. (2) IMPAIRED COLLATERAL VESSEL FORMATION â€” IL-4, IL-13, IFN-gamma have direct anti-lymphangiogenic effects on LECs; counterbalance upregulated VEGF-C. (3) FIBROADIPOSE DEPOSITION â€” Th2 cytokines (IL-4, IL-13, TGF-beta1) drive fibrosis. (4) EPIDERMAL CHANGES â€” keratinocytes produce Th2-promoting cytokines (TSLP, IL-25, IL-33), creating a positive feedback loop.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "Explain the role of TGF-beta1 in lymphedema-associated fibrosis. What is the therapeutic implication?", "answer": "TGF-beta1 is a key driver of lymphedema-induced fibrosis. Mechanism: CD4+ cells differentiate into Th2 cells which produce profibrotic cytokines including IL-4, IL-13, and TGF-beta1. TGF-beta1 promotes: extracellular matrix collagen deposition, fibroblast activity, progressive sclerosis of collecting lymphatics (obliteration of functional parenchyma replaced by scar tissue). Fibrosis independently DECREASES lymphatic vessel regeneration and function (creating a vicious cycle). Macrophages play an opposing antifibrotic role promoting ECM breakdown. Therapeutic implications: inhibition of TGF-beta1 with small-molecule inhibitors was shown to DECREASE fibrosis, INCREASE collateral lymphatic formation, IMPROVE radiation-induced lymphatic dysfunction, and DECREASE lymphedema severity in animal models. However, chronic TGF-beta1 inhibition risks autoimmune responses â€” further studies needed for effective pharmacological interventions.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "Describe the pathological progression of collecting lymphatic vessels in lymphedema using the NECST classification.", "answer": "NECST (Koshima classification) describes four progressive histological steps in collecting lymphatics after lymphadenectomy: (1) NORMAL (Step 0): lymphatic vessels are normal and fully functional. (2) ECTASIS (Step 1): endolymphatic pressure increases, causing LECs to flatten; lymphangiectasia (vessel dilation) begins. Early stage: disruption of endogenous NO gradient causes REVERSIBLE dilatation. (3) CONTRACTION (Step 2): smooth muscle cells convert into synthetic cells promoting collagenous fiber growth; lymphatic vessel wall THICKENS; loss of intraluminal diameter. (4) SCLEROSIS (Step 3): lumen of lymphatic vessels narrowed or completely OBSTRUCTED; most tissue is fibrosed; lymphatic vessels have lost transport and concentrating ability. This progressive sclerosis explains why late-stage lymphedema is IRREVERSIBLE â€” permanent collecting lymphatic pumping impairment from both structural obliteration and smooth muscle cell proliferation.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "Why does lymphedema only develop in a subset of patients who undergo lymphadenectomy, and why is presentation delayed?", "answer": "Key concept: lymphatic injury is NECESSARY but NOT SUFFICIENT for lymphedema. Additional pathological changes are required. After lymph node dissection, acute surgical swelling resolves within weeks and in most patients never recurs. In the early stages, chronic inflammation and subclinical fluid stasis promote PROLIFERATION AND COLLATERALIZATION of capillary lymphatics in the superficial dermis â€” these vessels effectively bypass the zone of obstruction, preventing overt lymphedema. However, in 30-50% of patients, these compensatory mechanisms eventually fail: increased VEGF-C (from macrophages) induces formation of NONFUNCTIONAL hyperplastic, irregularly shaped vessels that do NOT bypass the injury zone. When BOTH superficial AND deep lymphatic systems fail (capillary + collecting), clinically evident lymphedema develops. Average onset: 8 months after breast cancer surgery; 75% diagnosed within first 3 years. Lower extremity onset faster (3-6 months, possibly due to gravity).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "How are obesity and lymphedema related? What is the evidence for a bidirectional relationship?", "answer": "BIDIRECTIONAL RELATIONSHIP: (1) Obesity causes lymphedema: BMI >30 gives â‰¥3-fold increased lymphedema risk after breast cancer surgery (almost linear relationship). Massively obese patients (BMI >59) can SPONTANEOUSLY develop lower extremity lymphedema WITHOUT lymphatic surgery â€” this is PERMANENT with little improvement even after gastric bypass. Obesity causes leaky lymphatics, decreased lymphatic pumping, and lymphatic function inversely proportional to body weight (mouse studies). (2) Lymphedema causes adipose deposition: Prox-1 haploinsufficient mice (impaired lymphatic pumping/leakiness) become obese â€” demonstrating lymphatic abnormalities CAUSE weight gain. Fatty acids in interstitial/lymphatic fluid increase adipocyte proliferation and differentiation. Adiponectin and leptin levels elevated in lymphedema. KEY: adverse effects of obesity on lymphatic system are REVERSIBLE with weight loss, calorie restriction, or exercise. Therefore, weight loss counseling is essential before lymphadenectomy/lymphatic surgery.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "What is the role of nitric oxide (NO) in lymphedema progression?", "answer": "CD4+ T cells accumulate around lymphatic vessels in lymphedema and produce large amounts of nitric oxide (NO). This EXTRINSIC source of NO causes: (1) Lymphatic vessel DILATATION â€” decreases the force lymphatics generate for pumping. (2) In EARLY disease: disruption of the endogenous NO gradient leads to REVERSIBLE lymphatic vessel dilatation. (3) In LATE disease: IRREVERSIBLE lymphatic obliteration develops, leading to permanent collecting lymphatic pumping impairment. Additionally, NO-mediated dilatation contributes to lymphatic VALVULAR INCOMPETENCE, resulting in localized areas of RETROGRADE FLOW to capillary lymphatics in the superficial dermis (dermal backflow). At this point, collecting lymphatics maintain ability to actively contract but pulsations become more irregular with loss of correlation between pulse amplitude and stroke volume.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Diagnosis", "question": "Describe the ISL staging system for lymphedema. What are the clinical, imaging, and histological features of each stage?", "answer": "STAGE 0 (Latent): lymphatic vessels injured but capacity sufficient to drain; no measurable swelling; subclinical interstitial fluid stasis. STAGE I (Spontaneously reversible): pitting edema responsive to compression/elevation; dilated lymphatics with irregular pulsation; localized dermal backflow on ICG; histology shows modest hyperkeratosis, collagen deposition, inflammatory cell infiltration, dilated capillaries/collectors. STAGE II (Spontaneously irreversible): irreversible swelling; no pitting, spongy consistency; limbs harden and enlarge. ICG: loss of major collectors, extensive dermal backflow, decreased/absent pumping. Histology: sclerosed lymphatics, type I collagen accumulation, smooth muscle cell proliferation, adipocyte accumulation. STAGE III (Lymphostatic elephantiasis): severe irreversible swelling; heavily fibrosed, thickened skin. ICG: no recognizable collectors, diffuse dye accumulation. Histology: hyperkeratosis, parakeratosis, chronic inflammation, massive adipose/collagen deposition.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Diagnosis", "question": "Compare the diagnostic modalities for lymphedema: circumference measurements, volume measurements, bioimpedance, lymphoscintigraphy, MRI, and ICG lymphangiography.", "answer": "CIRCUMFERENCE: measured at distinct anatomic locations; >2 cm difference diagnostic; inter/intra-operator variability; limited in high BMI patients. VOLUME: more sensitive/specific than circumference; methods include water displacement, perometer (infrared scanner using truncated cone formula â€” expensive, not widely available), or 4 cm interval circumference with truncated cone calculation; >200 mL or 10% difference diagnostic. BIOIMPEDANCE (L-DEX): measures electrical current transmission rate; score â‰¥7 indicative of clinical lymphedema, â‰¥6.5 subclinical; variable due to skin temperature/dryness; helpful for early-stage detection. LYMPHOSCINTIGRAPHY: 99mTc uptake in draining nodes; most commonly used radiologic test but LOW sensitivity (0.61) for early disease. MRI LYMPHANGIOGRAPHY: high sensitivity/specificity; visualizes lymphatic vessels, pathologic changes, venous outflow abnormalities, AND fat hypertrophy. ICG LYMPHANGIOGRAPHY: advocated as GOLD STANDARD; nontoxic; visualizes collecting lymphatics, dermal backflow, abnormal vasculature; detects pathology even when volume/bioimpedance are normal.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Diagnosis", "question": "What is the Stemmer sign? What is its diagnostic significance?", "answer": "The Stemmer sign (Kaposi-Stemmer sign) is the INABILITY to pinch the skin fold at the base of the second toe on the dorsal aspect of the foot, or the webspace of the hand, in patients with lymphedema. A POSITIVE Stemmer sign is a SENSITIVE predictor for both primary and secondary lymphedema of arms or legs, making it a useful part of the physical examination. However, a positive sign is NOT REQUIRED for diagnosis â€” in some patients with extremity lymphedema, the hands or feet are SPARED from swelling. Described by Stemmer in 1976.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Diagnosis", "question": "Describe the M.D. Anderson ICG lymphedema classification system.", "answer": "Four-stage system based on indocyanine green (ICG) findings and degree of dermal backflow: STAGE 1: MANY patent lymphatic vessels present; MINIMAL dermal backflow in localized areas. STAGE 2: MODERATE number of lymphatic vessels; SEGMENTAL dermal backflow. STAGE 3: FEW patent lymphatic vessels; SIGNIFICANT dermal backflow throughout the ENTIRE arm. STAGE 4: NO patent lymphatic vessels; SEVERE dermal backflow throughout entire arm AND hand. Although somewhat subjective, useful for classification and patient selection for lymphovenous bypass procedures. This system complements the Koshima NECST classification which focuses on histological changes in collecting lymphatics (normal â†’ ectasis â†’ contraction â†’ sclerosis).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "List the key genetic syndromes associated with primary lymphedema, their gene mutations, and distinguishing clinical features.", "answer": "1) MILROY DISEASE: FLT4/VEGFR-3 mutation; congenital lower extremity lymphedema; upslanting 'SKI JUMP' toenails from nail bed edema; 2-3% of primary lymphedema. 2) LYMPHEDEMA-DISTICHIASIS: FOXC2 mutation; lower-limb lymphedema at PUBERTY; DOUBLE ROW OF EYELASHES (distichiasis). 3) HYPOTRICHOSIS-LYMPHEDEMA-TELANGIECTASIA: SOX18 mutation; lymphedema + hair loss + dilated superficial blood vessels. 4) MEIGE'S DISEASE: GJC2 (connexin 47); impaired gap junctions; increased breast cancer-related lymphedema risk. 5) HENNEKAM SYNDROME: CCBE1 mutation; severe limb/genital/facial lymphedema; seizures; intellectual disability; often presents in utero. 6) EMBERGER SYNDROME: GATA2 mutation; childhood lower limb lymphedema; severe cutaneous warts; myelodysplasia. 7) PROTEUS SYNDROME: AKT1 mutation; lymphatic malformations + skeletal/cutaneous/CNS abnormalities.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "What is the role of VEGF-C in lymphedema, and why do functional lymphatic vessels fail to form despite high VEGF-C levels?", "answer": "VEGF-C (mainly produced by macrophages) is HIGHLY UPREGULATED in lymphedematous tissues. It is a key signal for LEC growth, migration, and survival via VEGFR-3 receptor. However, despite high VEGF-C levels, FUNCTIONAL lymphatic vessels fail to form because: (1) T-cell-derived cytokines including IL-4, IL-13, and IFN-gamma have DIRECT ANTI-LYMPHANGIOGENIC effects on LECs. (2) These anti-lymphangiogenic cytokines COUNTERBALANCE the pro-lymphangiogenic effect of VEGF-C, preventing functional lymphatics from forming. (3) The abnormal lymphatic vessels that DO form are NONFUNCTIONAL â€” they are hyperplastic, irregularly shaped vessels that arise from existing collecting vessels and proliferate around them but do NOT bypass the zone of injury. This paradox explains why simply promoting lymphangiogenesis may be insufficient therapy â€” the inflammatory microenvironment must also be addressed.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "What is the role of adipose deposition in lymphedema progression? How does it affect treatment response?", "answer": "End-stage lymphedema is characterized by PROGRESSIVE ADIPOSE DEPOSITION. Initially, lymphedema involves fluid accumulation (60-70% in subcutaneous tissues between adipose and around small veins; remainder above/below muscular fascia and in dermis). Over time, this fluid promotes chronic fibrofatty tissue deposition. Mechanisms: (1) Fatty acids in lymphatic fluid increase adipocyte PROLIFERATION and DIFFERENTIATION. (2) Lymphatic injury upregulates adipose differentiation genes, causes adipose hypertrophy. (3) Adiponectin and leptin (fat-regulating hormones) are elevated. (4) IL-6, a regulator of adipose homeostasis, is increased â€” paradoxically, inhibiting IL-6 INCREASES adipose deposition. Clinical significance: progressive fibrofatty deposition makes lymphedema MORE RESISTANT to compressive therapies. The irreversible nature of swelling and lack of pitting in stage II/III patients is explained by adipocyte accumulation. This is why LIPOSUCTION-based approaches (e.g., Brorson technique) may be needed for fat-predominant disease.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Diagnosis", "question": "What is the differential diagnosis for lymphedema? Why is venous obstruction particularly important to exclude?", "answer": "Differential diagnosis includes: (1) VENOUS INSUFFICIENCY, (2) deep vein thrombosis (DVT), (3) congestive heart failure, (4) recurrent or primary MALIGNANCY causing lymphatic obstruction, (5) medications, (6) infections. VENOUS OBSTRUCTION is particularly critical to exclude because: nearly 70% of interstitial fluid is removed by the VENOUS system (not lymphatics). Venous obstruction from thrombosis or recurrent tumor compressing venous system is a COMMON cause of limb swelling in cancer patients. MRI lymphangiography is valuable because it can also identify venous pathology â€” venous hypertension may not only contribute to swelling but also COMPROMISE the effects of lymphovenous bypass or lymph node transplant. Appropriate imaging to rule out venous obstruction is warranted in patients with unusual disease presentation. Always EXCLUDE RECURRENT DISEASE before attributing edema to lymphedema treatment.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "Describe the risk factors for secondary lymphedema. How do radiation and infection each contribute?", "answer": "Risk factors: obesity (BMI >30 = â‰¥3x risk), radiation, infection, extent of lymph node dissection, type of surgery, genetic factors (connexin 47, hepatocyte growth factor mutations increase risk). RADIATION: increases lymphedema risk up to 5-FOLD; effect is ADDITIVE with surgery (lymphedema from radiation alone is unusual, <7%); radiation-induced FIBROSIS independently decreases lymphatic vessel regeneration and function. Lymphedema significantly more prevalent in obese patients treated with surgery + radiation (risk factors are additive). INFECTION: one-third of lymphedema patients develop RECURRENT soft-tissue infections. Unclear if infection causes lymphedema or is a symptom of subclinical lymphedema. Bacteria cause lymphatic dysfunction via loss of lymphatic muscle cells (LMCs). Early postoperative infections significantly increase lymphedema incidence. GENETICS: connexin 47 and hepatocyte growth factor gene mutations increase secondary lymphedema risk â€” challenges the traditional view that secondary lymphedema is solely due to mechanical trauma.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "What is the evidence for anti-Th2 immunotherapy in lymphedema? Describe the phase I clinical trial results.", "answer": "Phase I clinical trial: open-label, single-arm study of 9 breast cancer-related lymphedema patients. Treatment: monthly IL-4 and IL-13 neutralizing antibody injections with 4-month washout. Results: (1) NO effect on limb volumes. (2) SIGNIFICANT decrease in skin stiffness (measured by tonometry). (3) Improved quality of life (validated lymphedema-specific QoL tool). (4) QoL scores returned to baseline after washout period (suggesting NOT placebo effect). Biopsy findings: Th2 blockade significantly decreased: epidermal thickness, skin collagen deposition, mast cell infiltration, T cell infiltration. Additional discovery: keratinocytes produce Th2-promoting cytokines (TSLP, IL-25, IL-33) that promote Th2 differentiation â€” these DECREASED after treatment, suggesting keratinocytes may play a role in lymphedema pathophysiology (active area of investigation). These findings support the Th2-mediated inflammatory model of lymphedema.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Anatomy and pathophysiology", "question": "What is the role of regulatory T cells (Tregs) in lymphedema? Why is their function paradoxical?", "answer": "Tregs have a DUAL (paradoxical) role in lymphedema: (1) BENEFICIAL: Tregs normally suppress inflammatory responses â€” inhibition of Tregs was shown to INCREASE tissue inflammatory responses in a preclinical model, resulting in MORE SEVERE lymphedema phenotype. This is because the Th2-mediated inflammatory cascade that drives lymphedema pathology becomes more intense without Treg suppression. (2) DETRIMENTAL: Lymphatic dysfunction causes increased infiltration of Tregs in lymphedematous tissues. These Tregs SUPPRESS host humoral and innate immunity and peripheral tolerance. Inhibition of Tregs was shown to IMPROVE bacterial clearance and immune responses in lymphedema. This explains why lymphedema patients are prone to recurrent infections â€” Tregs suppress the immune responses needed to fight pathogens. Clinical implication: therapeutic approaches must balance these opposing roles â€” blocking Tregs improves infection clearance but worsens lymphedema inflammation.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Lymphedema", "subtopic": "Diagnosis", "question": "What are the main patient-reported outcome measures (PROMs) used in lymphedema? What subscales does each measure?", "answer": "1) LYMQOL (Lymph Quality of Life Measure for Limb Lymphedema): upper and lower extremity; subscales: pain, mood, function, appearance, overall QoL. 2) ULL27 (Upper Limb Lymphedema 27): upper extremity only; subscales: physical, psychological, social. 3) LYMPH-ICF (Lymphedema Functioning, Disability and Health): upper and lower extremity; subscales: physical function, mental function, household activities, mobility activities, life/social activities. 4) LLIS (Lymphedema Life Impact Scale): upper and lower extremity; subscales: physical, psychosocial, functional, infection occurrence. 5) LYMPH-Q: upper extremity; subscales: arm symptoms, function, appearance, psychological function, satisfaction with information and arm sleeves. Developed to address limitations of existing PROMs (low reliability/validity, limited patient input). LYMPH-Q complements BREAST-Q for breast cancer patients. New scales in development for lymphedema burden and work impact.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Classification of skin cancers", "question": "What are the recommended surgical margins for wide excision of nonmelanocytic skin tumors: BCC, SCC, Merkel cell carcinoma, and soft-tissue sarcoma?", "answer": "HORIZONTAL MARGINS: BCC: low risk 4 mm, high risk 5-10 mm. SCC: low risk 4-6 mm, high risk 10 mm. Merkel cell carcinoma: 10-20 mm. Sarcoma: low risk 10 mm, high risk 20 mm. VERTICAL MARGINS based on depth of invasion: tumors limited to dermis â†’ excise with fat layer; tumors extending into fat â†’ excise with deep fascia; tumors extending into fascia â†’ excise with skeletal muscle; tumors into muscle â†’ excise with membranes of deeper structures (cartilage/bone); tumors into bone/cartilage membranes â†’ excise with those structures. General principle: at least one layer of barrier structure should be excised beyond the deepest plane of tumor invasion.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "BCC", "question": "Describe the histological classification of basal cell carcinoma (BCC). What are the key subtypes?", "answer": "WHO classification includes 10 types: (1) Multifocal superficial BCC (superficial multicentric), (2) Nodular BCC (solid, adenoid cystic), (3) Infiltrating BCC â€” subdivided into 3a nonsclerosing and 3b sclerosing (desmoplastic, morpheic), (4) Fibroepithelial BCC, (5) BCC with adnexal differentiation â€” 5a with follicular differentiation, 5b with eccrine differentiation, (6) Basosquamous carcinoma, (7) Keratotic BCC, (8) Pigmented BCC, (9) BCC in basal cell nevus syndrome, (10) Micronodular BCC. BCC is the MOST COMMON type of skin cancer. Rarely metastasizes but can invade surrounding tissues causing significant destruction/disfigurement. Most commonly affects head and neck. Treatment: surgical excision; Mohs micrographic surgery for complex cases; CO2 lasers or cryosurgery for selected superficial BCC.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "SCC", "question": "What are the precursor lesions and risk factors for cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (SCC)?", "answer": "SCC arises most commonly on DAMAGED SKIN. Precursor lesions and risk factors: (1) ACTINIC KERATOSIS: intraepidermal early-stage SCC from chronic UV exposure; atypical pleomorphic keratinocytes at basal layer extending upward; progresses to invasive SCC over time. (2) BOWEN'S DISEASE: intraepidermal carcinoma (carcinoma in situ) of keratinocytes; can progress to invasive SCC (then called Bowen's carcinoma, which can metastasize); classic feature: nonsteroid-responsive dermatosis. (3) Postburn scars â†’ MARJOLIN'S ULCER. (4) Traumatic scars. (5) Chronic stasis ulcers. (6) Chronic radiation dermatitis. (7) Lupus erythematosus lesions. (8) Lichen planus of oral mucosa. (9) HPV infection lesions. (10) KERATOACANTHOMA: controversial entity resembling SCC; grows rapidly, sometimes self-heals; atypical squamous cells on histology make it difficult to distinguish from SCC â€” excisional biopsy recommended.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Merkel cell carcinoma", "question": "Describe Merkel cell carcinoma: etiology, clinical features, and management.", "answer": "Merkel cell carcinoma: rare, HIGHLY AGGRESSIVE cancer developing on/beneath skin and in hair follicles. Etiology: majority caused by MERKEL CELL POLYOMAVIRUS (newly discovered). Clinical features: most common on face, head, and neck; appears as firm, PAINLESS nodules or tumors. Management: wide excision with 1-2 cm normal skin margin. Because it tends to METASTASIZE TO LYMPH NODES: sentinel lymph node biopsy and lymph node dissection should be considered. Adjuvant RADIATION THERAPY recommended for nearly all non-metastatic patients. Distant metastasis cases require CHEMOTHERAPY. Treatment fields should be large (3-5 cm margins from Ch27 data) due to propensity for in-transit and regional lymphatic spread.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Classification of skin cancers", "question": "Explain the TNM classification system for skin carcinoma. How do the T stages differ?", "answer": "TNM system (UICC): T = primary tumor size/invasion; N = regional lymph node involvement; M = distant metastasis. T STAGES for skin carcinoma (excluding eyelid, H&N, perianal, vulva, penis): Tis: carcinoma in situ. T1: â‰¤2 cm greatest dimension. T2: >2 cm and â‰¤4 cm. T3: >4 cm, OR minor bone erosion, OR perineural invasion, OR deep invasion. T4a: gross cortical bone/marrow invasion. T4b: axial skeleton invasion including foraminal and/or vertebral foramen involvement to epidural space. N STAGES: N0: no regional node metastasis. N1: single node â‰¤3 cm. N2: single ipsilateral node >3-6 cm, or multiple ipsilateral nodes â‰¤6 cm. N3: node >6 cm. STAGING: Stage 0 = Tis; Stage I = T1N0; Stage II = T2N0; Stage III = T3N0 or T1-3N1; Stage IVA = T1-3N2-3 or T4; Stage IVB = any M1. Note: pN0 requires â‰¥6 lymph nodes examined.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Classification of skin cancers", "question": "What is Mohs micrographic surgery? What are its indications and advantages?", "answer": "Mohs micrographic surgery: technique where tumors undergo HISTOLOGIC ANALYSIS DURING SURGERY so that almost ALL surgical margins can be examined for tumor extensions. Provides COMPLETE MARGIN CONTROL during removal. Advantages: (1) highest cure rate of all treatment modalities for nonmelanoma skin cancer, (2) maximal tissue conservation (removes only involved tissue), (3) real-time margin assessment. Indications: (1) BCC â€” frequently used, especially for complex cases, (2) SCC â€” frequently used (especially on nose/face), (3) Keratoacanthoma â€” especially on nose/face for good margin control with minimal tissue removal, (4) Dermatofibrosarcoma protuberans â€” with continuous histological margin control to reduce local recurrence, (5) Sweat gland carcinoma â€” reduces high recurrence rates of conventional excision, (6) Extramammary Paget's disease â€” helpful for determining normal skin margins for wide excision. Also useful for anatomically complex and cosmetically sensitive regions.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Classification of skin cancers", "question": "What is dermoscopy and how is it used in the two-step diagnostic algorithm for skin lesions?", "answer": "Dermoscopy: specialized technique employing a binocular microscope to observe skin surface. STEP 1: differentiate MELANOCYTIC from NONMELANOCYTIC lesions using dermoscopic criteria for melanocytic lesions (pigment network, negative network, aggregated globules, streaks, homogeneous blue pigmentation, pseudonetwork, parallel pattern). If melanocytic â†’ pattern analysis to categorize (malignant melanoma, Clark's nevus, Spitz/Reed nevus, congenital nevus, blue nevus, etc.). STEP 2: If nonmelanocytic â†’ evaluate sequentially for: SEBORRHEIC KERATOSIS (multiple milia-like cysts, comedo-like openings, fingerprint-like structures, fissures/ridges) â†’ BCC (absent pigment network PLUS arborizing vessels, leaf-like areas, large blue-gray ovoid nests, blue-gray globules, spoke wheel areas, ulceration) â†’ VASCULAR LESION (red-blue lacunas, red-bluish to red-black homogeneous areas). Essential for differentiating malignant melanoma from nevus and diagnosing BCC.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Classification of skin cancers", "question": "Compare the imaging characteristics of benign versus malignant skin tumors on MRI and Doppler ultrasound.", "answer": "MRI: MALIGNANT tumors typically show LOW-TO-ISOINTENSE signal on T2WI and LOW signal on T1WI. BENIGN tumors typically show HIGH signal on T2WI and LOW signal on T1WI. MRI detects soft tissues better than CT; magnetic resonance angiography superior for determining nidus and collateral structures in hemangiomas/vascular malformations. DOPPLER ULTRASOUND: 90% of MALIGNANT skin tumors exhibit HIGH BLOOD FLOW rate (3-20 cm/s) that is NOT observed in >95% of benign tumors. Power Doppler has higher resolution than color Doppler imaging (CDI). CDI useful for detecting blood flow in AVMs. M-mode and duplex scanning useful for hemangiomas/vascular malformations. HIGH-FREQUENCY ULTRASOUND (20-50 MHz): determines tumor thickness, relationship with adjacent structures, lymph node metastasis. For lesions extending >20 mm deep, standard ultrasound (3-10 MHz) should be used. CT: better for detecting bone, lymph node, and lung metastases than MRI.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Sarcomas", "question": "What is dermatofibrosarcoma protuberans (DFSP)? Describe its molecular pathology, clinical features, and treatment.", "answer": "DFSP (giant cell fibroblastoma): mesenchymal-origin malignant tumor. Molecular pathology: >90% have chromosomal translocation t(17;22) fusing COLLAGEN GENE COL1A1 with PLATELET-DERIVED GROWTH FACTOR (PDGF) gene. Clinical features: multiple or solitary tumors with RED color, hemispherical elevation, papillary vessels on surface; KELOIDAL APPEARANCE (sometimes misdiagnosed as keloid and treated with steroids). Metastasizes RARELY, but distant metastasis to lung can occur from local recurrence. Treatment: radical resection with 5 cm normal skin margin. MOHS MICROGRAPHIC SURGERY with continuous histological margin control needed to reduce local recurrence rates. Adjuvant chemotherapy and radiation therapy may be useful. Because of the COL1A1-PDGF fusion, imatinib (tyrosine kinase inhibitor targeting PDGF receptor) has shown efficacy in unresectable/metastatic cases.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Sarcomas", "question": "Describe angiosarcoma and Kaposi's sarcoma: etiology, clinical features, and management.", "answer": "ANGIOSARCOMA: malignant neoplasm of ENDOTHELIAL CELLS; subdivided into hemangiosarcoma and lymphangiosarcoma. Due to endothelial origin, metastasis to distant sites occurs OFTEN. Treatment: surgery, radiation, chemotherapy, immunotherapy (interleukin-2). Prognosis: generally POOR; superficial lesions have slightly better prognosis due to lower malignancy risk and better accessibility. KAPOSI'S SARCOMA: caused by KSHV (Kaposi's sarcoma-associated herpesvirus / HHV-8). Became widely known with AIDS epidemic in 1980s. Presentation: red, purple, brown, or black nodules/blotches that are papular (palpable/raised); found on skin but can spread to mouth, GI tract, respiratory tract. Growth ranges from very slow to explosively fast. Treatment: radiation therapy, cryotherapy, chemotherapy; surgery NOT primary choice (useful as supportive therapy); HIGHLY ACTIVE ANTIRETROVIRAL THERAPY (HAART) should be combined with other treatments in HIV-positive patients.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Classification of skin cancers", "question": "Describe the Leser-TrÃ©lat sign and its clinical significance.", "answer": "The sign of Leser-TrÃ©lat is the dramatic, SUDDEN APPEARANCE of MULTIPLE SEBORRHEIC KERATOSES. It is a PARANEOPLASTIC SYNDROME â€” an ominous sign of an INTERNAL MALIGNANCY. Features: not only do new lesions suddenly appear, but pre-existing lesions also frequently INCREASE IN SIZE and become SYMPTOMATIC. Clinical significance: this sign should NOT be overlooked. When observed, screening for INTERNAL MALIGNANCY should be recommended to the patient. Seborrheic keratosis itself is a benign growth originating from basal and squamous cells in the epidermis; it must be differentiated from nevus cell nevus, senile keratosis, BCC, and malignant melanoma.", "notes": "Closest match for paraneoplastic syndromes under skin cancers"}, {"topic": "Benign and congenital conditions", "subtopic": "Pigmented skin lesions", "question": "Classify pigment cell nevi. Which types have malignant potential?", "answer": "Five types of pigmented nevi: (1) LENTIGO SIMPLEX: black-brown, 2-3 mm; proliferation of melanocytes in basal layer; NOT induced by sun; earliest form of acquired nevus. (2) ACQUIRED PIGMENT CELL NEVUS: three subtypes by melanocyte location â€” JUNCTION (epidermis-dermis junction), COMPOUND (junction + dermis), INTRADERMAL (dermis only). Sutton's halo nevus has depigmented area around it. (3) CONGENITAL PIGMENT CELL NEVUS: present at birth; small (<1.5 cm), medium (1.5-20 cm), large/giant (>20 cm). (4) DYSPLASTIC NEVUS (Clark's nevus): resembles early melanoma; familial atypical mole and melanoma syndrome = melanoma in 1st/2nd-degree relative + numerous (>50) nevi + clinically atypical + specific histologic features. (5) SPITZ NEVUS (juvenile melanoma): dome-like, ~1 cm, face/legs of young patients; rapid growth then becomes static. MALIGNANT POTENTIAL: GIANT CONGENITAL NEVI can develop melanoma. De novo carcinogenesis theory: most melanomas arise directly from epidermal melanocytes, NOT from pre-existing nevi.", "notes": "Closest topic match; pigmented lesion classification not a standalone subtopic"}, {"topic": "Benign and congenital conditions", "subtopic": "Pigmented skin lesions", "question": "Compare nevus of Ota, nevus of Ito, and mongolian spots: origin, location, demographics, and treatment.", "answer": "All are DERMAL MELANOCYTOSES (melanocyte proliferation in dermis causing blue color). NEVUS OF OTA: distribution along V1 and V2 branches of trigeminal nerve; common in ASIANS, rare in Europeans; women 5x more affected; NOT congenital but appears in infancy and puberty; believed derived from melanocytes that didn't complete migration from neural crest to epidermis; treat with Q-switched ruby or alexandrite laser (4-8 treatments). NEVUS OF ITO: subtype of Ota; located on ACROMIODELTOID region; same treatment as Ota. MONGOLIAN SPOT (congenital dermal melanocytosis): sacral/coccygeal region; >90% Native American, 80% Asian, 70% Hispanic, <10% European infants; results from melanocyte entrapment in dermis during embryonic migration; DISAPPEARS before age 10; treatment usually unnecessary. Key: if a pigmented nevus >7 mm is still GROWING, consider malignant melanoma.", "notes": "Closest topic match; specific dermal melanocytoses not standalone subtopics"}, {"topic": "Benign and congenital conditions", "subtopic": "Pigmented skin lesions", "question": "What is the diagnostic significance of cafe-au-lait spots (nevus spilus)? When should neurofibromatosis be suspected?", "answer": "Nevus spilus (cafe-au-lait spot): benign tumor of melanocytes characterized by INCREASED MELANIN GRANULES (not melanocyte proliferation). Uniform cafe-au-lait color. Suspect NEUROFIBROMATOSIS TYPE 1 (NF1, von Recklinghausen's disease) when: â‰¥6 cafe-au-lait spots >5 mm in PREPUBERTY or >15 mm in POSTPUBERTY. NF1: mutation of chromosome band 17q11.2 encoding NEUROFIBROMIN. NF1 features: cutaneous neurofibromas (allow early diagnosis), cafe-au-lait spots. NF2 differences: patients RARELY have cafe-au-lait spots; do NOT have cutaneous neurofibromas but may have cutaneous schwannomas resembling skin tags; symptoms from cranial nerve VIII schwannomas usually begin in 3rd decade; diagnosed LATER than NF1.", "notes": "Closest topic match"}, {"topic": "Benign and congenital conditions", "subtopic": "Benign skin and subcutaneous tumors", "question": "Describe the clinical features, diagnosis, and management of schwannoma. What are the two histological types?", "answer": "Schwannoma (neurilemmoma): benign proliferation of SCHWANN CELLS in dermis/subcutaneous tissues. Associated with NF2 (multiple schwannomas). Two histological types (Antoni classification): TYPE A: numerous VEROCAY BODIES â€” acellular, eosinophilic areas (oval/linear/serpiginous) surrounded by parallel-lying or palisading bundles of spindled Schwann cells with blunt, elongated nuclei; long axes all oriented toward acellular area. TYPE B: LACKS Verocay bodies; loose, myxomatous stroma with fewer, randomly arranged spindle cells. Neither type contains neurites. Features: typically ENCAPSULATED; associated peripheral nerve visible microscopically. ANCIENT SCHWANNOMAS: older lesions with degenerative changes (hemorrhage, hemosiderin, chronic inflammation, fibrosis, nuclear pleomorphism) â€” benign but must differentiate from neurofibrosarcoma and malignant schwannoma. Treatment: surgical removal.", "notes": "Closest topic match; peripheral nerve tumors not a standalone subtopic"}, {"topic": "Benign and congenital conditions", "subtopic": "Benign skin and subcutaneous tumors", "question": "What is a glomus tumor? Describe the diagnostic signs and treatment.", "answer": "Glomus tumors arise from the arterial portion of the GLOMUS BODY (Sucquet-Hoyer canal), which is an arteriovenous anastomosis in the dermis involved in TEMPERATURE REGULATION. Presentation: SOLITARY lesions have PAROXYSMAL PAIN that can be severe, exacerbated by PRESSURE or TEMPERATURE CHANGES (especially cold). Multiple glomus tumors are less common; pain usually less severe. Classic location: subungual (under nail). Two diagnostic signs: (1) HILDRETH SIGN: disappearance of pain after a TOURNIQUET is placed on the proximal arm. (2) LOVE TEST: pain elicited by pressing the skin overlying the tumor with the tip of a PENCIL. Treatment: solitary â€” surgical excision (treatment of choice). Multiple â€” excision limited to SYMPTOMATIC lesions due to poor circumscription and large number of lesions.", "notes": "Closest topic match"}, {"topic": "Vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Classification of vascular anomalies", "question": "Classify vascular malformations and describe their associated syndromes.", "answer": "CAPILLARY MALFORMATIONS (hemangioma simplex): three types by location â€” (1) Portwine stain (face, limbs, upper body), (2) Salmon patch (medial forehead, glabella, nasal tip, upper lip), (3) Nevus Unna (nape). Only salmon patch can disappear within first year. Associated syndromes: STURGE-WEBER (facial portwine stain) and KLIPPEL-TRENAUNAY (limb). Patients need brain examination. Treatment: dye laser, Nd:YAG laser. STRAWBERRY HEMANGIOMA: endothelial cell proliferation; appears ~3-4 weeks after birth, peaks 6-7 months; volume rarely decreases naturally but color may fade; treat with laser EARLY. VENOUS MALFORMATION (cavernous hemangioma): low-flow blood-storing lesion; NO endothelial cell proliferation; seen in Klippel-Trenaunay syndrome. Treatment: sclerotherapy (ethanol, polidocanol, sodium tetradecyl sulfate). AVM: high-flow pulsating lesion with A-V shunt; Schobinger classification: I (quiescence), II (expansion), III (destruction), IV (decompensation with heart failure â€” PARKES-WEBER syndrome). Incomplete resection â†’ rapid regrowth.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Classification of skin cancers", "question": "Describe extramammary Paget's disease (EMPD): clinical features, associations, diagnosis, and treatment.", "answer": "EMPD: adenocarcinoma LIMITED TO THE EPIDERMIS (intraepidermal). Key distinction: Mammary Paget's disease is sometimes associated with invasive BREAST CANCER (considered intraepidermal proliferating breast carcinoma). EMPD is only OCCASIONALLY associated with underlying invasive malignancy. Location: vulva, penis, axilla. Clinical features: relatively HIGH INVASIVE SPEED making early detection difficult; often initially misdiagnosed as ECZEMA. Diagnosis and treatment: MOHS MICROGRAPHIC SURGERY or MAPPING BIOPSY to determine normal skin margins for wide excision. Sentinel lymph node biopsy useful for deciding whether to remove lymph nodes. Chemotherapy: 5-FU + mitomycin C; 5-FU + carboplatin + leucovorin; 5-FU + carboplatin + mitomycin C + epirubicin + vincristine.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Benign and congenital conditions", "subtopic": "Benign skin and subcutaneous tumors", "question": "Compare epidermoid cyst, dermoid cyst, trichilemmal cyst, and pilomatricoma: origin, location, features, and treatment.", "answer": "EPIDERMOID CYST (atheroma): smooth, dome-shaped, freely movable subcutaneous swelling; attached to skin by CENTRAL PORE; lined with stratified squamous epithelium resembling epidermis; contains keratin. Giant atheromas need pathology to rule out malignancy. Treatment: excision; for large cysts, contents removed first then walls extracted through minimal incision. DERMOID CYST: CONGENITAL subcutaneous cyst along embryonic lines of closure; most common on supraorbital region, brow, upper eyelid, glabella, scalp; contains keratin debris and hair shaft fragments; can undergo malignant change â€” complete removal recommended. TRICHILEMMAL CYST: from outer root sheath of hair follicle; most common on HAIRY SCALP; multiple in 70% of cases; resembles epidermoid cyst. Proliferating type has malignant potential. PILOMATRICOMA (calcifying epithelioma): cystic nodule on head/neck of young patients; CALCIFIED region visible on imaging; multiple pilomatricoma associated with MYOTONIC DYSTROPHY; no clear capsule â€” careful complete excision needed.", "notes": "Closest topic match"}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Sarcomas", "question": "What is a Marjolin's ulcer? In what clinical settings does SCC arise from chronic wounds or scars?", "answer": "MARJOLIN'S ULCER: squamous cell carcinoma arising in a POSTBURN SCAR. SCC can arise from many chronic wound/scar types: (1) Postburn scars (classic Marjolin's ulcer), (2) Traumatic scars, (3) Chronic stasis ulcers, (4) Chronic radiation dermatitis, (5) Lupus erythematosus lesions, (6) Lichen planus on oral mucosa, (7) HPV infection lesions. SCC characteristics: elevated, indurated lesion with varying degrees of ulceration and crusting; notable BAD SMELL from macerated keratin and bacterially infected necrotic tissues. Key differentiator from BCC: SCC can arise on ANY site but most common on damaged skin. Treatment: surgical excision; Mohs micrographic surgery frequently used; radiotherapy (external-beam or brachytherapy) also effective. Margins: low-risk SCC 4-6 mm, high-risk 10 mm.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Vascular anomalies", "subtopic": "Classification of vascular anomalies", "question": "Describe the Schobinger classification for arteriovenous malformations (AVMs). What is the treatment approach?", "answer": "Schobinger classification â€” four clinical stages: STAGE I (Quiescence): AVM present but clinically dormant. STAGE II (Expansion): AVM growing, pulsatile. STAGE III (Destruction): AVM causing tissue destruction, pain, bleeding, ulceration. STAGE IV (Decompensation): high-flow AVM causing CONGESTIVE HEART FAILURE (seen in Parkes-Weber syndrome with huge limb AVMs). AVMs are HIGH-FLOW PULSATING lesions with arteriovenous shunts; either acquired (trauma) or congenital. Color Doppler imaging (CDI) useful for detecting blood flow. Treatment: surgical removal is FIRST CHOICE but often hampered by diffuse vessel distribution and local anatomy (e.g., facial nerve). Critical principle: INCOMPLETE RESECTION results in RAPID REGROWTH of remaining lesion. For cases where surgical removal is difficult, embolosclerosing therapy used as palliative therapy.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Benign and congenital conditions", "subtopic": "Benign skin and subcutaneous tumors", "question": "Describe nevus sebaceous: what is it, where does it occur, and why should it be excised?", "answer": "Nevus sebaceous: a HAMARTOMA (not neoplasm) essentially confined to HEAD AND NECK regions. Found in sebaceous gland but also involves epidermis, dermis, hair follicles, and sweat glands â€” hence also called ORGANOID NEVUS. Resembles an epidermal nevus in appearance. Key clinical concern: other tumors like BCC and TRICHILEMMOMA can ARISE FROM nevus sebaceous over time â€” therefore complete surgical excision is RECOMMENDED. Surgical technique considerations: if located in hair, the HAIR STREAM should be carefully considered during excision and suturing; dehairing caused by unnecessary buried or dermal sutures should be avoided.", "notes": "Closest topic match"}, {"topic": "Scar assessment/treatment/revision", "subtopic": "Keloids/hypertrophic scars", "question": "What is the current understanding of the relationship between keloids and hypertrophic scars? What role do mechanical forces play?", "answer": "Keloids and hypertrophic scars (HTS) are caused by HYPERPRODUCTION OF COLLAGEN due to abnormal, prolonged cutaneous wound healing. MECHANICAL FORCES (skin-stretching tension) and MECHANOTRANSDUCTION signaling pathways are associated with their generation and growth. Differential diagnosis remains difficult â€” they may be manifestations of a FIBROPROLIFERATIVE DISORDER of the skin expressing a CONTINUUM of features. Clinical distinction: HTS improve NATURALLY and gradually (full maturation 2-5 years); KELOIDS RARELY resolve naturally. Treatment: MULTIMODAL therapy recommended â€” steroid ointment/tape/injection, taping fixation, silicone gel sheeting, surgery, radiation, cryotherapy, laser, and 5-FU.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Sarcomas", "question": "List the main types of malignant soft-tissue sarcomas of the skin and their key distinguishing features.", "answer": "(1) DFSP: t(17;22) COL1A1-PDGF translocation; keloidal appearance; rarely metastasizes; 5 cm margins. (2) PLEOMORPHIC UNDIFFERENTIATED SARCOMA (formerly MFH): four types (storiform-pleomorphic, myxoid, giant cell, inflammatory); atypical fibroxanthoma is superficial type; many reclassified as liposarcoma/leiomyosarcoma/rhabdomyosarcoma. (3) LIPOSARCOMA: from deep soft tissue fat cells; large bulky tumors with satellites; diagnosis requires LIPOBLASTS (multivacuolated cytoplasm, acentric nucleus). (4) LEIOMYOSARCOMA: from smooth muscle; limbs of middle-aged/older patients; can remain dormant and recur after years; not very responsive to chemo/RT. (5) RHABDOMYOSARCOMA: from skeletal muscle progenitors; three types â€” embryonal (younger children), alveolar (older children/teens), pleomorphic (older patients, rare). (6) OSTEOSARCOMA: mesenchymal origin with osteoblastic differentiation; produces malignant osteoid; radical en bloc resection. (7) CHONDROSARCOMA: not responsive to chemo/RT; proton beam RT showing promise.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Classification of skin cancers", "question": "Describe the axillary lymph node levels and the key structures to preserve during axillary lymph node dissection.", "answer": "Axillary lymph nodes classified by relationship to PECTORALIS MINOR MUSCLE: LEVEL I: lateral to (below lower edge of) pectoralis minor muscle. LEVEL II: deep to (underneath) pectoralis minor muscle. LEVEL III: medial to (above) pectoralis minor muscle. Structures that MUST be preserved during dissection: (1) Pectoral nerves (medial and lateral), (2) LONG THORACIC NERVE (injury â†’ winged scapula), (3) Intercostobrachial nerves (sensory to medial arm), (4) Axillary artery and veins, (5) Thoracoacromial artery and veins, (6) Subscapular artery and veins. Indications for axillary dissection include metastatic SCC and positive sentinel lymph node biopsy. With widespread use of sentinel lymph node biopsy, fewer occasions for preventive dissection.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are the histologic subtypes of melanoma? Describe their relative frequency, clinical features, and molecular characteristics.", "answer": "Traditional classification: (1) SUPERFICIAL SPREADING (SSM): 80% of melanomas; significant radial epidermal growth component; occurs in younger patients; frequently has BRAFV600E mutation; fulfills ABCDE criteria (asymmetry, border irregular, color variegated, diameter >6 mm, evolution). (2) NODULAR (NM): 14%; frequently ulcerated and AMELANOTIC (pink, raised papules); mitotically active throughout; grows rapidly with considerable depth relative to diameter; defined as no in situ component extending >3 rete ridges from invasive component. (3) LENTIGO MALIGNA MELANOMA (LMM): 5%; occurs in areas of chronic sun damage (solar elastosis); poorly circumscribed; may be amelanotic; majority have NEITHER BRAF NOR NRAS mutation. (4) ACRAL LENTIGINOUS (ALM): 1% in Europeans but EQUAL INCIDENCE across all skin types; occurs on glabrous skin (palms, soles) and nailbeds; NOT related to UVR (protected by thick stratum corneum); frequent copy number variations, few point mutations (low mutational burden).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are the recommended wide local excision margins for primary cutaneous melanoma at different Breslow thicknesses?", "answer": "Based on multiple randomized controlled trials: MELANOMA IN SITU: 5-10 mm margin recommended (5 mm may be inadequate in up to 50% of cases, particularly lentigo maligna subtype; 10 mm recommended where feasible). MELANOMAS â‰¤2 mm Breslow thickness: 1 cm surgical margin. MELANOMAS >2 mm Breslow thickness: 2 cm surgical margin. No data exist that margins WIDER than 2 cm result in superior disease-specific outcomes. Key distinctions: 1 cm margins usually allow PRIMARY CLOSURE under local anesthesia with minimal morbidity; 2 cm margins often require general anesthesia and may need SKIN GRAFT or complex locoregional flap reconstruction. Important: all margins refer to SURGICAL (in vivo) margins, not pathologic margins â€” there is typically ~14% tissue shrinkage after excision and formalin fixation. MELMART-II trial (ongoing) investigating 1 cm vs 2 cm for pT2b-pT4b melanomas.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Describe the AJCC 8th Edition melanoma staging system: T categories, N categories, and M categories.", "answer": "T CATEGORY (Breslow thickness + ulceration): T1: â‰¤1.0 mm (a: <0.8 mm without ulceration; b: <0.8 mm with ulceration or 0.8-1.0 mm). T2: >1.0-2.0 mm. T3: >2.0-4.0 mm. T4: >4.0 mm. Each subdivided into a (without ulceration) and b (with ulceration). N CATEGORY: includes regional nodal disease AND in-transit/satellite/microsatellite disease (all represent intralymphatic metastases). Microsatellites: within 2 cm of primary; satellites: clinically detected within 2 cm; in-transit: beyond 2 cm but proximal to regional nodes. Subcategory 'a' = clinically occult (SLNB-detected); 'b' = clinically detected; 'c' = intralymphatic without nodal disease. M CATEGORY: M1a = distant skin/soft tissue/nonregional nodes; M1b = lung; M1c = non-CNS visceral sites; M1d = CNS metastases (NEW in 8th edition â€” worst prognosis). LDH suffix: (0) normal, (1) elevated. For T2-T4, SLNB required for accurate N staging (clinical exam detects only ~24% of SLNB-positive patients).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What is sentinel lymph node biopsy (SLNB) in melanoma? Describe the technique, indications, and key trial evidence.", "answer": "SLNB: technique first described by Donald Morton and Alistair Cochrane's team. Identifies sentinel lymph nodes (first nodes draining the primary site) using DUAL lymphatic mapping: (1) preoperative LYMPHOSCINTIGRAPHY (Tc99m-labeled colloid), (2) intraoperative BLUE DYE. Combined technique identifies sentinel nodes in >99% of patients with ~96% accuracy for nodal basin status. SPECT/CT hybrid imaging provides precise 3D anatomical localization. Indications (NCCN): routinely offered when risk of positive node >10% (generally melanomas >1.0 mm thick); considered when risk 5-10%. Increasing age is a NEGATIVE predictor of SN positivity. KEY TRIALS: MSLT-I: no overall survival difference, but subgroup analysis showed improved MSS in SN-positive intermediate-thickness melanomas (HR 0.56). MSLT-II and DeCOG-SLT: completion lymphadenectomy (CLND) for SN-positive patients increased nodal basin control but did NOT improve MSS â†’ CLND largely abandoned in favor of observation with ultrasound surveillance + adjuvant systemic therapy.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Describe the immune checkpoint inhibitors used in melanoma: mechanisms, agents, and key efficacy data.", "answer": "ANTI-CTLA-4: IPILIMUMAB (FDA approved 2011). Mechanism: CTLA-4 and CD28 compete for B7-1/B7-2 ligands on antigen-presenting cells. CTLA-4 provides INHIBITORY signals; CD28 provides STIMULATORY signals. Ipilimumab blocks CTLA-4, suppressing inhibitory signals and enhancing anti-tumor T-cell response. ANTI-PD-1: NIVOLUMAB and PEMBROLIZUMAB (FDA approved 2015). Mechanism: melanoma cells express PD-L1; when PD-1 on cytotoxic T-cells binds PD-L1, T-cell enters ANERGY (tumor-mediated immune suppression). Anti-PD-1 antibodies prevent this binding, enhancing antitumor response. EFFICACY: both nivolumab and pembrolizumab are SUPERIOR to ipilimumab alone for advanced melanoma. Nivolumab + ipilimumab COMBINATION is superior to nivolumab alone. Stage IV: 5-year OS up to 52% with modern ICI therapy. ADJUVANT: pembrolizumab and nivolumab show significant improvement in relapse-free survival for resected stage III melanoma.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What is BRAF/MEK targeted therapy in melanoma? Describe the pathway, agents, and when it is indicated.", "answer": "The MAPK pathway (RAS â†’ BRAF â†’ MEK â†’ ERK) is constitutively activated in ~40% of advanced melanomas by BRAFV600E/K driver mutations, leading to unregulated cell growth. BRAF INHIBITORS: vemurafenib, dabrafenib, encorafenib. Single-agent BRAF inhibitor is NOT recommended because resistance inevitably develops via MAPK pathway reactivation. COMBINED BRAF/MEK treatment (e.g., dabrafenib + trametinib) shows increased efficacy with improved response rate, progression-free survival, and overall survival. INDICATIONS: (1) Metastatic/unresectable stage III/IV melanoma with BRAFV600E/K mutation. (2) Adjuvant therapy for resected stage IIIA-C BRAFV600-mutant melanoma. (3) NEOADJUVANT therapy showing promise â€” pathologic complete response in up to 58%. Toxicity: pyrexia/chills, fatigue, diarrhea, hypertension, vomiting â€” generally RESOLVE RAPIDLY after discontinuation (unlike some ICI toxicities which can be permanent).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What is desmoplastic melanoma? Describe its clinical features, diagnostic challenges, and management.", "answer": "Desmoplastic melanoma (DM): rare (~1%) subtype usually found in areas of HIGH cumulative sun damage, especially HEAD AND NECK. Clinical features: firm 'SCAR-LIKE' lesions with minimal or no pigmentation â€” often NOT in the differential diagnosis of melanoma. Due to clinical and histological subtlety, DMs typically have HIGHER Breslow thickness at diagnosis than other subtypes. Histology: sparse BLAND SPINDLE CELLS separated by abundant collagen â€” can be misdiagnosed as 'scar' (a 'scar' diagnosis without clear trauma history should raise suspicion). Classification: 'PURE' DM (â‰¥90% desmoplastic component) = lower risk of sentinel node positivity. 'MIXED' DM (10-89%) = higher risk. Neurotropism: most commonly found in DM (perineural, intraneural, or neural transforming); increases likelihood of close/involved margins and local recurrence risk. Management: wide excision; if adequate margins cannot be achieved, adjuvant RADIOTHERAPY may be indicated.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Describe the ABCDE rule and dermoscopy for melanoma diagnosis. What sensitivity/specificity do they provide?", "answer": "ABCDE rule: A = ASYMMETRICAL lesion, B = BORDER irregular, C = COLOR multiple/variegated, D = DIAMETER >6 mm, E = EVOLUTION (history of change). When used by dermatologists: sensitivity 73%, specificity 78%. DERMOSCOPY: 10-16x magnification with polarized light; 'TWO-STEP APPROACH': Step 1 = classify lesion as melanocytic or nonmelanocytic. Step 2 = for melanocytic lesions, assess specific features to determine benign vs malignant. Melanoma features include: atypical network, streaks, negative pigment network, crystalline structures (shiny white lines), atypical dots/globules, off-centered blotches, blue-white veil, regression structures, atypical vascular structures. Dermoscopy increases sensitivity to 90% while maintaining specificity AND reduces benign-to-malignant biopsy rate by up to 64%. REFLECTANCE CONFOCAL MICROSCOPY: 3-5 Î¼m slice thickness, up to 350 Î¼m depth; sensitivity 91-100%, specificity 68-91%; especially useful for amelanotic lesions and delineating lentigo maligna margins.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are the risk factors for developing melanoma? Describe the genetic predisposition syndromes.", "answer": "Risk factors: UVR exposure (especially intermittent high doses), fair skin, previous melanoma/NMSC, immunosuppression, family history, high total nevus count, solariums. GENETIC: MC1R high-penetrance variants: biallelic = red hair phenotype + OR 4.4 for melanoma; single allele = no red hair but OR 2.6. Total nevus count (TNC) â‰¥20 nevi >5mm: more significant than MC1R variants; OR 4.8 (even without MC1R variants). INTERACTION IS MULTIPLICATIVE: high TNC + biallelic MC1R = OR 25.1. FAMILIAL MELANOMA (~15% report family history, but most due to shared sun exposure/phenotypes): CDKN2A or CDK4 germline mutations account for ~45% of true familial cases. These genes linked to FAMMM syndrome (familial atypical mole multiple melanoma, formerly 'dysplastic nevus syndrome'). Features: early age of melanoma onset, multiple melanomas, family history, many dysplastic nevi, PANCREATIC CANCER. Development of acquired nevi appears initiated by BRAFV600E gene mutation.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Describe acral and subungual melanoma: etiology, clinical features, dermoscopic findings, and biopsy considerations.", "answer": "ACRAL MELANOMA (AM): occurs on GLABROUS (non-hair-bearing) skin of palms, soles, and nailbeds. Etiology: NOT related to UVR (thick stratum corneum scatters UV, protecting melanocytes); trauma postulated; equal incidence across ALL SKIN TYPES. Genomic profile: frequent copy number variations, few point mutations (low mutational burden) â€” different from CSD-related melanomas. Clinical features on palmar/plantar skin: follows ABCDE criteria; starts as spreading patch; may not appear raised due to thick stratum corneum; frequently POORLY CIRCUMSCRIBED. Dermoscopy: PARALLEL RIDGE PATTERN is 86% sensitive and 98% specific for early AM. SUBUNGUAL: arises from germinal matrix (must include in biopsy); HUTCHINSON'S SIGN = hyperpigmentation of proximal nailfold. Concerning features: streak wider at base than distally (rapid growth), blurred edges, sudden darkening/widening, nail dystrophy, single digit in 4th-6th decade. Biopsy: punch/incisional may be necessary for large lesions to avoid morbidity.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are Clark's levels? Are they still used for staging?", "answer": "Clark's levels describe the anatomical depth of melanoma invasion: LEVEL I: confined to epidermis (melanoma in situ). LEVEL II: into the papillary dermis but does NOT fill or expand this layer. LEVEL III: FILLS or EXPANDS the papillary dermis and reaches the junction with the reticular dermis. LEVEL IV: into the RETICULAR dermis. LEVEL V: into SUBCUTANEOUS tissue. Clark's level was REMOVED from the AJCC staging system in the 7th Edition (2009) after it was found to have the LOWEST independent prognostic significance on multivariable analysis for survival that included tumor mitotic rate. Breslow thickness (measured from granular layer of epidermis to deepest tumor in mm, perpendicular to skin surface) is the primary measurement used for T staging. Reported to nearest 0.1 mm in AJCC 8th Edition.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are the important histopathological features reported in melanoma beyond Breslow thickness and ulceration?", "answer": "NEUROTROPISM: melanoma cells abutting nerve sheaths at tumor periphery; three forms: perineural, intraneural, neural transformation. Most common in desmoplastic melanoma. Increases likelihood of close/involved margins â†’ increased local recurrence risk. May warrant adjuvant radiotherapy if greater margins not feasible. LYMPHOVASCULAR INVASION (LVI): melanoma cells within lymphatic or blood vessel lumina; generally a POOR prognostic factor; detection enhanced by staining with endothelial markers (CD31, CD34) and lymphatic markers (D2-40, LYVE-1). TUMOR INFILTRATING LYMPHOCYTES (TILs): lymphocytes opposing or infiltrating tumor cell nests; graded as absent, non-brisk (focal), or brisk (diffuse/entire base). Brisk TIL infiltrate is a GOOD prognostic factor. MICROSATELLITOSIS: tumor deposits in cutaneous/subcutaneous tissue within 2 cm of primary, truly separate from main mass (not just fibrosis/inflammation); rare (5-10% in intermediate thickness); classified as N1c in AJCC staging.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are the biopsy recommendations for suspected melanocytic lesions? Why are incomplete biopsies problematic?", "answer": "RECOMMENDED: EXCISION BIOPSY with 2 mm margin â€” offers best opportunity for correct pathologic diagnosis. INCOMPLETE BIOPSIES (punch, incision, curette, shave) are problematic because: (1) May contribute to significant pathologic MISDIAGNOSIS rate (both false-positives and false-negatives). (2) Unrepresentative sampling of HETEROGENEOUS tumor risks incorrect diagnosis. (3) Insufficient tissue for adequate assessment of pathologic criteria. (4) Shave biopsy TRANSECTING the base precludes accurate BRESLOW THICKNESS measurement â€” patient may not be offered appropriate SLNB. Rate of incomplete excision with shave biopsies: up to 97%. EXCEPTIONS: incisional biopsy acceptable when excision not feasible (e.g., large facial lentigo maligna â€” broad superficial shave appropriate when dermal invasion suspicion is low). KEY: false-negative rate significantly reduced by writing the SUSPECTED DIAGNOSIS on the pathology request form. All melanocytic tumors should be assessed by an expert DERMATOPATHOLOGIST.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What is lentigo maligna? How does it differ from lentigo maligna melanoma? What is its risk of progression?", "answer": "LENTIGO MALIGNA (LM): melanoma IN SITU occurring in the presence of significant chronic sun damage to the skin; historically called 'Hutchinson's melanotic freckle'. An IN SITU lesion (abnormal melanocytes confined to epidermis). Risk of progression to INVASIVE melanoma (LMM) estimated up to 3.5% PER YEAR, resulting in mean time to progression of 28 years. LENTIGO MALIGNA MELANOMA (LMM): progression of LM to dermal INVASION â€” a different entity than LM. LMM lesions are often POORLY CIRCUMSCRIBED both clinically and histologically; may be amelanotic or slightly pigmented; can extend well beyond visible lesion. Typically on chronically sun-exposed sites (face, forearms). Majority have NEITHER BRAF NOR NRAS mutations. Clinical significance of MIS in general: (1) signifies 5-10-fold elevated risk of developing FURTHER primary melanomas (lifelong surveillance needed), (2) without complete excision, INVASIVE component cannot be completely excluded.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Describe the congenital melanocytic nevus (CMN): classification, melanoma risk, and management.", "answer": "Classification by projected adult size: SMALL (<1.5 cm), MEDIUM (1.5-20 cm), GIANT (>20 cm). Prevalence: ~1% of population (vast majority small); giant = ~1/20,000 live births. Appearance: irregular pigmentation with hyperpigmented papules, sometimes hair; often deep and larger than acquired nevi. MELANOMA RISK: small CMN = very low; giant CMN = ~2% overall; highest risk (8%) in giant CMNs >60 cm projected adult size or multiple CMNs without single large lesion; highest risk (12%) if also abnormal brain MRI screening in first year of life. KEY POINTS: (1) Surgical excision of giant CMN does NOT completely remove melanoma risk â€” melanoma can develop at OTHER sites including LEPTOMENINGEAL. (2) Superficial removal techniques (e.g., dermabrasion) have NO EFFECT on final color of lesion â€” final color determined by normal skin color in process of spontaneous lightening. Management: giant nevi removed by serial excision, skin grafting, local flaps, or combination.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What is the WHO 2018 classification of melanoma? How does it differ from the traditional classification?", "answer": "WHO 2018 classification defines 9 subtypes by their DISTINCT EVOLUTIONARY PATHWAYS, grouped into three categories: GROUP A (associated with cumulative solar damage/CSD): Pathway I: SSM (low CSD); Pathway II: LMM (high CSD); Pathway III: Desmoplastic melanoma (high CSD). GROUP B (NOT associated with CSD): Pathway IV: Spitz melanomas; Pathway V: Acral melanomas; Pathway VI: Mucosal melanomas; Pathway VII: Melanomas arising in congenital nevi; Pathway VIII: Melanomas arising in blue nevi; Pathway IX: Uveal melanomas. GROUP C (can occur in most pathways): Nodular melanoma (NM) Â± CSD association. Key difference from traditional classification: organized by EVOLUTIONARY PATHWAY rather than morphology alone, recognizing that different subtypes have distinct molecular drivers (BRAF mutations in SSM, copy number variations in ALM, neither BRAF nor NRAS in LMM).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Describe the route of melanoma metastasis, the definitions of satellites, microsatellites, and in-transit metastases.", "answer": "Melanoma metastasizes through LYMPHATIC channels in ~90% of cases; direct hematogenous dissemination is less common. All intralymphatic metastases portend similarly poor prognosis and are included in the N category (AJCC 8th Edition). MICROSATELLITES: tumor deposits in cutaneous/subcutaneous tissue in the initial excision biopsy or wide local excision specimen, discrete from the main primary mass, within the pathologic specimen (effectively within 2 cm). Must be TRULY separate (not just fibrosis/inflammation between them). Rates: 5-10% in intermediate-thickness melanoma. SATELLITES: clinically detected tumor deposits within 2 cm of primary. IN-TRANSIT METASTASES: tumor deposits beyond 2 cm from primary but PROXIMAL to regional lymph nodes. N staging: N1c = intralymphatic deposits WITHOUT nodal disease; N2c = intralymphatic + single positive node; N3c = intralymphatic + multiple positive nodes. Important: deposits in DEEP structures (e.g., muscle) = stage IV, not stage III.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are the immune-related adverse events (irAEs) of checkpoint inhibitor immunotherapy? How do they differ from BRAF/MEK inhibitor toxicities?", "answer": "ICI irAEs: inflammatory AUTOIMMUNE toxicities in nearly any organ system. Premature treatment termination: <10% monotherapy, >30% combination therapy. Common irAEs: interstitial pneumonia, COLITIS, hypothyroidism, liver dysfunction, skin rash, vitiligo, hypophysitis, type 1 diabetes, renal dysfunction, myasthenia gravis, neuropathy, myositis, uveitis. Most irAEs are LOW-GRADE and respond rapidly to STEROIDS and immunosuppressants. EXCEPTION: most ENDOCRINOPATHIES are PERMANENT (hypopituitarism, hypothyroidism, hypoadrenalism, type I diabetes). No identified predictive factors â†’ rely on EARLY DETECTION and rapid intervention. BRAF/MEK TOXICITY (markedly different): pyrexia/chills, fatigue, diarrhea, hypertension, vomiting. Key distinction: toxicities generally RESOLVE RAPIDLY after discontinuation of treatment (unlike permanent endocrinopathies from ICI).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "What are the Sappey's lines and how has lymphoscintigraphy changed our understanding of lymphatic drainage patterns?", "answer": "SAPPEY'S LINES: lymphatic drainage patterns mapped by Sappey in 1874 using mercury injection into skin. General principles: lesions >2 cm ABOVE a 'belt line' (drawn through umbilicus) drain to AXILLARY nodes; >2 cm BELOW drain to INGUINAL nodes. Lesions >2 cm lateral to midline drain IPSILATERALLY. Lesions within the central 4 cm vertical and horizontal bands could drain to EITHER or BOTH sides and either or both axillary/inguinal nodes. MODERN LYMPHOSCINTIGRAPHY: has demonstrated many VARIATIONS in lymphatic drainage â€” very few body sites have reliably predictable drainage. This is why preoperative lymphoscintigraphy is essential for SLNB rather than relying on Sappey's lines alone. Techniques: Tc99m with various tracers (antimony sulfide colloid, nanocolloid, tilmanocept preferred over sulfur colloid); SPECT/CT hybrid imaging provides precise 3D anatomical localization of sentinel nodes, especially helpful in HEAD/NECK and PELVIS.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Describe the role and indications for adjuvant radiotherapy in melanoma.", "answer": "Adjuvant radiotherapy post-lymphadenectomy improves NODAL BASIN CONTROL in high-risk disease but confers NO OVERALL SURVIVAL benefit. Indications for consideration: (1) Multinodal disease â€” any parotid disease, â‰¥2 nodes in neck/axilla, â‰¥3 nodes in groin. (2) EXTRANODAL SPREAD. (3) Large involved node (â‰¥3 cm neck, â‰¥4 cm axilla/groin). (4) POSITIVE MARGIN. (5) Recurrent disease after previous surgery. (6) Desmoplastic melanoma with neurotropism where adequate surgical margins cannot be achieved. Limitations: lack of survival benefit must be balanced against morbidity of salvage lymphadenectomy, especially in the era of MORE EFFECTIVE SYSTEMIC THERAPY. Still has a role when ICI immunotherapy is unlikely to be tolerated or CONTRAINDICATED (e.g., autoimmune disease, solid organ transplantation). Note: melanoma is considered relatively RADIORESISTANT (broad shoulder on cell survival curve); overcome by HYPOFRACTIONATION (e.g., 6 Gy twice/week).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Skin cancers and oncology principles", "subtopic": "Melanoma", "question": "Describe the current approach to neoadjuvant therapy in stage III melanoma. What are the key trial results?", "answer": "Emerging data suggest NEOADJUVANT (before surgery) therapy may have increased therapeutic efficacy OVER adjuvant (after surgery) therapy for clinically evident regional metastasis. Key regimens and results: (1) DABRAFENIB + TRAMETINIB neoadjuvant: pathologic complete response (pCR) in 49-58%; neoadjuvant arm showed dramatically better disease-free outcomes vs adjuvant-only arm. (2) NIVOLUMAB + IPILIMUMAB neoadjuvant: pCR rates 45-57%; 2-cycle regimen showing pathologic response in up to 80%. (3) PEMBROLIZUMAB neoadjuvant: pCR/major pathologic response in 29.6%; 63% DFS and 93% OS at 2 years. Clinical implications: (1) In patients with neoadjuvant therapy showing radiologic response, more SELECTIVE surgery with nerve/vessel preservation may be oncologically sound. (2) Final pathology after neoadjuvant often shows pigmented macrophages WITHOUT viable melanoma. (3) Duration of adjuvant treatment (anti-PD1 or dabrafenib/trametinib) arbitrarily set at 1 year â€” optimal duration still unclear.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Define 'biomaterial' per the NIH definition, and describe how the definition has broadened with tissue engineering.", "answer": "NIH definition: any substance (other than a drug) or combination of substances, synthetic or natural in origin, which can be used for any period of time, as a whole or part of a system which treats, augments, or replaces tissue, organ, or function of the body. Broadened definition: any material used in a medical device intended to interact with biological systems â€” this includes structures and combination devices that actively interact with the body. Biomaterials can be classified as SYNTHETIC (man-made) or BIOLOGICAL (produced by a biological system). General categories: metals, polymers, ceramics, glues, skin substitutes, and bioprosthetics.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "List the properties of an ideal implant as described by Cumberland and Scales.", "answer": "(1) Minimal foreign-body response, (2) Elastic or supple, (3) Can be tailored easily, (4) Good tissue incorporation, (5) Allows collagen ingrowth, (6) Promotes permanent tissue repair, (7) Good tensile strength, (8) Tolerates infected environment, (9) Minimal wound complications. These criteria were published ~60 years ago but remain the fundamental properties that all modern biomaterials attempt to achieve.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Compare stainless steel, cobalt-chromium, and titanium alloys for medical implant use: composition, advantages, disadvantages, and current applications.", "answer": "STAINLESS STEEL (316L): iron-chromium-nickel alloy with >=17% chromium, low carbon, high nickel. Advantages: high tensile strength, easily bent (useful for arch bars). Disadvantages: can leach metallic ions causing inflammatory reaction/pain, less desirable mechanical properties than alternatives. Current use: surgical wire, arch bars. COBALT-CHROMIUM (CoCrMo/Vitallium): ~60% cobalt, 25-30% chromium, 5-7% molybdenum. Advantages: corrosion resistant, strong. Disadvantage: significant CT scatter artifact. Largely replaced by titanium; still used in dental applications. TITANIUM: strongest, lightest, highest corrosion resistance, lowest inflammation. <0.5% iron â€” does NOT trigger metal detectors, minimal CT/MRI artifact. Less stress shielding (less stiffness = less localized osteopenia). Unique property: forms chemical bonds with mineralized bone (OSSEOINTEGRATION) without intervening fibrous tissue. Used for plates, screws, orbital mesh.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "What is stress shielding, and why is titanium advantageous in this regard?", "answer": "Stress shielding: localized osteopenia secondary to a metal implant protecting bone from normal physiological loading. When an implant is stiffer than bone, it bears a disproportionate share of mechanical loads, causing the bone underneath to resorb due to lack of stimulus (Wolff's law). Titanium has LESS stiffness than other metal alloys (stainless steel, cobalt-chromium), resulting in less stress shielding and better preservation of underlying bone density.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "What are the medical applications of gold and platinum in plastic surgery? What determines the choice between them for eyelid weights?", "answer": "GOLD: chemically inert but poor mechanical properties in pure form. For eyelid weights in lagophthalmos (e.g., facial nerve palsy): 24-carat gold (99.9% purity) is used to ensure chemical inertness. PLATINUM: also inert, used in patients with GOLD SENSITIVITY. Key advantage: platinum is DENSER than gold, so eyelid implants have a LOWER PROFILE and are less noticeable. Platinum is also used as a catalyst (platinum black) in silicone gel breast implant manufacturing. Cisplatin (platinum complex) is a chemotherapeutic agent with side effects including cumulative irreversible kidney damage and deafness.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Differentiate the silicone nomenclature: silicon, silica, silicate, siloxane, silicone, and poly-dimethylsiloxane (PDMS).", "answer": "SILICON (Si): most abundant element on earth; does not occur naturally in metallic state. SILICA (SiO2): sand, marble, or quartz. SILICATE (Na2SiO3): used as desiccant (e.g., in anesthesia machines). SILOXANE (R2SiO): monomer of silicon and oxygen â€” the basic repeating unit of silicone. SILICONE (|R2SiO|n): polymers of silicon and oxygen. POLY-DIMETHYLSILOXANE/PDMS (|(CH3)2SiO|n): the building block for most medical-grade silicone products including breast implants; silicon-oxygen backbone with two methyl side chains; one of the most inert biomaterials available.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "How do the mechanical properties of silicone change with molecular weight and cross-linking? Describe the hydrosilation reaction in breast implant manufacturing.", "answer": "Molecular weight effects: PDMS with <30 monomers = low-molecular-weight, viscosity similar to baby oil. >3000 monomers = high-molecular-weight, solid. Cross-linking: as polymer chains are cross-linked, ability to move independently decreases â€” liquid becomes gel becomes solid. HYDROSILATION REACTION: some methyl side chains (CH3) are replaced by VINYL side chains (CH=CH2), allowing silicone chains to cross-link with each other. This reaction is catalyzed by PLATINUM â€” residual platinum can be found in silicone gel breast implants. The silicone SHELL is fully polymerized silicone with amorphous (noncrystalline) silica filler added for strength. Cohesive gel implants: extensively cross-linked silicone that retains shape even if implant ruptures.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "Describe the FDA regulatory timeline for silicone gel breast implants: key dates, decisions, and the IOM findings.", "answer": "1962: silicone gel-filled breast implants first introduced in US. 1988: FDA relabeled as class III medical devices, called for safety/effectiveness data. 1992: FDA claimed 'inadequate information to demonstrate safety and efficacy'; placed MORATORIUM on silicone gel implants for cosmetic use (still allowed for reconstruction, congenital deformities, replacement of ruptured implants). 1999: IOM released comprehensive report 'Safety of Silicone Breast Implants' â€” found 'diseases such as connective tissue diseases, cancer, neurological diseases are NO MORE COMMON in women with implants than without.' 2006: FDA lifted ban; required 10-year study on current recipients PLUS additional 10-year study in 40,000 women; mandated patient brochures explaining risks. Key: over 35 well-conducted studies from many countries found no conclusive evidence silicone causes disease.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "Describe the ISO classification of breast implant surface texturing. What manufacturing processes create textured surfaces?", "answer": "ISO 14607:2018 classification by average roughness: SMOOTH (<10 Âµm), MICROTEXTURED (10-50 Âµm), MACROTEXTURED (>50 Âµm). Manufacturing processes: (1) SALT-LOSS: salt crystals applied onto silicone shell before curing, removed by rinsing afterward; creates coarse, granular texture (e.g., Allergan BIOCELL surface). (2) IMPRINT-STAMPING: generates finer, more homogenous surface texture (e.g., Mentor Siltex surface). Purported benefits: tissue ingrowth, improved adherence, reduced rotation, and decreased capsular contracture. Recent evidence challenges these: long-term studies show minimal difference in contracture rates between textured and smooth. Macrotextured devices (roughness >80 Âµm) linked to highest foreign body response and inflammation. Use of textured implants has dropped precipitously in the US.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Breast cancer/reconstruction basics", "subtopic": "Implant-based reconstruction", "question": "Describe the relationship between textured breast implants and BIA-ALCL: epidemiology, hypothesized mechanisms, and FDA actions.", "answer": "BIA-ALCL: CD30-positive, ALK-negative T-cell non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. First sentinel case reported 1997. Only observed in patients with TEXTURED surface implants. Over 1,150 women worldwide diagnosed. FDA 2011: safety communication about 'very small but increased risk.' July 2019: FDA ordered CLASS I VOLUNTARY RECALL of all Allergan textured devices. Risk is HIGHER in macrotextured devices. Hypothesized mechanisms: (1) increased biofilm development, (2) shell shedding of particulates causing perpetual exhaustive phagocytosis and cytokine release by macrophages, (3) increased mechanical shear/friction stresses at implant-tissue interface causing overt inflammatory response. Macrotextured devices linked to chronic inflammation; animal studies confirm highest severity foreign body response with roughness >80 Âµm. Causal link not yet definitively established.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Compare PTFE (Teflon) and expanded PTFE (ePTFE/Gore-Tex): structure, properties, and medical applications. What are the limitations of ePTFE mesh?", "answer": "PTFE: carbon backbone with fluorine side chains; chemically very stable, cannot be cross-linked (making it flexible), nonadherent surface. ePTFE (Gore-Tex): created by Bob Gore (1969) by rapidly stretching heated PTFE rods â€” transforms solid PTFE into microporous structure that is more lightweight and pliable. Medical applications: vascular grafts, mesh for abdominal wall reconstruction, facial augmentation implants. ePTFE mesh limitations for hernia repair: (1) infection often requires EXPLANTATION (cannot be salvaged), (2) limited incorporation strength to surrounding fascial edge compared to macroporous meshes (polypropylene), (3) pore size 10-30 Âµm limits tissue ingrowth â€” this same property reduces repair site adhesions (advantage for visceral-facing surface).", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Compare polypropylene and polyethylene (Medpor) as biomaterials: structure, applications, advantages, and complications.", "answer": "POLYPROPYLENE: carbon backbone with hydrogen and methyl side chains. Applications: hernia repair mesh, sutures, pelvic organ prolapse repair. Advantages: rarely rejected, high ultimate tensile strength, strong fibrovascular incorporation. Complications: can erode through soft tissues over time; FDA warnings for pelvic organ prolapse mesh near vaginal wall due to erosion. Direct placement over viscera causes dense adhesions, fistula, and erosion. Reoperation challenging due to fibrotic scarring to intraperitoneal viscera. HIGH-DENSITY POROUS POLYETHYLENE (Medpor): carbon backbone with hydrogen side chains (ethylene). Applications: facial implants, orbital floor reconstruction (alone or with embedded titanium mesh). Advantages: porosity allows tissue and vascular ingrowth, can be carved/customized. Disadvantages: firm/stiff, difficult to place (tissue adheres readily), difficult to remove (due to ingrowth), poor CT visibility when used alone.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Describe the biodegradable polymers used in plastic surgery: chemistry, degradation mechanism, and clinical applications.", "answer": "Most are Î±-HYDROXY ACIDS: poly(lactic acid) (PLA), poly(glycolic acid) (PGA), and copolymer poly(lactic-co-glycolic acid) (PLGA). Degradation: HYDROLYSIS producing lactic or glycolic acid â€” common byproducts of normal human biochemical pathways. All breakdown products must be biocompatible. Key principle: increasing PLA concentration DECREASES degradation rate. Familiar example: Vicryl (polyglactin 910) = PGA/PLA copolymer suture. Applications: biodegradable meshes for abdominal wall reconstruction (Vicryl mesh for temporary abdominofascial closure in contaminated wounds â€” creates iatrogenic hernia for delayed repair), biodegradable plates/screws for craniofacial and hand applications. Examples: LactoSorb (82% PLA, 18% PGA), Resorb X (100% PDLLA). At implantation: strength equal to titanium plating; parameters tuned to preserve structural integrity for first 8 weeks for bony healing.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "What are the properties of ceramics as biomaterials? Compare hydroxyapatite and tricalcium phosphate.", "answer": "Ceramics: crystalline structure of inorganic, nonmetallic molecules with HETEROPOLAR bonding (electrons bound to individual atoms, unlike metals' homopolar bonding with free-flowing electrons). Manufactured by SINTERING (fusion under high pressure and temperature). Advantages: decreased foreign body response, resist bacterial colonization, high compressive strength, tissue ingrowth into porous materials (100 Âµm pore size for bone, 30 Âµm for soft tissue). Disadvantage: BRITTLE â€” fracture easily under tensile, torsional, or bending loads. Main use: non-load-bearing bone augmentation/replacement (face and cranium). CALCIUM PHOSPHATES â€” most common ceramics in plastic surgery. Hydroxyapatite (Ca10(PO4)6(OH)2): slower resorption, available as cement paste (can be molded intraoperatively for cranioplasty). Tricalcium phosphate (Ca3(PO4)2): FASTER resorption and replacement by bone. Both: granules for injection or solid/porous blocks; laboratory evidence of osteoinduction and osteoconduction (not yet demonstrated clinically).", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Compare the three tissue adhesives used in plastic surgery: fibrin sealant, platelet gels (PRP), and cyanoacrylate â€” mechanisms, preparation, and applications.", "answer": "FIBRIN SEALANT: two components â€” fibrinogen + thrombin (from pooled human plasma) combined with factor XIII, calcium, antifibrinolytic, and bovine aprotinin. Requires refrigeration, 20 min prep, warming. Adhesive strength proportional to FIBRINOGEN concentration; polymerization rate controlled by THROMBIN concentration (lower thrombin when tissues need manipulation). Mist applicators produce thinnest/strongest layer. Applications: skin graft adherence, seroma treatment. PLATELET GELS (PRP): from 70 mL whole blood, centrifuged; platelet layer combined with bovine thrombin. Less expensive but LOWER fibrinogen concentration = weaker adhesive/hemostatic properties. Applications: brow lift, facelift, abdominoplasty, DIEP/TRAM donor sites. CYANOACRYLATE: polymerizes on exposure to MOISTURE. Butyl-cyanoacrylate (first gen): short chain, rapid breakdown, wound dehiscence, toxic breakdown products (formaldehyde, cyanoacetate). Octyl-cyanoacrylate: longer side chains, stronger, longer-lasting. Application: skin closure only (deep layers must be tension-free).", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Wound healing biology", "subtopic": "Skin substitutes", "question": "Describe the composition and mechanism of Integra: layers, indications, and the two-stage application process.", "answer": "Integra: BILAYER skin substitute. Lower 'dermal' layer: BOVINE COLLAGEN base with glycosaminoglycan CHONDROITIN-6-SULFATE. Upper layer: SILICONE sheet acting as temporary epidermis. Mechanism: as wound heals, dermal layer is replaced with patient's own cells (neodermis); neodermis attaches to underlying bed and VASCULARIZES over 10-14 days. TWO-STAGE process: Stage 1 â€” apply Integra to wound. Stage 2 â€” after vascularization (10-14 days), remove silicone layer and apply thin split-thickness skin graft onto neodermis. Indications: partial- or full-thickness burns, complex wounds, multiple types of ulcers, wounds where skin graft is nonadherent to the wound bed. Compared to Biobrane: higher wound infection rate but better wound-healing time than autograft, allograft, or xenograft.", "notes": "Skin substitutes not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Wound healing biology"}, {"topic": "Wound healing biology", "subtopic": "Skin substitutes", "question": "Compare Epicel, Dermagraft, and Apligraf: cell source, composition, indications, and key features.", "answer": "EPICEL (cultured epidermal autograft): patient's OWN keratinocytes grown on proliferation-arrested 3T3 MURINE FIBROBLAST feeder cells until 2-8 cell layers thick; attached to petrolatum gauze with stainless steel clips (~50 cm2). Indication: deep dermal or full-thickness burns >=30% TBSA. DERMAGRAFT: POLYGLACTIN (Vicryl) mesh seeded with NEONATAL FIBROBLASTS that produce collagen, GAGs, fibronectin, growth factors; mesh resorbs and is replaced by patient's tissue. Indications: chronic wounds, burn excision sites with STSG. Equivalent to allograft for infection, healing time, graft take. APLIGRAF (bilayered skin-equivalent): lower 'dermal' layer = type I bovine collagen + neonatal foreskin FIBROBLASTS; upper 'epidermal' layer = neonatal KERATINOCYTES. Must be applied FRESH â€” shelf life only 5 DAYS at room temperature. Indications: venous ulcers, diabetic foot ulcers, temporary covering over meshed expanded autograft for burns.", "notes": "Skin substitutes not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Wound healing biology"}, {"topic": "Wound healing biology", "subtopic": "Skin substitutes", "question": "What are the characteristics of an ideal skin substitute?", "answer": "Five characteristics: (1) Adhere to the wound bed RAPIDLY, (2) Recapitulate the physiologic and mechanical properties of normal skin, (3) Be INEXPENSIVE, (4) Avoid immune rejection by the host, (5) Be highly effective in accelerating tissue regeneration and wound repair. Engineering of cultured skin substitutes requires three components: (1) a CELL source, (2) a 'tissue differentiation-inducing' SUBSTANCE, and (3) a MATRIX. A variety of cells, mediators, and polymers have been tested in various combinations. The ideal skin substitute does not yet exist.", "notes": "Skin substitutes not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Wound healing biology"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Compare human acellular dermal matrix (HADM/AlloDerm) and porcine acellular dermal matrix (PADM): processing, applications, and the key difference between cross-linked and non-cross-linked PADM.", "answer": "HADM (AlloDerm, Allomax, FlexHD): from donated allograft human dermis. Processing: epidermis and subcutaneous tissue removed, dermis processed with freeze-drying or chemical detergents to produce collagen structure of dermal matrix. Applications: implant-based breast reconstruction, abdominal wall, chest wall, pelvis reconstruction, lip augmentation. Micronized form (Cymetra) for laryngoplasty/soft tissue filler. PADM: more abundant, easier to harvest, but xenogeneic source requires additional processing. CROSS-LINKED PADM (CollaMend, Permacol): chemical cross-linking of collagen reduces immunogenicity and collagenase degradation, BUT alters ECM structure, inhibiting cellular infiltration, revascularization, and matrix remodeling â€” implant becomes ENCAPSULATED. NON-CROSS-LINKED PADM (Strattice): galactose-Î±(1,3)-galactose antigen (major cause of immune response) enzymatically removed; rapidly infiltrated with host cells and vessels, weaker adhesions, increased mechanical strength at early timepoints. Non-cross-linked may have early clinical advantages.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "What is small intestinal submucosa (SIS)? Describe its source, processing, and applications.", "answer": "SIS (Biodesign/Surgisis, Cook Biotech): biomaterial from PIG SMALL INTESTINE. Processing: mucosal, serosal, and muscular layers removed, leaving the strong collagenous SUBMUCOSAL matrix (the layer providing mechanical strength to the intestine). The submucosa is biochemically rich and diverse in extracellular matrix components. First described as a vascular graft in 1989. Applications in humans: multiple types of hernia repair, dural repair, bladder reconstruction, stress urinary incontinence treatment (>20 applications total). Originally released as Surgisis (1989), renamed Biodesign (2008) reflecting significant improvements. Key advantages: naturally derived, infection-resistant, strong yet biocompatible extracellular matrix scaffold that allows tissue remodeling.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Wound healing biology", "subtopic": "Skin substitutes", "question": "Describe the use of amniotic membrane as a biomaterial: structure, properties, and clinical applications.", "answer": "Amnion: used as a biomaterial for over 100 years (first published use as skin graft 1910, first use in burns 1912). Structure: MONOLAYER of epithelial cells, THICK BASEMENT MEMBRANE, and AVASCULAR matrix. The epithelium manufactures multiple cytokines and growth factors. Properties: promotes epithelialization, antimicrobial, immunomodulatory, and analgesic â€” many properties preserved even after de-epithelialization and sterilization. Products: dehydrated/decellularized amniotic membrane (BioFix, AmnioFix) for wound coverage; products with chorion included (BioFix Plus, EpiFix); injectable placental connective tissue matrix (BioFix Flow); cryopreserved placental membrane containing native cells including epithelial cells, fibroblasts, and stem cells (Grafix â€” must be thawed before use). Dehydrated products: room temperature storage, 5-year shelf-life, no preparation needed, can be placed either side up.", "notes": "Skin substitutes not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Wound healing biology"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "Describe the foreign body response to biomedical implants: cellular sequence, consequences, and why it is the fundamental limitation of implant longevity.", "answer": "The foreign body response is a chronic inflammatory reaction at the biomaterial-tissue interface. Cellular sequence: (1) NEUTROPHILS and MACROPHAGES recruited to interface, (2) inflammatory cells recruit collagen-producing FIBROBLASTS, (3) excessive fibroblast proliferation causes ENCAPSULATION of foreign body by collagen-rich matrix. Consequences: reduced biomaterial-tissue integration, loss of implant function, contracture, and pain. Examples: breast implants â€” capsule initially positions implant, but excessive fibrosis leads to capsular contracture; continuous glucose monitors â€” foreign body response develops in 30-90 days leading to impaired sensor functionality and unreliable readings. This is the FUNDAMENTAL LIMITATION in improving implant function and longevity. Nearly ALL known implanted materials elicit a host response in vivo. Current mitigation strategies: anti-inflammatory/antifibrotic drugs (local and systemic), chemical modification of biomaterial surfaces, study of mechanical signaling effects on fibrotic response.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "What are hybrid biosynthetic meshes? Name three commercially available products and their compositions.", "answer": "Hybrid biosynthetic meshes combine BIOLOGIC substrates with PERMANENT SYNTHETIC materials, aiming to provide: increased durability/support, mitigation of host response, and promotion of tissue ingrowth â€” addressing limitations of both purely synthetic and purely biologic meshes. Three commercially available products: (1) SYNECOR (Gore): polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE) fibers combined with bioabsorbable copolymer scaffold of polyglycolic acid (PGA) and trimethylene carbonate (TMC). (2) ZENAPRO (Cook): polypropylene mesh sandwiched between layers of porcine small intestinal submucosa (SIS). (3) OVITEX (TELA Bio): ovine rumen reinforced with interwoven polypropylene. Preclinical evidence: reinforced biologic scaffolds support cellular adhesion, display biomimetic properties, and maintain native architecture over prolonged period. These are used primarily in abdominal wall reconstruction.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Biomaterials and implants", "question": "What pore sizes are optimal for tissue ingrowth into porous biomaterials? How does this differ between bone and soft tissue?", "answer": "Optimal pore sizes for tissue ingrowth: BONE requires approximately 100 Âµm pore size; SOFT TISSUE requires approximately 30 Âµm pore size. These specifications guide ceramic implant design and other porous biomaterials. For example, porous polyethylene (Medpor) implants allow tissue and vascular ingrowth through their porosity â€” this provides stability but makes removal difficult. Conversely, ePTFE mesh modulates pore size to 10-30 Âµm to LIMIT tissue ingrowth (desired for visceral-facing surfaces to reduce adhesions in hernia repair). The relationship between pore size and ingrowth is a fundamental design parameter: too small prevents integration, too large compromises structural integrity.", "notes": "Biomaterials not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Define autologous, allogeneic, and xenogeneic transplantation. Give a clinical example of each in plastic surgery.", "answer": "AUTOLOGOUS: reconstruction using the patient's own tissue; no immune reaction. Example: DIEP flap breast reconstruction, skin grafts. ALLOGENEIC: transplantation between unrelated individuals of the SAME species; requires lifelong immunosuppression due to rejection risk. Example: face transplantation, hand transplantation, cadaver skin for burns. XENOGENEIC: from a DIFFERENT species; highest risk of acute rejection. Example: porcine heart valves, temporary coverage of burn wounds with pig skin. In plastic surgery terminology: 'flap' implies defined blood flow, 'graft' does not. In transplant terminology, 'graft/allograft' is used even for vascularized transplants (organs, VCA). Key historical milestone: Joseph E. Murray (plastic surgeon, Nobel Prize) performed first successful kidney transplant between identical twins in 1954.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "What is vascularized composite allotransplantation (VCA)? List the nine UNOS/OPTN definition criteria for a VCA.", "answer": "VCA: transplantation of whole anatomical units (hands/arms, face) composed of multiple tissue types (skin, muscle, tendons, bone, vessels, lymphatics, nerves). VCA is LIFE-ENHANCING (not life-saving), making risk-benefit analysis critical. Nine UNOS criteria: (1) Must be VASCULARIZED requiring surgical connection of blood vessels, (2) must contain MULTIPLE tissue types, (3) must be recovered from a human donor as an ANATOMICAL UNIT, (4) must be transplanted as an anatomical unit, (5) cannot be PROCESSED, (6) must be used for LIKE-WITH-LIKE replacement, (7) cannot be combined with a device, (8) is susceptible to ISCHEMIA and cannot be cryopreserved, (9) is susceptible to REJECTION requiring immunosuppression. To date: >90 upper extremity transplants and >44 face transplants performed worldwide. VCA came under UNOS/OPTN oversight in 2014; defined as human ORGANS (not tissue).", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Describe the role of MHC class I and class II antigens in transplant immunology. What other antigen system is critical?", "answer": "MHC (Major Histocompatibility Complex): glycoprotein family encoded on CHROMOSOME 6 (224 genes, 3.6 megabase pairs) determining recipient-donor compatibility. Function: epitope for antigen binding and presentation â€” immune cells bind, recognize, and stimulate immune response. MHC CLASS I: expressed on nearly ALL NUCLEATED CELLS and platelets; presents antigens to CD8+ cytotoxic T lymphocytes. MHC CLASS II: expressed only on ANTIGEN-PRESENTING CELLS (macrophages, B lymphocytes, dendritic cells); presents antigens to CD4+ T-helper lymphocytes. ABO SURFACE ANTIGENS: also critical; expressed on blood cells AND vascular endothelial cells. Patients develop antibodies against ABO antigens they don't express. ABO mismatch can cause RAPID graft rejection. Crossmatching: donor lymphocytes incubated with recipient serum to exclude preformed donor-specific antibodies (prevents hyperacute rejection).", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Describe the three types of antigen-presenting cells (APCs) and their roles in transplant rejection.", "answer": "APCs present foreign antigens complexed with MHC molecules to T lymphocytes, driving adaptive immunity. (1) MACROPHAGES: circulate in blood or reside stationary in tissues (e.g., LANGERHANS CELLS in skin). Phagocytize antigens, break them down, present fragments on surface. Activate T lymphocytes through antigen presentation and cytokine secretion. (2) DENDRITIC CELLS: reside in interstitial space; necessary for activation of NAIVE T cells (critical first step). When activated, migrate to lymph nodes where they activate T lymphocytes. (3) B LYMPHOCYTES: internalize foreign antigens and present them to T-helper lymphocytes. Upon activation, T-helpers stimulate B lymphocyte differentiation into PLASMA CELLS that produce immunoglobulins. Five immunoglobulin classes: IgG, IgM, IgE, IgA, IgD. Immunoglobulins act by opsonization (marking for phagocytosis) and stimulating the COMPLEMENT pathway (membrane attack complex).", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Describe T lymphocyte subtypes and their roles in transplant rejection.", "answer": "T lymphocytes originate from the THYMUS; each expresses a unique T cell receptor (TCR) for specific pattern recognition. Three subtypes: (1) T-HELPER (TH) LYMPHOCYTES: CD4+; assist other immune cells upon recognition of antigens presented by APCs. Secrete cytokines that regulate/boost immune response by activating other immune cells. (2) CYTOTOXIC T LYMPHOCYTES: CD8+; bind target antigens complexed with MHC CLASS I on nucleated cell surfaces. Kill target cells directly and attract macrophages. (3) REGULATORY T LYMPHOCYTES (Tregs): also CD4+; main role is SUPPRESSION of autoreactive T lymphocytes and regulation of immunological tolerance. In VCA rejection: skin contains TWICE as many effector T lymphocytes as peripheral blood. During active rejection in face transplants, the majority of lymphocytes in injured areas were DONOR-DERIVED CD8+ T lymphocytes (Boston group finding), meaning both recipient and donor immune cells contribute.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "What is 'split tolerance' in VCA? Why is skin the most immunogenic component?", "answer": "Split tolerance: phenomenon where rejection episodes affect SKIN but NOT other allograft components (muscle, bone). Rejection of muscle rarely occurs without skin rejection. This is because skin is as much a part of the IMMUNE SYSTEM as lymph nodes and the spleen â€” it functions as a lymphoid organ. Key evidence: normal skin contains TWICE as many effector T lymphocytes compared to peripheral blood (Clark et al.). Implications: (1) skin is primary site of rejection in VCA (often the only tissue to react), (2) for face transplants, mucosal rejection can occur BEFORE skin rejection and may be more severe, (3) 80-100% of VCA patients experience acute rejection within first year (vs only 10% of kidney transplants), (4) 50% experience MULTIPLE rejection episodes. Advantage: direct observation of transplanted skin allows early detection. Environmental stimuli (trauma, irritation, UV radiation) can trigger rejection through DAMPs (damage-associated molecular pattern molecules).", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Describe the triple immunosuppression maintenance protocol for VCA: drugs, mechanisms, and side effects.", "answer": "Standard maintenance: CORTICOSTEROIDS + MYCOPHENOLATE MOFETIL (MMF) + TACROLIMUS (calcineurin inhibitor). CORTICOSTEROIDS: bind intracellular receptors causing expressional changes reducing pro-inflammatory cytokines. Side effects: glucose intolerance, osteoporosis, hypertension, osteonecrosis. MMF: inhibits inosine monophosphate (IMP)-dehydrogenase required for purine synthesis during RNA/DNA metabolism. Most cells can circumvent this pathway EXCEPT lymphocytes â€” therefore selectively inhibits lymphocyte proliferation. Side effects: bone marrow suppression, GI irritation. Initiation: 1000 mg pre-surgery, then 1000 mg bi-daily. TACROLIMUS: blocks calcineurin/NFAT (nuclear factor of activated T-cell) signaling pathway, causing T-cell arrest and preventing cytokine transcription. Most relevant side effect: NEPHROTOXICITY through vasoconstriction of prerenal arterioles. Trough levels: 10-15 ng/mL. Can be replaced by BELATACEPT (T-cell co-stimulation blocker) in severe renal dysfunction. Topical tacrolimus can treat lower-grade rejections.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Describe induction and rescue immunosuppression protocols in VCA.", "answer": "INDUCTION: aims to prevent early allograft rejection during perioperative phase. Most common agent: antithymocyte globulin (ATG) â€” polyclonal antibodies against human lymphocyte antigens. Preparation: immunizing pathogen-free RABBITS with human thymocytes/lymphocytes. Mechanism: binds T-lymphocyte surface antigens causing complement activation and cell lysis; also modulates cell surface/adhesion molecules. Dose: thymoglobulin 1.5 mg/kg daily for first 4-5 days postop. Side effects: leukopenia, thrombocytopenia, cytokine release syndrome (serum sickness â€” fever, rash). Additional induction: 500 mg methylprednisolone before allograft reperfusion. RESCUE (for acute rejection despite maintenance therapy): (1) Increase maintenance immunosuppression to therapeutic levels, (2) corticosteroid BOLUS therapy. If corticosteroid-resistant (7.5-19% of episodes): ATG or ALEMTUZUMAB. Can be supplemented with immunosuppressive topical ointments and mouth rinses.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Describe the Banff 2007 classification for acute VCA rejection: grades, criteria, and limitations.", "answer": "Banff 2007: standardized histopathological grading system for VCA rejection evaluating perivascular/epidermal infiltration and epidermal injury. GRADES: Grade 1 â€” Mild perivascular and dermal infiltration WITHOUT epidermal affection. Grade 2 â€” Moderate perivascular inflammation WITH or WITHOUT epidermal involvement. Grade 3 â€” Severe inflammation and epidermal affection with epithelial apoptosis, dyskeratosis, and keratinolysis. Grade 4 â€” Epidermal NECROSIS. LIMITATIONS: (1) Susceptible to inter- and intra-rater differences based on pathologist expertise. (2) Vascular inflammation/allograft vasculopathy NOT included. (3) Originally developed for HAND transplant patients; facial skin contains larger neutrophilic lymphocytic infiltrates that resemble Grade 1, so many centers don't treat Grade 1 in face transplants. (4) Used for mucosal rejection though it's fundamentally different tissue. (5) Regular biopsies cause additional scarring. Sentinel flaps (donor-originated free flaps) showed good correlation (r=0.88) but lost monitoring potential over time.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Differentiate hyperacute, acute, and chronic rejection in VCA: timing, mechanism, and treatment.", "answer": "HYPERACUTE: occurs IMMEDIATELY after allograft reperfusion. Mechanism: preformed antibodies against donor or ABO antigens cause complement activation, endothelial cell injury, arterial/venous thrombosis. Prevention: immunologic screening for preformed antibodies and crossmatching. ACUTE: most common complication; ~80% of VCA patients within first year. Skin is primary site (often only tissue affected); mucosa may reject before skin in face transplants. Presentation: fever, maculopapular rash, edema, induration, loss of function. Histology: lymphatic infiltration (Banff classification) with vascular destruction. Predisposing factor: allograft ischemia time. Treatment: corticosteroid bolus; ATG for severe/steroid-resistant cases. CHRONIC: not fully defined; involves primarily skin and vascular system. Mechanism: likely antigen-mediated intimal damage. Presentation: cutaneous plaques, rashes, sclerosis, fibrosis, necrotic ulcers, premature aging. NO sufficient treatment available â€” prevention of acute rejection episodes is crucial (acute rejection likely contributes to chronic rejection development).", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "What are the major complications of lifelong immunosuppression after VCA?", "answer": "Three categories: (1) INFECTIONS: most common complication. Viral: CMV infection (risk factors: donor-recipient serology mismatch, degree of immunosuppression, ATG use; range from flu-like to severe organ disease), EBV causing post-transplant lymphoproliferative disorder (uncontrolled B-cell proliferation â†’ aggressive lymphoma). Bacterial: early postop, affecting wound/bloodstream/respiratory/urinary tract; characterized by HIGH MULTIDRUG RESISTANCE. Fungal: Candida spp. or Aspergillus spp. (invasive candidiasis/aspergillosis). (2) MALIGNANCIES: up to 5-FOLD increased incidence; in SOT, ~50% develop neoplasia within 25 years (cancer is a leading cause of death). Most frequent: BCC and SCC of skin â€” requires regular dermatologic follow-up. (3) RENAL DYSFUNCTION: most common DRUG-related complication. Calcineurin inhibitors (tacrolimus) cause afferent arteriolar constriction and chronic structural changes (fibrosis, glomerulosclerosis). Management: reduce calcineurin inhibitor levels or switch to belatacept.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Describe the surgical sequence for upper extremity transplantation. How does it compare to replantation?", "answer": "Sequence: BONE osteosynthesis â†’ EARLY REVASCULARIZATION (reduce ischemia time; one artery + â‰¥2 veins end-to-end) â†’ MUSCLE/TENDON repair â†’ DEFINITIVE REVASCULARIZATION (remaining artery + additional veins; â‰¥4 veins total from superficial and deep systems) â†’ NERVE repair (ulnar, radial, median + branches; epineural if fascicular repair impossible) â†’ PROPHYLACTIC CARPAL TUNNEL RELEASE â†’ skin/soft tissue closure. Key differences from replantation: VCA allows thorough preoperative planning; replantation is emergency. In replantation, bone shortening is needed for tension-free repair. In VCA, excess length of arteries/veins/nerves/tendons can be harvested. Critical ischemia time: 4-6 hours for muscle (travel time limit: 2 hours). Skin incisions: four-flap design preserving subcutaneous veins and perforators. Better outcomes with distal amputation levels (shorter nerve distance to intrinsic muscles, functioning forearm flexors/extensors allowing immediate tenorrhaphy).", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Compare trunk versus branch-level facial nerve coaptation in face transplantation: advantages, disadvantages, and timeline for motor recovery.", "answer": "TRUNK-LEVEL coaptation: includes parotid gland in allograft (adds bulk to cheek area or requires superficial parotidectomy); limits access to individual facial nerve branches. Motor reinnervation begins within 5-6 months (longer distance to neuromuscular end plates). Higher risk of SYNKINESIA. BRANCH-LEVEL coaptation (medial to parotid): allows EXCLUSION of parotid gland (better cheek contour). Advantages: (1) reduces synkinesia, (2) allows better TARGETED reinnervation, (3) earlier motor reinnervation within 3-4 months (shorter distance to effector muscles). Mean restoration of facial motor function: ~60% within 2 years. SENSORY recovery: can occur as early as 3 months; usually 3-8 months. Includes near-total recovery of heat/cold discrimination and light-touch sensibility. Important: sensory recovery occurred during first year REGARDLESS of whether surgical sensory nerve coaptation was performed (trigeminal nerve branches). Recovery achieved through end-to-end coaptation; nerve grafts avoided as much as possible.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "What functional outcomes are achieved after face transplantation?", "answer": "MOTOR recovery: begins 6-8 months post-transplant; ~60% restoration of facial motor function within 2 years. Smile restored (zygomaticus major) in all patients. SENSORY recovery: begins as early as 3 months; usually 3-8 months. Near-total recovery of heat/cold discrimination and light-touch. Occurs only during first year; independent of surgical nerve coaptation. BREATHING: nose breathing restored; patients with tracheostomy decannulated. SMELL: restored to pre-trauma levels by restoring nasal passage. EATING: significant mastication improvement within first year; previously necessary gastrostomies removed. SPEECH: intelligibility restored (80-97% at word/sentence level) within first year through restoration of labial function. SOCIAL REINTEGRATION: significant improvement in quality of life. Assessment methods: EMG (detects early re-myelinization but doesn't correlate with clinical improvement), facial expression recognition software (evaluates smile, frown, purse lips, open mouth, lift eyebrows, close eyes, wrinkle nose compared to healthy controls).", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "Describe the VCA patient and donor selection process. What are the key matching criteria?", "answer": "PATIENT SELECTION (3-12 months): (1) Team leader assesses surgical indication and potential for form/function restoration. (2) Medical evaluation. (3) Psychiatric evaluation by TWO psychiatrists: one identifies disqualifying conditions, another serves as patient advocate assessing understanding, expectations, and compliance ability. Exclusions: active psychiatric issues, substance abuse. (4) Social work assessment: stable support network, financial resources. (5) Immunologic profiling: blood type, HLA, panel reactive antibody (%PRA) â€” high %PRA = low chance of negative crossmatch. (6) Infectious disease screening (hepatitis A/B/C, CMV, VZV, TB, syphilis, EBV, HIV). Team decision: consensus attempted; >50% in favor â†’ waitlist. Re-evaluation every 6 months. DONOR SELECTION: brain-dead donors (all US VCA to date). Matching: ABO compatibility, sex, age, skin color. Additional: limb size, tattoos, scars. Crossmatching performed to exclude preformed donor-specific antibodies. Next-of-kin: separate authorization required for VCA donation (per UNOS).", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "What are the critical ischemia time considerations in VCA? How is allograft preservation managed?", "answer": "Maximal tolerable ischemia time for MUSCLE tissue without irreversible damage: 4-6 HOURS (muscle is the most ischemia-sensitive component). Travel time limit: maximum 2 hours recommended. VCA procurement MUST be performed PRIOR to solid organ procurement (recovery frequently exceeds 6 hours). However, life-saving organ procurement takes PRIORITY if cardiopulmonary instability occurs. Allograft preservation: perfused with UNIVERSITY OF WISCONSIN SOLUTION, sterilely packed, stored on ICE SLURRY during transport. To reduce ischemia time: vascular anastomoses performed FIRST during allograft inset. Intraoperative perfusion assessment: INDOCYANINE GREEN (ICG) angiography. Future: extracorporeal (ex vivo) perfusion of allografts may extend tolerable ischemia time (already used in SOT), could reduce ischemia-reperfusion injury using antioxidant solutions. Post-procurement donor dignity: facial restorative mask placed by anaplastologist; limb prostheses of adequate skin tone provided.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Reconstructive principles", "subtopic": "Transplantation and immunology", "question": "What are the emerging VCA indications beyond face and upper extremity transplantation?", "answer": "UTERUS TRANSPLANTATION: first performed 2000; first successful live birth reported by BrÃ¤nnstrÃ¶m in 2014. Enables women with absolute uterine factor infertility or hysterectomy to undergo normal pregnancy (especially relevant where surrogacy is illegal). Major advantage: lifelong immunosuppression NOT needed because uterus can be REMOVED after pregnancy. PENILE TRANSPLANTATION: first performed in China 2005 (removed after 2 weeks due to recipient's wife's psychological concerns); subsequently performed in US and South Africa with promising functional results (erectile function, ejaculation, urination). VCA is still considered EXPERIMENTAL; biggest challenge is transition to standard of care. Current funding: governmental/institutional grants (not scalable). Acceptance by third-party payers (insurance) needed, which requires universally accepted treatment protocols and uniform outcome measures.", "notes": "Transplantation not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Reconstructive principles"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic principles", "subtopic": "Noninvasive body contouring", "question": "Compare the five noninvasive body contouring technologies: cryolipolysis, HIFEM, radiofrequency, ultrasound, and LLLT â€” in terms of mechanism and target tissue effect.", "answer": "CRYOLIPOLYSIS: cooling below physiologic but above freezing temperatures causes adipocyte APOPTOSIS (fat cells more susceptible to cold than skin/nerves/vessels). Inflammatory response removes injured cells (peaks day 14). No skin change. HIFEM (high-intensity focused electromagnetic field): supraphysiologic muscle contractions (20,000 pulses/30 min) cause MUSCULAR HYPERTROPHY; may decrease fat via lipolysis from free-fatty acid release. Only technology targeting muscle. RADIOFREQUENCY: energy waves cause tissue molecules to move/collide/change orientation producing HEAT. Variable impedance means different tissues affected differently. Adipocyte apoptosis + deep dermal collagen contraction/remodeling for skin tightening. ULTRASOUND: HFFU (high-frequency) uses heat for COAGULATIVE NECROSIS of adipocytes and collagen; LFFU (low-frequency) causes MECHANICAL DISRUPTION of adipocytes with less heat/discomfort. LLLT (low-level laser therapy): 635-680 nm wavelength; PHOTOCHEMICAL (not thermal); creates microscopic PORES in adipocyte membranes allowing lipid leakage without cell death; 80% of contents released at 4 min, 99% at 6 min.", "notes": "Noninvasive body contouring not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Aesthetic principles"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic principles", "subtopic": "Noninvasive body contouring", "question": "What is paradoxical adipose hyperplasia (PAH)? What technology causes it and how is it treated?", "answer": "PAH: a complication of CRYOLIPOLYSIS where treated areas paradoxically INCREASE in fat volume rather than decrease. Only 16 cases reported in published literature (systematic review). Hypothesized mechanism: some adipocytes may be 'naturally selected' to survive cold exposure and subsequently proliferate. Although rare, it is an important risk to communicate to patients. Treatment: the ONLY treatment is surgical lipectomy â€” either direct excision or liposuction. This phenomenon has generated significant concern in the lay press.", "notes": "Noninvasive body contouring not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Aesthetic principles"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic principles", "subtopic": "Noninvasive body contouring", "question": "Describe the HIFEM (EMSCULPT) protocol: dosing, frequency, maintenance, and what unique finding has been reported regarding rectus diastasis.", "answer": "Protocol: 20,000 electromagnetic pulses during a 30-minute session, delivered supraphysiologically. Schedule: twice per week for 2 weeks (4 total sessions). Maintenance: one treatment every 3-6 months. Results: average waist circumference reduction of 3.29 cm after 4th treatment; increased abdominal muscle thickness of 1.6 mm in 21/22 patients. RECTUS DIASTASIS: significant narrowing in 20/22 subjects (1.8 mm narrower by MRI, P <0.001). This is the only noninvasive technology that can improve muscle tone and has NO surgical equivalent for muscle toning. FDA approved 2018 for abdomen and buttocks. Contraindications: pregnancy, metal implants, pacemakers, defibrillators, spinal cord stimulators. Side effects: transient muscle soreness. Better results in patients with LOWER BMI. Limitation: most early studies were industry-funded.", "notes": "Noninvasive body contouring not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Aesthetic principles"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic principles", "subtopic": "Noninvasive body contouring", "question": "Compare high-frequency focused ultrasound (HFFU) and low-frequency focused ultrasound (LFFU) for body contouring: mechanism, tissue depth, pain, and efficacy.", "answer": "HFFU (e.g., Ultherapy): uses external transducer to transmit ultrasound energy generating HEAT causing COAGULATIVE NECROSIS of adipocytes and collagen. Can target specific tissue planes up to 8 mm depth: dermis (1.5 mm), deep dermis (3.0 mm), or SMAS/subdermal tissues (4.5 mm) by altering transducers. Painful (mean pain score 3.9/10 despite topical anesthesia); causes erythema and edema. Two-pass protocol targeting SMAS and superficial fascia showed improvement in facial/neck laxity in 8/10 patients. LFFU (e.g., UltraShape): uses sound for MECHANICAL DISRUPTION of adipocytes; produces LESS heat and LESS discomfort. Mean abdominal circumference decrease of 1.65 cm after 3 treatments. No adverse effects reported. Summary: HFFU has more discomfort and transient risks but more potential aesthetic benefit compared to LFFU.", "notes": "Noninvasive body contouring not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Aesthetic principles"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic principles", "subtopic": "Noninvasive body contouring", "question": "Describe radiofrequency energy devices (RFED) for aesthetic body contouring: mechanism of action, tissue effects, and clinical results.", "answer": "Mechanism: RF energy causes tissue molecules to move, collide, or change orientation, producing and releasing HEAT. Key concept: VARIABLE IMPEDANCE â€” RF affects specific tissues differently. Two tissue effects: (1) Preferential adipocyte injury â†’ apoptosis â†’ subcutaneous volume reduction. (2) Heating deep dermis and collagen-based FIBROUS SEPTAE â†’ contraction, remodeling â†’ improved skin tightness/tone. Results: facial application showed clinical improvement in nasolabial/mesolabial folds in 28/30 patients; no improvement in patients >62 years. Abdominal use: average circumference decrease of 4.93 cm after 4 sessions, maintained at 4 years (4.42 cm reduction). Side effects: erythema (common), soreness requiring NSAIDs, dysesthesia (rare). No burns or long-term complications. Limitation: offers only MILD benefits; best suited for individuals with MILD cutaneous and subcutaneous excess. Multiple FDA-approved devices: ThermaCool, truSculpt, Venus Legacy, Vanquish, Velashape.", "notes": "Noninvasive body contouring not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Aesthetic principles"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic principles", "subtopic": "Noninvasive body contouring", "question": "How does LLLT differ from all other noninvasive body contouring modalities in terms of mechanism? What are its limitations?", "answer": "Key difference: LLLT acts through a PHOTOCHEMICAL pathway, not a THERMAL mechanism (unlike cryolipolysis, RF, and ultrasound). Uses 635-680 nm wavelength laser. Creates MICROSCOPIC PORES in adipocyte cell membranes allowing lipids to leak into interstitial space â€” no demonstrable temperature change, no macroscopic cell changes, no cell death/apoptosis. Efficacy: cumulative circumference reduction of 3.51 inches (waist/hips/thighs) in RCT; 70% satisfaction. LIMITATIONS: (1) Unlike liposuction or other devices that DESTROY adipocytes, LLLT does not kill cells â€” unclear how adipocytes react or rebound over time. (2) Effect of releasing triglycerides and adipocyte contents into interstitial space is unknown (unclear if reabsorbed into bloodstream). (3) Requires multiple sessions (6-8 treatments). Contraindications: pregnancy, scar or tattoo at treatment site. Safety: well tolerated with no documented adverse effects (photochemical, not thermal).", "notes": "Noninvasive body contouring not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Aesthetic principles"}, {"topic": "Aesthetic principles", "subtopic": "Noninvasive body contouring", "question": "When should patients be counseled toward surgery versus noninvasive body contouring? What patient factor most limits noninvasive results?", "answer": "Surgery (liposuction/excisional procedures) remains GOLD STANDARD for loose skin and excess subcutaneous fat â€” results are more limited with noninvasive technologies. Direct to SURGERY when: significant skin laxity or adipose excess is present. Noninvasive options appropriate for: patients with early aging changes, mild skin/subcutaneous excess, those not ready for surgery, or who desire modest changes. HIFEM is unique as an adjunct even to surgery (no surgical equivalent for muscle toning). Key limiting factor: BMI â€” the lipolytic response is INVERSELY PROPORTIONAL to BMI; higher BMI patients have less appreciable/quantifiable results from noninvasive treatments. Additional patient education: multiple treatments are required; despite avoiding surgery costs, accumulated treatment costs may eliminate financial advantage; results are more modest than surgery. The minimally invasive procedural volume in the US has increased by nearly 300% over two decades vs 22% for cosmetic surgery.", "notes": "Noninvasive body contouring not a standalone subtopic in topic list; closest match under Aesthetic principles"}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Preoperative assessment and WPATH criteria", "question": "Describe the WPATH SOC8 criteria for gender-affirming surgery. How do requirements differ between facial surgery, mastectomy, gonadectomy, and genital surgery?", "answer": "SOC8 criteria COMMON TO ALL: (1) Letter from healthcare professional with competencies in TGD assessment â€” 1 letter required for ALL procedures (changed from SOC7 which required 2 letters for genital surgery). (2) Marked and sustained gender incongruence. (3) Capacity to consent. (4) Meets diagnostic criteria for gender incongruence where required. (5) Other causes of gender incongruence excluded. (6) Mental/physical conditions controlled. (7) Stable on gender-affirming hormones for at least 6 months (unless not desired or contraindicated). ADDITIONAL requirements by procedure: GONADECTOMY and GENITAL SURGERY: fertility counseling required. SOC7 vs SOC8 differences: SOC7 required 0 letters for facial surgery, 1 for breast augmentation/mastectomy, 2 for genital surgery. SOC7 also required 12 months continuous social transition for genital reconstruction.", "notes": "Gender-affirming surgery has its own topic in the topic list"}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Hormone therapy considerations", "question": "List the common hormone therapies used in gender-affirming care and their main side effects. What are the perioperative hormone management considerations?", "answer": "ESTROGEN: main side effect is deep venous thrombosis (transdermal administration may lessen this risk). PROGESTERONE: increased cardiac and cancer risks. ANTI-ANDROGENS (e.g., spironolactone): potential effects on electrolytes. TESTOSTERONE: polycythemia and lipid alterations. Perioperative management: ESTROGEN â€” controversy exists. Some surgeons stop 2-4 weeks preoperatively, others reduce dose, others continue. Data suggesting continuation is safe are not robust enough for standardized protocols. TESTOSTERONE â€” generally accepted to continue perioperatively. For breast augmentation: patients should be on well-controlled exogenous estrogen for at least 12 months to allow maximal breast development before surgery. For facial feminization: estrogen effects on midface should be given 1-2 years before considering malar augmentation, as estrogen alone can feminize this region.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Chest masculinization (mastectomy)", "question": "Describe the Fischer grading scale for gender-affirming mastectomy. How does each grade guide the surgical approach?", "answer": "Fischer grading evaluates three components: skin laxity, degree of ptosis, and glandular tissue volume. GRADE 1: no laxity, NAC above IMF, minimal tissue. Approach: periareolar (small NAC) or circumareolar (moderate/large NAC). GRADE 2A: little to no laxity, NAC above IMF, moderate tissue. Approach: circumareolar, inferior pedicle, or double incision with free nipple graft (DIFNG). GRADE 2B: increased laxity, NAC at or below IMF, moderate tissue. Approach: inferior pedicle or DIFNG. GRADE 3: irrespective of laxity, NAC below IMF, significant tissue. Approach: DIFNG. GRADE 4: significant laxity, NAC below IMF, deflated breast. Approach: DIFNG. DIFNG is the most commonly performed procedure â€” most patients present with significant excess of both volume and skin (many develop ptosis/laxity from prolonged breast binding). DIFNG has consistently lower revision rates than other approaches.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Chest masculinization (mastectomy)", "question": "Describe the double incision with free nipple graft (DIFNG) technique: markings, NAC positioning, and common complications.", "answer": "Markings: gently curved incision mirroring the pectoralis major border; can extend laterally for axillary adiposity contouring. NAC position: lateral two-thirds of the clavicle, one fingerbreadth above planned incision along pectoralis border (~2 Ã— 3 cm oval FNG). Technique: FNG harvested full thickness and thinned; superior chest flap elevated just above breast capsule (can be thicker to approximate upper abdominal subcutaneous thickness); breast removed above pectoralis fascia; IMF released; closure in layers over drain; NAC site de-epithelialized and FNG secured with bolster. COMPLICATIONS: hematoma (5-12%, up to 5-10% requiring acute reoperation); seroma (2-5%); nipple necrosis (2-5%); NAC pigmentation changes; revision rates 10-40% (DIFNG lowest). Common revisions: scar revision, dog-ear excision, liposuction. KEY: this is NOT an oncologic resection â€” specimens must be screened by pathologist for occult cancer. Post-mastectomy: self-exam plus yearly clinical breast exam recommended.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Breast augmentation in transfeminine patients", "question": "What anatomical differences must be considered in transfeminine breast augmentation compared to cisgender augmentation?", "answer": "Key anatomical differences: (1) LIMITED SKIN EXPANSION from testosterone exposure. (2) Proportionally SHORTER nipple-to-IMF distance. (3) WIDER STERNUM with wider breast base width â€” often requires wider implants leading to larger volumes (BW <13: 300-500cc; BW 13-17: 400-600cc; BW >17: 500-700cc). (4) LATERALIZED NAC position â€” medial placement offers better cleavage but displaces NAC relative to implant. (5) More developed PECTORALIS MUSCLE â€” can cause animation deformity with subpectoral approach; 'pec test' assesses for marked pectoral hypertrophy. Pocket selection: subglandular if pinch test >1.5 cm, good estrogen skin softening, and excess sternal bone width; otherwise dual-plane subpectoral (90% of cases). IMF lowering: N-IMF should equal half of implant base width. Scarpa's fascia should be secured to chest wall when IMF is lowered to prevent malposition. Medium profile implant standard unless anatomy mandates otherwise. Previous silicone injections can impact candidacy.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Phalloplasty", "question": "Compare the four phalloplasty donor sites: radial forearm, anterolateral thigh (ALT), SCIP/lower abdomen, and modified latissimus dorsi.", "answer": "RADIAL FOREARM: best vascularity (++++), BEST sensation (+++++), BEST pliability (+++++), moderate donor site morbidity (++), moderate hairlessness (++). Elevated with cephalic vein, radial artery, vena comitans; includes branches of lateral/medial/posterior antebrachial cutaneous nerves. Donor site: STSG or biologic matrix coverage; requires hand therapy. ANTEROLATERAL THIGH (ALT): good vascularity (++++), good sensation (++++), moderate pliability (+++), higher morbidity (+++), good hairlessness (+++). Includes LFCN; preoperative CT for perforator mapping; pinch test <1 cm for TWT suitability. SCIP/LOWER ABDOMEN: moderate vascularity (+++), limited sensation (++), moderate pliability (+++), BEST donor site morbidity (+++++), best hairlessness (++++). Can be closed primarily. MODIFIED LATISSIMUS DORSI: best vascularity (+++++), poorest sensation (+), limited pliability (++), best morbidity (+++++), good hairlessness (+++). Most common flaps: radial forearm and ALT. Most common design: tube-within-tube (TWT).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Phalloplasty", "question": "Differentiate simple metoidioplasty, complete metoidioplasty, and phalloplasty: what each achieves and key counseling points.", "answer": "SIMPLE METOIDIOPLASTY: shaft lengthening + shaft skin creation WITHOUT urethral extension. Can be with or without vaginectomy/scrotoplasty. Creates small sensate phallus using local tissue based on embryologic origin (labia majora â†’ scrotum, labia minora â†’ shaft skin). Requires preoperative clitoral length â‰¥3 cm. Suspensory ligament and urethral plate released; ventral raw surface covered with buccal mucosal graft. Standing micturition sometimes possible; penetrative intercourse usually NOT possible. COMPLETE METOIDIOPLASTY: adds urethral lengthening + vaginectomy + scrotoplasty. Vaginectomy strongly encouraged if full-length urethra created (adds vascularized tissue layers over reconstruction). PHALLOPLASTY: creates adult-sized phallus capable of standing micturition and penetrative intercourse (with erectile implant). CRITICAL counseling: patients should NOT undergo standard metoidioplasty if they ultimately desire phalloplasty â€” the urethral diameter and potential complications can make conversion technically challenging.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Phalloplasty", "question": "Compare single-stage phalloplasty, the Big Ben method, and metoidioplasty-first staging: components, advantages, and disadvantages.", "answer": "SINGLE-STAGE: shaft + shaft urethra + perineal urethra + vaginectomy + scrotoplasty in ONE surgery (glansplasty optional; implants always later). Advantage: fewer surgeries, less recovery/cost, higher patient volume. Disadvantage: flap complications can simultaneously impact urethral reconstruction. BIG BEN METHOD (St. Peter Andrology Institute, London): Stage 1 â€” shaft + shaft urethra + unilateral labia minora resection. Stage 2 â€” glansplasty + perineal urethra + scrotoplasty + vaginectomy. Advantages: separates flap-related from urologic complications; perineal urethra is SHORTER; urethral anastomosis closed as inverted Y (non-circumferential), potentially reducing stricture risk. METOIDIOPLASTY-FIRST: Stage 1 â€” metoidioplasty with urethral lengthening. Stage 2 â€” phalloplasty with clitoral burying. Advantage: urethra connected to clitoral glans (better erogenous stimulation); helpful for undecided patients. All approaches: erectile implants always placed at LATER stage. Overall complication rate ~50% regardless of method.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Vaginoplasty", "question": "Describe the penile inversion vaginoplasty (PIV) technique: key surgical steps, neoclitoral creation, and canal depth.", "answer": "Lithotomy position; hip/knee flexion <90Â° (prevent neuropraxia/compartment syndrome). Key steps: (1) Posterior perineal flap raised (pedicled posteriorly), 2 fingerbreadths above anus. (2) Scrotal skin graft harvested (12-15 cm Ã— ~5 cm), thinned, tubularized. (3) Bilateral orchiectomies. (4) Penis degloved above Buck's fascia preserving dorsal neurovascular bundle. (5) Canal dissection above rectum/below urethra/prostate in Denonvillier's fascia plane to peritoneal reflection (~15 cm depth). (6) Rectal integrity tested (dilute povidone-iodine enema). (7) NEOCLITORIS: W-shaped design (2 cm wide) at proximal dorsal corona, raised with deep erectile tissue, pedicle dissected in subtunical plane, coned and inset at adductor longus tendon line. (8) Urethra separated from corpora spongiosum, split ventrally, spatulated open for vulvar cleft. (9) Penile skin + scrotal graft sewn (non-circular suture line to prevent contracture), inverted into canal. (10) Labia majora contoured and closed.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Vaginoplasty", "question": "What are the common complications after penile inversion vaginoplasty? What is the most important postoperative requirement?", "answer": "COMPLICATIONS: Hematoma (up to 10%, some requiring operative drainage). Urinary retention requiring catheter replacement. Rectovaginal fistula (RVF): most serious surgical complication (1-3%); managed with colorectal surgery, usually requires temporary diverting ostomy. Surgical site complications: up to 70% â€” wound dehiscence (labia majora/introitus), hypergranulation tissue in vaginal canal, partial or complete neovaginal STENOSIS. For intestinal vaginoplasty: mucorrhea, diversion colitis, bowel anastomotic leaks. MOST IMPORTANT postoperative requirement: VAGINAL DILATATION â€” typically 20 minutes twice daily; must be CONSISTENT or stenosis will invariably occur. Postop protocol: Foley catheter and vaginal packing/stenting for 5-6 days; antibiotics while bolster in place; speculum exam confirming neovaginal integrity before starting dilations and vaginal rinses. CONTRAINDICATIONS to vaginal vault creation: previous prostatectomy, prostatic radiation, IBD (higher RVF risk).", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Facial feminization surgery", "question": "Describe the testosterone-driven skeletal changes in the upper face and the surgical techniques for forehead feminization.", "answer": "Testosterone effects on upper face: (1) Increased muscle strength â†’ facial skull grows more angular. (2) FRONTAL BOSSING from enlarged frontal sinuses with decreased nasofrontal angle. (3) Lower-set eyebrows with less lateral arching and more acute angulation between eyelid crease and brows. (4) Increased AP dimension of supraorbital rim (more shadows, decreased perceived eyelid-brow distance). (5) Thickened skull cortices. (6) More acute forehead slope. (7) Masculine hair pattern (testosterone â†’ DHT conversion). FOREHEAD FEMINIZATION via hairline or bicoronal incision: (1) Frontal bone contoured for more convex shape; often requires ANTERIOR TABLE OSTEOTOMY (setback) to reduce AP dimension, with subsequent osteosynthesis. (2) Orbital aperture opened with burring/lateral orbital osteotomy for more oval shape with sharpened supraorbital edges. (3) Brow elevation with bony fixation and soft-tissue draping. (4) Hairline advancement (if pretrichial incision); galeal scoring incisions posteriorly. (5) Simultaneous hair transplantation possible. Complication: bone resorption of anterior table, mucoceles.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Facial feminization surgery", "question": "What are the key surgical considerations for feminization of the middle and lower thirds of the face?", "answer": "MIDDLE THIRD: Rhinoplasty â€” reductive approach especially at nasal dorsum; infracturing osteotomies (prevent open roof); decrease length/projection, increase tip rotation; cephalic trim of lower lateral cartilages; crural strut grafts for inferior rotation. Upper lip lift: resect 4-6 mm subnasal skin (decreases upper lip length, adds volume via vermilion eversion; avoid if gummy smile). Malar augmentation: fillers, fat grafting, or implants (allow 1-2 years of estrogen effect first); zygomatic osteotomies for width reduction. LOWER THIRD: Masculine features include increased vertical height, wider bigonial width with flare/hypertrophy, square menton. Jaw contouring: intraoral triple incision with mental nerve protection; chin reduction (vertical and/or horizontal); sliding genioplasty; gonial angle width reduction (avoid over-resection). Critical: inferior alveolar nerve limits body resection. Soft-tissue resuspension essential (internal sutures + compressive garment). LARYNX: laryngochondroplasty â€” resection limited inferiorly by vocal cord insertions (located by CT or intraoperative needle). Patients must be warned of iatrogenic jowling requiring secondary skin tightening.", "notes": ""}, {"topic": "Gender-affirming surgery", "subtopic": "Phalloplasty", "question": "What are the urethral creation options in phalloplasty, and why is vaginectomy strongly recommended with urethral lengthening?", "answer": "Two parts of urethra needed: PERINEAL URETHRA (pars fixa) and SHAFT URETHRA (pars pendulans). Shaft urethra options: (1) TUBE-WITHIN-TUBE (TWT): urethra created as part of primary flap (2-4 cm longer than shaft), most common design. (2) COMPOSITE PHALLOPLASTY: separate flap for urethra. (3) PRELAMINATION: graft placed within donor site before phallic creation (largely abandoned due to high complication rates). (4) SPLIT SHAFT AND GRAFT: phallus split vertically, graft secured, then tubularized at third surgery. Graft materials: uterine, vaginal, or buccal mucosa, or skin. Perineal urethra: created from vulvar tissue (urethral plate, medial labia minora, anterior vaginal flap, natal urethral meatus). VAGINECTOMY STRONGLY RECOMMENDED because: (1) adds multiple VASCULARIZED TISSUE LAYERS over urethral reconstruction, (2) vaginal canal abuts native urethra â€” retaining it risks long-segment urethral strictures. Vaginal preservation is considered a CONTRAINDICATION to urethral lengthening by most surgeons. Hair removal on urethral segments is ESSENTIAL before surgery.", "notes": ""}];